ile-in-honeydew-single/1263179577|title=A-Reece - Meanwhile in Honeydew|website=iTunes}}</ref>\n| \u2014\n| \u00d72Platinum \n|-\n| \"Don't Bother\"<ref>{{Citation|url=https://itunes.apple.com/za/album/dont-bother-single/1263161436|title=A-Reece - Don't Bother|website=iTunes}}</ref>\n| \u2014\n|\n|-\n| \"Sloppy\"<ref>{{Citation|url=https://itunes.apple.com/za/album/sloppy-single/1329611204|title=A-Reece - Sloppy|website=iTunes}}</ref>\n| \u2014\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"7\" | 2018\n| \"Sweet Revenge\"<br /><small>(with Zoocci Coke Dope and Flame)</small>\n| \u2014\n|Gold \n|-\n| \"Better Luck Next Time\"<br /><small>(featuring Ecco and Wordz)</small><ref>{{Citation|url=https://open.spotify.com/album/3Mq8acERy1R1bwUb0h3IpZ|title=A-Reece - Better Luck Next Time|website=Spotify}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|url=https://soundcloud.com/user-256318544/a-reece-ecco-wordz-better-luck-next-time|title=A-Reece - Better Luck Next Time|website=SoundCloud}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|url=https://itunes.apple.com/za/album/better-luck-next-time-feat-ecco-wordz-single/1387197361|title=A-Reece - Better Luck Next Time|website=iTunes}}</ref>\n| \u2014\n|\n|-\n| \"Gone Are the Days\"<ref>{{Citation|url=https://open.spotify.com/album/5xvH89tYnyWQ1kdVZrx29x|title=A-Reece - Gone are the days|website=Spotify}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|url=https://soundcloud.com/user-256318544/gone-are-the-days|title=A-Reece - Gone are the days|website=SoundCloud}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|url=https://itunes.apple.com/za/album/gone-are-the-days-single/1393505449|title=A-Reece - Gone are the days|website=iTunes}}</ref>\n| \u2014\n|\n|-\n| \"Amber Rose\"<ref>{{Citation|url=https://itunes.apple.com/za/album/amber-rose-single/1437739994|title=A-Reece - Amber Rose|website=iTunes}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|url=https://soundcloud.com/user-256318544/amber-rose|title=A-Reece - Amber Rose|website=SoundCloud}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|url=https://open.spotify.com/album/03DKZVEoURgCdbVaN2Llcr|title=A-Reece - Amber Rose|website=Spotify}}</ref>\n| \u2014\n|\n|-\n| \"Fuck You\"<ref>{{Citation|url=https://soundcloud.com/user-256318544/fuck-you|title=A-Reece - Fuck You|website=SoundCloud}}</ref>\n| \u2014\n|\n|-\n| Carele$$ \n| \u2014\n|\n|-\n|A Message From Reece\n| \u2014\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"8\"| 2020\n| In His Image [EXP 1]\n| \u2014\n|\n|-\n| Selfish [EXP 2]\n| \u2014\n|\n|}\n\n\"\u2014\" denotes a recording that did not chart or was not released in that territory.\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Award Ceremony\n!Prize\n!Work/Recipient\n!Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" |<div align=\"center\">2016</div>\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2016 South African Hip Hop Awards\n|Lyricist Of The Year<ref name=\"SAHHA16\">{{cite web|title=SA Hip Hop Awards 2016 Nominations Revealed!|url=http://www.mytvnews.co.za/sa-hip-hop-awards-2016-nominations-revealed/|website=My TV News|accessdate=17 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=FULL LIST: SA Hip Hop Awards winners|url=http://www.channel24.co.za/The-Juice/News/full-list-sa-hip-hop-awards-winners-20161215|website=channel24|accessdate=15 December 2016}}</ref>\n|Himself\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|Best Video<ref name=\"SAHHA16\"/>\n|Couldn't (featuring [[Emtee (rapper)|Emtee]])\n|{{nom}}\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Twitter|reece_youngking}}\n*{{Instagram|theboydoingthings}}\n*A-Reece on Facebook\n\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:South African rappers]]\n[[Category:South African record producers]]\n", "name_user": "41.13.10.207", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A-Reece"}
{"title_page": "Clone High", "text_new": "{{short description|Television series}}\n{{Infobox television\n | show_name           = Clone High\n | image               = Clone High Logo.png\n | caption             =\n | show_name_2         = Clone High U.S.A.\n | genre               = {{Unbulleted list|\n[[Adult animation]]|\n[[Animated sitcom]]|\n[[Comedy-drama]]|\n[[Comic science fiction]]|\n[[Satire]]|\n[[Surreal humour|Surreal humor]]\n}}\n | runtime              = 22\u201323 minutes\n | creator              = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Phil Lord and Christopher Miller|Phil Lord<br>Christopher Miller]]\n* [[Bill Lawrence (TV producer)|Bill Lawrence]]\n}}\n | director             =  {{Plainlist|\n* Ted Collyer\n* Harold Harris\n}}\n | voices               =  {{Plainlist|\n* [[Will Forte]]\n* Phil Lord\n* [[Michael McDonald (actor)|Michael McDonald]]\n* [[Christa Miller]]\n* Christopher Miller\n* [[Nicole Sullivan]]\n}}\n | opentheme          = \"Clone High\" by [[Abandoned Pools]]\n | theme_music_composer = [[Tommy Walter]]\n | composer             =  {{Plainlist|\n* Jamie Dunlap\n* Scott Nickoley\n}}\n | country              =  {{Plainlist|\n* Canada\n* United States\n}}\n | language             = English\n | num_seasons          = 1\n | num_episodes         = 13\n | list_episodes        = #Episodes\n | picture_format       = [[480i]]/[[576i]] ([[4:3]] [[Standard-definition television|SDTV]])\n | audio_format         = [[Dolby Surround]] 2.0\n | executive_producer   = {{Plainlist|\n* Phil Lord\n* Christopher Miller\n* Bill Lawrence\n* Geoff Suddleston, Jacquelin French and John Miller <small>(for [[MTV]])</small>\n* [[Michael Hirsh (producer)|Michael Hirsh]], Scott Dyer and Toper Taylor </small>(for [[Nelvana]])<small>\n}}\n | producer             = Kim Cleary\n | company              = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Doozer (company)|Doozer]]\n* [[Phil Lord and Christopher Miller|Lord Miller Productions]]\n* [[Nelvana]]\n* [[ABC Studios#Touchstone Television|Touchstone Television]]\n* [[MTV Animation]]\n* [[Paramount Television]]\n}}\n | distributor          =\n | network              = {{Plainlist|\n* [[MTV]] <small>(United States)</small><ref name=\"lat\"/>\n* [[Teletoon]] <small>(Canada)</small>\n}}\n | first_aired          = {{Start date|2002|11|2}}\n | last_aired           = {{End date|2003|4|13}}\n | website              = https://web.archive.org/web/20050315055511/http://www.corusent.com/corporate/press_room/pressReleaseDetail.asp?id=785\n |}}\n'''''Clone High''''' (occasionally referred to in the U.S. as '''''Clone High U.S.A.''''') is a Canadian\u2013American [[adult animation|adult animated]] sitcom created by [[Phil Lord and Christopher Miller|Phil Lord]], [[Phil Lord and Christopher Miller|Christopher Miller]] and [[Bill Lawrence (TV producer)|Bill Lawrence]]. The [[comedy film|comedy]] centers on a [[high school]] populated by the [[Cloning|clones]] of famous historical figures. The show's central cast includes adolescent depictions of [[Abraham Lincoln]], [[Joan of Arc]], [[Mahatma Gandhi]], [[John F. Kennedy]], and [[Cleopatra]]. The series also serves as a parody of [[teen drama]]s such as [[Dawson's Creek]] and [[Beverly Hills, 90210]]; every episode is introduced as a \"[[very special episode]]\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Perlmutter |first1=David |title=The Encyclopedia of American Animated Television Shows |date=2018 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-1538103739 |page=129 }}</ref>\n\nLord and Miller first developed the series' concept while at [[Dartmouth College]] in the 1990s, later pitching it to executives at American network [[Fox Broadcasting Company]], who ultimately decided to pass on the program. It was later purchased by [[cable television|cable]] channel [[MTV]], and was produced between 2002\u201303. The show's design is heavily stylized and its animation style limited, emphasizing humor and story over visuals. The ''Clone High'' theme song was written by [[Tommy Walter]] and performed by his [[alternative rock]] band [[Abandoned Pools]], who also provided much of the series' background music.\n\n''Clone High'' first aired in its entirety on Canadian cable network [[Teletoon]] between 2002 and 2003, later debuting on MTV. It became embroiled in a controversy regarding its depiction of Gandhi soon afterward, which prompted hundreds in [[India]] to mount a [[hunger strike]] in response. Shortly after, MTV pulled the series, which had been receiving low ratings. ''Clone High'' attracted mixed reviews from television critics upon its premiere, but it has since received critical acclaim and a [[cult following]].\n\n==Premise==\n''Clone High'' is set in a [[high school]] in the fictional town of Exclamation, USA, that is secretly being run as an elaborate military experiment orchestrated by a [[Federal government of the United States|government office]] called the Secret Board of Shadowy Figures. The school is entirely populated by the [[cloning|clones]] of famous historical figures that have been created and raised with the intent of having their various strengths and abilities harnessed by the [[United States military]]. The [[school principal|principal]] of the high school, Cinnamon J. Scudworth, has his own plans for the clones, and secretly tries to undermine the wishes of the Board (Scudworth wants to use the clones to create a clone-themed amusement park, dubbed \"Cloney Island\", a decidedly less evil intention than that of the Board). He is assisted by his [[robot]] butler/[[School principal|vice principal]]/[[dehumidifier]], Mr. Butlertron (a parody of ''[[Mr. Belvedere]]''), who is programmed to call everyone \"Wesley\" and speak in two distinct intonations.\n\nThe main protagonists of ''Clone High'' are the clones of [[Abraham Lincoln]] (referred to as \"Abe\"), [[Joan of Arc]], and [[Mahatma Gandhi]]. Much of the plot of the show revolves around the attempts of Abe to woo the vain and promiscuous clone of [[Cleopatra]], while being oblivious to the fact that his friend Joan of Arc is attracted to him. Meanwhile, [[John F. Kennedy]]'s clone (referred to as \"JFK\"), a macho, narcissistic womanizer, is also attempting to win over Cleopatra and has a long-standing rivalry with Abe. Gandhi acts in many of the episodes as the comic relief. Also on a few occasions, the characters that we see learn most of \"Life's Lessons\" the hard way.\n\n===Themes and style===\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Thegrassyknollclonehigh.jpg|thumb|280px|right|The [[Grassy Knoll]], a reference to the [[John F. Kennedy assassination|JFK assassination]] [[John F. Kennedy assassination conspiracy theories|conspiracy theory]] about a second shooter, dubbed \"[[Dealey Plaza#The \"grassy knoll\"|The Man on the Grassy Knoll]]\". Notice the flag at half mast and JFK leaning over the car.]] -->\nWhile the clones derive many character qualities from their ancestors,<ref name=\"Hal205\">Erickson, 2005. p.205</ref> much of the humor in the show comes from the large contrast between the personality of the clones and the actual values and legacy of the historical figures they are descended from. For instance, Gandhi is portrayed as a hyperactive jerk-with-a-heart-of-gold whose biggest dream is to be accepted by those around him, in contrast to his historical legacy of calm nonviolence. Abe Lincoln is similarly portrayed as weak and indecisive, completely lacking the resolve of the [[President of the United States|President]] whose DNA he shares. All of the clones are also given mis-matched [[foster parent]]s who have little in common with them. Gandhi's parents are a [[stereotype|stereotypical]] [[American Jews|Jewish-American]] couple, while JFK is raised by a [[homosexuality|homosexual]], [[interracial couple]]; Joan's \"foster grandpa\" is an elderly blind musician similar to [[Ray Charles]] named Toots, a parody of the stereotypical [[wise old man]] role (and the [[magical negro]] role) found in many teen shows, and who begins many of his declarative sentences with the words, \"Now, I may be blind, but I can see...\" followed by a wise-sounding observation that has little or nothing to do with anything.\n\nThe show also includes humor based on the historical figures themselves. For example, the diner the clones frequent is called The Grassy Knoll, a reference to the [[Assassination of John F. Kennedy|JFK assassination]] [[John F. Kennedy assassination conspiracy theories|conspiracy theory]] about a second shooter, dubbed \"[[Grassy knoll|The Man on the Grassy Knoll]]\". Other references seen are the flag at The Grassy Knoll being permanently at [[half mast]] and the car on the roof of the diner containing the original JFK's body leaning over the edge. There are pictures of assassinations hanging on the walls of the restaurant, such as the famous [[:Image:The Assassination of President Lincoln - Currier and Ives.png|Currier and Ives print]] of the [[Assassination of Abraham Lincoln|Lincoln assassination]] (though this version is in color and considerably more graphic than the original print). The genetic ancestors of all of the five main clones died of similarly irregular causes: three assassinations, one execution and one suicide. Other historical figure-based humor includes offhand coincidental remarks to other students, such as Abe mentioning that the clone of [[Napoleon]] is so annoying because of \"[[Napoleon complex|some kind of complex]]\", or Gandhi telling [[Catherine the Great]] to \"[[Legends of Catherine the Great|get off her high horse]]\".\n\nThe show is also a [[parody]] of \"issue\" episodes of high-school themed comedies. Each episode is introduced as a \"[[very special episode]].\"<ref name=\"Hal205\"/> Episodes center on various social issues, including Gandhi being shunned by his school for having [[attention-deficit hyperactivity disorder|ADD]] (because of misinformation about the disorder), parodying shows which tackle [[AIDS]] awareness (it even included a special guest celebrity who tries to educate the students). Other episodes tackle [[recreational drug use|drugs]] (smoking raisins), the environment, and underage drinking in a similarly ridiculous fashion. In a clear sign that it is parodying the high school genre, it even ends at [[prom]]: a stereotypical \"high school show\" ending. Even the prom is a joke however, as we learn it is only the Winter Prom.\n\nThere was a [[running gag]] that creators Phil Lord and Christopher Miller wanted to include in the show \"where Clone High \u2013 being an exaggeration of typical high schools in teen dramas \u2013 would have many proms throughout the year\".{{Citation needed|date=September 2009}} Planned proms included \"an Early Winter Prom, a Late Winter/Early Spring Prom, a Mid-Semester Prom, a Post-Prom Clean Up Prom, etc\".{{Citation needed|date=September 2009}} The only surviving references to this joke are the Homecoming Prom in episode 6, \"Homecoming: A Shot in D'Arc\", and the winter prom in episode 13, \"Changes: The Big Prom: The Sex Romp: The Season Finale\".<ref name=\"pundog6\">{{cite web | author=Pava, Adam | title=Episode Six: 'Homecoming: A Shot in the D'Arc' Notes | work=CloneHighUSA.com | url=http://www.clonehighusa.com/backstage/episode_notes/episode_six.html | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030427125949/http://www.clonehighusa.com/backstage/episode_notes/episode_six.html | archivedate=2003-04-27}}</ref> Another reference to the gag was deleted from episode 8, \"A Room of One's Clone: Pie of the Storm\".<ref name=\"pundog6\"/>\n\n==Characters==\n{{See also|List of Clone High characters}}\n[[File:Clone High Cast Promo.jpg|thumb|right|The main characters of ''Clone High'': Mr. Butlertron, John F. Kennedy, Cleopatra, Abe Lincoln, Joan of Arc, Gandhi and \"Cinnamon\" J. Scudworth (reclining).]]\n* '''Abe Lincoln''' (voiced by [[Will Forte]]) is a clone of [[Abraham Lincoln]] and the main [[protagonist]]. He admires his clonefather Abraham Lincoln and feels that he is struggling to live up to him. He is in love with Cleopatra and has a very na\u00efve and awkward personality. Abe doesn't notice that Joan has feelings for him and unintentionally mistreats her by reinterpreting it as a sign of friendship. He later realizes his feelings for her too late.\n* '''Joan of Arc''' (voiced by [[Nicole Sullivan]]) is a clone of [[Joan of Arc]] and Abe's closest friend and confidante. She is an intelligent, cynical and angsty goth. She loves Abe and hates how he ignores her in order to hook up with Cleopatra. She holds liberal political views, and \"somewhat naively support[s] every special-interest cause.\"<ref name=\"Hal205\"/> In the Season Finale, realizing that JFK loves her for herself, Joan begins a relationship with him.\n* '''Gandhi''' (voiced by [[Michael McDonald (comedian)|Michael McDonald]]) is a clone of [[Mahatma Gandhi]] and Abe's other best friend. He, like Abe, is struggling to live up to his clonefather Mahatma Gandhi. As a result, he reinvents himself as a wild party animal who tries to become popular by being outrageous and practicing finger snaps. In the end he begins a relationship with Marie Curie\n* '''JFK''' (voiced by [[Phil Lord and Christopher Miller|Chris Miller]]) is a clone of [[John F. Kennedy]] and a handsome, popular, arrogant, and horny jock as well as Abe's on-and-off rival for Cleo's affections. He later develops feelings for Joan and hates how Abe treats her.\n* '''Cleopatra Smith''' (voiced by [[Christa Miller]]) is a clone of [[Cleopatra|Cleopatra VII]] as well as Abe's love interest and later girlfriend. She is a self-absorbed, vain, and often mean-spirited popular cheerleader who is the object of desire for every male in the school, most notably Abe and JFK. She is also known to live with Joan of Arc due to Cleopatra's mum and Joan's grandfathers relationship\n* '''Principal Scudworth''' ('''Dr. Cinnamon J. Scudworth''') (voiced by [[Phil Lord and Christopher Miller|Phil Lord]]) is the literally \"[[wiktionary:mad|mad]]\" scientist and principal of Clone High, who secretly plans to use the clones as attractions for his hypothetical amusement park, dubbed \"Cloney Island,\" and many of the series' subplots surround him trying to find ways to accelerate his plans. He also hates John Stamos. In his spare time he makes little pirate hats from newspapers, which he collects in a drawer on his desk.\n* '''Mr. Lynn Butlertron''' (voiced by Chris Miller) is Scudworth's [[Mr. Belvedere]]-esque sane robotic butler and reluctant sidekick in his stupid schemes. He refers to everyone as \"Wesley\".\n*Phil Lord as [[Genghis Khan]]\n*[[Nicole Sullivan]] as [[Marie Curie]]\n*[[Donald Faison]] as Toots, Wally, X-Stream Bob, [[Martin Luther King Jr.|Martin Luther King]] and [[George Washington Carver]]\n*[[Neil Flynn]] as [[Julius Caesar]], [[Buddy Holly]], Carl, and [[Moses]], Krabby Kakes, Glenn [[Janitor (Scrubs)|The Janitor]]\n*[[Andy Dick]] as Mr. Sheepman, Police Officer and [[Vincent van Gogh]]\n*[[Murray Miller]] as [[Catherine the Great]]\n*[[Judah Miller]] as Scangrade\n*[[Debra Wilson]] as [[Harriet Tubman]], [[Eva Per\u00f3n]], Skunky-Poo, Reporter\n*[[Sarah Chalke]] as X-Stream Erin, [[Marie Antoinette]]\n*[[Zach Braff]] as X-Stream Mike, [[Paul Revere]]\n*[[Joe Flaherty]] as Abe's Foster Dad\n\n==Production==\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| image1 = Phil_Lord_by_Gage_Skidmore.jpg\n| width1 = 150\n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = \n| image2 = Chris_Miller_by_Gage_Skidmore.jpg\n| width2 = 150\n| alt2 = \n| caption2 = \n| footer = The show was created by [[Phil Lord and Christopher Miller]], seen here at [[San Diego Comic-Con International]] in 2013.\n}}\nMiller initially developed the show's premise while in college, initially imagining the clones would be at a university rather than high school.<ref name=\"grantland\"/> The series was originally developed in 2000 under the title ''Clone High School, USA!''. The production was overseen by [[ABC Studios#Touchstone Television|Touchstone Television]]. It was originally pitched to the [[Fox Broadcasting Company]], who purchased the show immediately but ultimately decided not to order it to series. Miller deemed it the \"easiest pitch ever,\" considering the show's use of famous figures.<ref name=\"grantland\"/> Following Fox's rejection, MTV purchased the program in May 2001.<ref>{{cite news|title=MTV set to attend 'Clone High'|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=May 3, 2001|author=Cynthia Littleton}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://clonehighusa.com/backstage/episode_notes/episode_seven.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040215201829/http://clonehighusa.com/backstage/episode_notes/episode_seven.html|archivedate=2004-02-15|website=CloneHighUSA.com|date=2004-02-25|accessdate=2011-07-12}}</ref> All the original character designs were much different from what they would become even though the characters kept the same physical attributes and appearance. Each episode was budgeted at approximately $750,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2003/feb/17/entertainment/et-solomon17|title=Freshman animators|website=articles.latimes.com|date=2003-02-27|accessdate=2011-07-27|first=Charles|last=Solomon|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121107173707/http://articles.latimes.com/2003/feb/17/entertainment/et-solomon17|archive-date=2012-11-07|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDespite being an [[MTV]]/[[Nelvana]] Co-production, the show was co-produced with [[Touchstone Television]], marking as Disney's third adult animated series after ''[[The PJs]]'' and ''[[Clerks: The Animated Series]]''.\n\nIn forming the show's central cast, they found themselves limited in the number of historical figures they could depict, in consideration with avoiding \"litigious estates\" (such as the families of [[Albert Einstein]] or [[Marilyn Monroe]]) and keeping in mind the viewership of MTV.<ref name=\"grantland\"/> The show also parodies teen dramas, such as ''[[Dawson's Creek]]'', which Lord and Miller watched in preparation to create the series.<ref name=\"grantland\"/> The show's art design has been described as angular and \"evocative of [[UPA (animation studio)|UPA]] at its best.\"<ref name=\"Hal205\"/> It is characterized by a flat and very stylized appearance resembling the animation used in [[Cartoon Network]] animated series from the 1990s and early 2000s, such as ''[[Dexter's Laboratory]]'', ''[[The Powerpuff Girls]]'' and ''[[Time Squad]]'' (Lord and Miller specifically cited ''[[Samurai Jack]]'' as an influence). The character designs were all done by Carey Yost, known for his work on ''Dexter's Laboratory'', ''Samurai Jack'', ''The Powerpuff Girls'', ''[[The Ren & Stimpy Show]]'', and ''[[Timon & Pumbaa (TV series)|Timon & Pumbaa]]''. The characters and backgrounds were [[traditional animation|traditionally drawn]], and frames and cels were frequently recycled. Co-creator Chris Miller explained, \"We like the snappy pose-to-pose animation, more for reasons of comic timing than anything else. Things that aren't expected are funnier: If an anvil's going to fall on your head, it had better not take more than three seconds. That's why we like the quick pose-to-pose stuff. For scenes with more emotional content, the characters move a little slower and more fluidly\". Phil Lord added, \"But we never want the viewer to be paying attention to the animation, because it's there to serve the jokes and the story. We strip out extraneous movements, because we don't want to draw your eye to anything that's not part of a joke.\" Gandhi is the most animated character on the show; he requires twice as many story-board poses as any other character.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clonehighusa.com/backstage/funfacts/fun_facts.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080602070504/http://www.clonehighusa.com/backstage/funfacts/fun_facts.html|archivedate=2008-06-02|title=Clone High Fun Facts|accessdate=2011-07-28}}</ref>\n\nThe series was produced by [[Bill Lawrence (TV producer)|Bill Lawrence]], who also produced ''[[Scrubs (TV series)|Scrubs]]'', ''[[Spin City]]'' and ''[[Cougar Town]]''. Many ''Scrubs'' alumni, such as [[Zach Braff]], [[Donald Faison]], [[Sarah Chalke]], [[John C. McGinley]], [[Neil Flynn]], and [[Christa Miller]], provided the voices of characters in ''Clone High''.\n\n''Clone High'' was notable for subtle jokes hidden in the animation. There is an image of a [[dolphin]] hidden in almost every episode. The use of dolphins (sounds or images) would be later featured in Lord and Miller's later work. In the episode \"Raisin the Stakes\", there were numerous hidden messages, which appeared to be a parody of [[subliminal messaging]].\n\n==Controversy and cancellation==\nAn article in ''[[Maxim (magazine)|Maxim]]'' Magazine depicting [[Mahatma Gandhi]] being beaten up by a muscular man sparked outrage in India.<ref name=\"youtube.com\">{{cite web |author=\"\" |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XHlhFghZ1gM |title=Clone High NEW Behind the Scenes Discussion |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=2010-12-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110914092820/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XHlhFghZ1gM |archive-date=2011-09-14 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''Clone High'' was caught in a crossfire when citizens in the country conducted internet searches on the Maxim article but also found out about the show's Gandhi character on MTV's website. This sparked an outrage in India over the show's depiction of Gandhi.<ref name=\"youtube.com\"/> On January 30, 2003, the 55th anniversary of [[Attempts to assassinate Mahatma Gandhi|Mahatma Gandhi's assassination]], approximately 150 protesters (including [[Member of Parliament#India|members of parliament]]) gathered in [[New Delhi]] and vowed to fast in response to ''Clone High''.<ref>{{cite news | first=Ashok | last=Sharma | title=MTV's Gandhi 'insult' outrages Indian MPs | date=2003-01-31 | publisher=The Guardian | url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2003/jan/31/pressandpublishing.india | location=London | access-date=2016-12-14 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217024444/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2003/jan/31/pressandpublishing.india | archive-date=2017-02-17 | url-status=live }}</ref> Tom Freston, the head of [[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]] (owner of MTV), was visiting the network's India branch and was \"trapped in the building\", according to Miller. In 2014, he recalled that protestors \"basically threatened that they'd revoke MTV's broadcasting license in India if they didn't take the show off the air\".<ref name=\"grantland\"/>\n\nMTV offered a quick apology, stating that \"''Clone High'' was created and intended for an American audience\", and \"we recognize and respect that various cultures may view this programming differently, and we regret any offense taken by the content in the show\".<ref name=\"Grossberg\">{{cite news | first=Josh | last=Grossberg | title=MTV Apologizes for Gandhi Goofing | date=2003-01-31 | publisher=E! Online | url=http://www.eonline.com/news/article/index.jsp?uuid=c520a80c-f8ba-4e92-9355-cbbf7c15647a | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080121191507/http://www.eonline.com/news/article/index.jsp?uuid=c520a80c-f8ba-4e92-9355-cbbf7c15647a | archivedate=2008-01-21}}</ref> Miller would later recall that executives at MTV enjoyed the show, and asked for the duo to pitch a second season without Gandhi. Lord and Miller's two potential versions of a second season included one that made no mention of Gandhi's absence, and another that revealed that the character was, in fact, a clone of actor [[Gary Coleman]] all along, and the show continued as normal. \"We pitched that, and it went up to the top at Viacom again and it got a big no,\" he remembered.<ref name=\"grantland\">{{cite web|url=http://grantland.com/hollywood-prospectus/phil-lord-and-chris-miller-of-the-lego-movie-look-back-on-clone-high-their-cult-classic-mtv-cartoon/|date=February 7, 2014|title=Phil Lord and Chris Miller of 'The Lego Movie' Look Back on 'Clone High,' Their Cult Classic MTV Cartoon|author=Amos Barshad|publisher=[[Grantland]]|accessdate=March 29, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402150328/http://grantland.com/hollywood-prospectus/phil-lord-and-chris-miller-of-the-lego-movie-look-back-on-clone-high-their-cult-classic-mtv-cartoon/|archive-date=2015-04-02|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Future==\nLord and Miller have since stated that they have \"considered\" a film adaptation of the series. In 2014, they explained that as they at that time were under contract with [[20th Century Fox Television|Fox]], Lawrence had a television deal at [[Warner Bros. Television]], and the rights to ''Clone High'' were owned by MTV/Viacom, it would be difficult to resurrect the show.<ref name=\"collider\">{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/clone-high-movie-phil-lord-chris-miller/|date=June 12, 2014|title=Phil Lord and Chris Miller Say They're Discussing the Possibility of a CLONE HIGH Movie; Talk Potential Rating and More|author=Adam Chitwood|publisher=Collider.com|accessdate=March 29, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402124455/http://collider.com/clone-high-movie-phil-lord-chris-miller/|archive-date=2015-04-02|url-status=live}}</ref> References to ''Clone High'' are present in their later productions: the duo admitted many jokes in ''[[22 Jump Street]]'' were \"ripped off straight from ''Clone High''\", and Forte also voices a [[Lego]] version of Lincoln in ''[[The Lego Movie]]''.<ref name=\"grantland\"/> In a 2014 [[Grantland]] article, the two joked that \"our entire career has just been about getting ''Clone High'' back on the air\".<ref name=\"grantland\"/> In the 2018 film ''[[Spider-Man: Into the Spider-Verse]],'' there's a movie poster featuring Abe and JFK in [[Miles Morales]]' universe titled \"Clone College.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.avclub.com/in-the-spider-verse-theres-a-shaun-of-the-dead-sequel-1831083941|title=In the Spider-Verse, there's a Shaun Of The Dead sequel and a Clone High movie|date=December 13, 2018|accessdate=December 13, 2018|website=[[The A.V. Club]]|author=Sam Barsanti}}</ref>\n\n==Episodes==\n===Season 1 (2002\u201303)===\n{{Episode table\n|background=#7ea6e2\n|overall=\n|season=\n|title=\n|writer=\n|airdate=\n|airdateT=Canadian air date<ref name=crtclogs>{{cite web|url=ftp://support.crtc.gc.ca/logs/|title=Television Program Logs|date=2016-03-02|publisher=[[Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission]]|archive-url=https://archive.org/details/support_crtc_gc_ca15052016|archive-date=2016-05-16|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|altdate=\n|altdateT=American air date<ref>http://www.mtv.com/shows/clone-high/episode-guide</ref>\n|country=US\n|episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=1\n |EpisodeNumber2=1\n |Title=Escape to Beer Mountain: A Rope of Sand\n |Aux1=[[Phil Lord and Christopher Miller|Phil Lord & Christopher Miller]] and [[Bill Lawrence (TV producer)|Bill Lawrence]]\n |OriginalAirDate=  {{Start date|2002|11|02}}\n |AltDate= January 20, 2003\n |ShortSummary=In desperation to get with the beautiful and popular Cleopatra, Abe Lincoln is hoping to make a move on her at JFK's party. JFK, however, also has the hots for her and will only let Abe come on the condition that he brings the beer. Meanwhile, Joan of Arc, who is trying to win Abe's heart, starts up a Teen Crisis Hotline in an attempt to impress him with her commitment to community service; their mutual friend, Gandhi, who accidentally agrees to help with the hotline, forwards the calls to his cell phone so he can go to the party. All the while, Principal Scudworth and Mr. Butlertron attempt to crash the party so as to better understand the students.<br>''Notable Guest Stars:'' [[Michael J. Fox]] as Gandhi's remaining kidney, [[Andy Dick]] as [[Vincent Van Gogh|Van Gogh]], [[Donald Faison]] as [[George Washington Carver]].\n| LineColor = 7ea6e2  }}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=2\n |EpisodeNumber2=2\n |Title=Episode Two: Election Blu-Galoo\n |Aux1=Phil Lord & Christopher Miller\n |OriginalAirDate=  {{Start date|2002|11|03}}\n |AltDate= January 27, 2003\n |ShortSummary=Cleo discovers she cannot continue to run for Student Body President because of term limits, so she convinces JFK to run on her behalf, and when Abe sees that Cleo appreciates leaders, he decides to run as well. But students of Clone High do not care about real issues, and many are infatuated with JFK; Abe employs a corporate sponsor, \"X-Stream Blu,\" to jazz up his campaign. The only problem is that Gandhi becomes horribly addicted to this mysterious food product.<br>''Notable guest stars'': [[Marilyn Manson]] as himself, [[Sarah Chalke]] as X-stream Erin, [[Donald Faison]] as X-stream Bob, [[Zach Braff]] as X-stream Mike.\n| LineColor = 7ea6e2  }}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=3\n |EpisodeNumber2=3\n |Title=A.D.D.: The Last 'D' is for Disorder\n |Aux1=[[Tom Martin (writer)|Tom Martin]]\n |OriginalAirDate=  {{Start date|2002|11|10}}\n |AltDate= February 3, 2003\n |ShortSummary=When Gandhi is diagnosed with Attention Deficit Disorder (A.D.D.), the students of Clone High begin to ostracize him. Abe must decide whether to please Cleo by doing the same, or to stand up for his \"best dude 4 ever\" and lose any chance of being with Cleo. Meanwhile, Joan struggles with living up to the legacy of her 15th century clone mother, and begins hearing strange religious voices in her head. Also, Principal Scudworth starts wearing Mr. Butlertron's sweater vest, in the belief that it gives him the power to relate to the students of Clone High.<br>''Notable guest stars'': [[Zach Braff]] as [[Paul Revere]], [[Donald Faison]] as Toots, [[Tom Green]] as himself.\n| LineColor = 7ea6e2  }}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=4\n |EpisodeNumber2=4\n |Title=Film Fest: Tears of a Clone\n |Aux1=Erica Rivinoja\n |OriginalAirDate=  {{Start date|2002|11|17}}\n |AltDate= February 10, 2003\n |ShortSummary=When Abe decides to organize a Clone High Student Film Festival, he spends much time working on a movie about a misunderstood football-playing giraffe; Cleo stars in an autobiographical epic about how difficult it is to be as perfect and glamorous as her; Joan directs an avant-garde film which expresses her love for Abe through psychoanalytic dream imagery; and Gandhi and George Washington Carver work together to make a hilarious mixed-race buddy cop action comedy called Black and Tan. Meanwhile, JFK plans a film but never manages to leave the casting couch with his various wouldbe female co-stars, and Principal Scudworth starts to panic when his bosses on the Secret Board of Shadowy Figures invite themselves to his house for dinner, but thankfully for him, Mr. Butlertron is there to save the day.<br>''Notable guest stars'': [[Donald Faison]] as George Washington Carver, [[Neil Flynn]] as Boy auditioning for Abe's film.\n| LineColor = 7ea6e2  }}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=5\n |EpisodeNumber2=5\n |Title=Sleep of Faith: La Rue D'Awakening\n |Aux1=[[Murray Miller]] & [[Judah Miller]]\n |OriginalAirDate=  {{Start date|2002|12|01}}\n |AltDate= February 17, 2003\n |ShortSummary=The PXJTs (a parody of the SATs) are right around the corner, but Abe is losing sleep running errands for his beloved Cleo. When Joan keeps trying to warn Abe about his sleep deprivation, a secret of hers is uncovered. Also, Gandhi, overwhelmed by the pressure of studying, decides not take the test and become a trucker instead. Mr. Butlertron and an old foe battle it out for the last time.<br>''Notable guest stars'': [[John C. McGinley]] as Doug Prepcourse.\n| LineColor = 7ea6e2  }}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=6\n |EpisodeNumber2=6\n |Title=Homecoming: A Shot in D'Arc\n |Aux1=Eric Kentoff\n |OriginalAirDate=  {{Start date|2002|11|24}}\n |AltDate= February 24, 2003\n |ShortSummary=Since the CHHS basketball team refuses to allow girls or animals to play, the athletic Joan decides to cleverly disguise herself as \"John D'Arc\", becoming the star player. Cleo then falls for D'Arc, making team-captain Abe \"Weakest\"-Lincoln jealous. But Cleo's not the only one falling for John, as fellow athlete JFK finds himself having confusingly sexual feelings about the whole affair. Meanwhile, Gandhi and Genghis Khan kidnap the mascot of Clone High's rival school, Genetically Engineered Superhuman High.<br>''Notable guest stars'': [[Chris Berman]] as himself, [[Dan Patrick]] as himself, [[Neil Flynn]] as [[Julius Caesar]].\n| LineColor = 7ea6e2  }}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=7\n |EpisodeNumber2=7\n |Title=Plane Crazy: Gate Expectations\n |Aux1=Tom Martin\n |OriginalAirDate=  {{Start date|2002|12|08}}\n |AltDate= March 3, 2003\n |ShortSummary=Abe and Cleo's new relationship is threatened when she is picked to be on a Canadian Spring Break Dance show, hosted by Ashley Angel from O-Town. Meanwhile, Gandhi becomes an international rap sensation with the help of JFK as his manager. Also, Principal Scudworth is constantly being tricked by a pesky skunk.<br>''Notable guest stars'': [[Ashley Parker Angel|Ashley Angel]] as himself, [[Neil Flynn]] as [[Buddy Holly]].\n| LineColor = 7ea6e2  }}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=8\n |EpisodeNumber2=8\n |Title=A Room of One's Clone: The Pie of the Storm\n |Aux1=Adam Pava\n |OriginalAirDate=  {{Start date|2002|12|15}}\n |AltDate=<small>N/A</small>\n |ShortSummary=Storm's-a-brewin' when Joan's house burns down and her family has no choice but to move in with Cleo's, where conflict ensues; Abe attends a Conflict Mediation Seminar to learn how to more effectively resolve disputes between the two. Gandhi and JFK find themselves in escalating arguments. Meanwhile, Mr. Butlertron becomes jealous when Principal Scudworth forms a relationship with a robotic toy dog.<br>''Notable guest stars'': [[Donald Faison]] as [[Martin Luther King Jr.]] and Toots, [[Neil Flynn]] as [[Moses]].\n| LineColor = 7ea6e2  }}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=9\n |EpisodeNumber2=9\n |Title=Raisin the Stakes: A Rock Opera in Three Acts\n |Aux1=Phil Lord & Christopher Miller\n |OriginalAirDate=  {{Start date|2003|01|12}}\n |AltDate= March 10, 2003\n |ShortSummary=After an anti-drugs assembly at the school, a rumor goes around that one can get high smoking raisins, leading the clones to embark on a musical, mystical journey of intoxication and irresponsibly long hair. Sober Joan is trying to keep Abe from turning into a drugged-out hippie, while Principal Scudworth and the PTA build a giant wall in an attempt to fence the students in. Meanwhile, Gandhi goes on a raisined-out subconscious mindtrip where he encounters a hummingbird-unicorn-donkey creature, a two-headed [[Mary-Kate and Ashley Olsen|Olsen Twins]] monster, a talking Italian pencil, and a stereotypically Australian dragon, on his quest to rescue a princess who he believes will have sex with him.<br>''Notable guest stars'': [[Jack Black]] as Larry Hardcore/the Pusher.\n| LineColor = 7ea6e2  }}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=10\n |EpisodeNumber2=10\n |Title=Litter Kills: Litterally\n |Aux1=[[Murray Miller]] & [[Judah Miller]]\n |OriginalAirDate=  {{Start date|2003|01|19}}\n |AltDate=<small>N/A</small>\n |ShortSummary=JFK's long time best friend, Ponce de Le\u00f3n, literally dies, causing JFK to sink into a spiral of depression. This causes tension between Abe and Cleo, who dutifully attempts to comfort JFK, her former boyfriend, during his grief. Meanwhile, Gandhi is mistakenly sent to death row where he has trouble getting high fives, but makes new friends in the showers.<br>''Notable guest stars'': [[Luke Perry]] as [[Juan Ponce de Le\u00f3n|Ponce]], [[Neil Flynn]] as Glenn the Janitor and Julius Caesar.\n| LineColor = 7ea6e2  }}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=13\n |EpisodeNumber2=11\n |Title=Snowflake Day: A Very Special Holiday Episode\n |Aux1=Erica Rivinoja\n |OriginalAirDate=  {{Start date|2003|04|13}}<ref>{{IMDb episode|0542914|Snowflake Day: A Very Special Holiday Episode| LineColor = 7ea6e2  }}</ref>\n |AltDate=<small>N/A</small>\n |ShortSummary=It's the politically correct Snowflake Day season, and everyone is in the holiday spirit, except for Joan, who is against the commercialism of the made-up holiday. But a homeless urchin who \"may or may not be\" pop sensation Mandy Moore teaches Joan an important lesson. Meanwhile, Abe and Gandhi attempt to invent and market an interesting device, so that Abe will have money to buy Cleo an expensive Snowflake Day gift.<br>''Notable guest stars'': [[Mandy Moore]] as herself.<br>''Note'': This episode begins with a parody of the 1973 \"A [[CBS]] Special Presentation\" bumper.\n| LineColor = 7ea6e2  }}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=11\n |EpisodeNumber2=12\n |Title=Makeover, Makeover, Makeover: The Makeover Episode\n |Aux1=Eric Kentoff\n |OriginalAirDate= {{Start date|2003|01|26}}\n |AltDate=<small>N/A</small>\n |ShortSummary=With prom not too far away, Abe wants to ask his girlfriend, Cleo, but cannot stop thinking about Joan's prom date situation. Meanwhile, Gandhi goes on a desperate search for a date. So, Abe and Cleo each have a go at making over Joan for prom, JFK gives Gandhi a makeover, and Mr. B gives Scudworth a makeover to help him execute a sinister, evil plan to \"win\" the prom king vote.\n| LineColor = 7ea6e2  }}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=12\n |EpisodeNumber2=13\n |Title=Changes: The Big Prom: The Sex Romp: The Season Finale\n |Aux1=Phil Lord & Christopher Miller\n |OriginalAirDate= {{Start date|2003|03|02}}\n |AltDate=<small>N/A</small>\n |ShortSummary=As all the clones are preparing for the winter prom, Abe decides whether to ask Cleo or Joan; Gandhi concocts a brilliant plan to get dates for all the school geeks; and Principal Scudworth attempts to execute his sinister, evil plan, while the Secret Board of Shadowy Figures prepares to abduct the clones on prom night to advance their own evil plan.<br>''Notable guest stars'': [[John Stamos]] and [[Tommy Walter]] as themselves.\n| LineColor = 7ea6e2\n}}}}\n\n==Soundtrack==\nThe previous animated MTV series ''[[Daria]]'' and ''[[Beavis and Butt-head]]'' had used then-current [[popular music]] as a soundtrack, but, in contrast, ''Clone High'' featured a wide variety of music, usually exclusive to [[alternative rock]], [[indie rock]], [[midwest emo]], [[hardcore punk]] [[pop rock]], [[metalcore]], from mostly unknown and [[underground music|underground]] bands and musicians; a previous MTV animated series, ''[[Undergrads]]'', had also done this. Of these include [[Alkaline Trio]], [[American Football (band)|American Football]], [[Ritalin (band)|Ritalin]], [[Catch 22 (band)|Catch 22]], [[Ilya (band)|Ilya]], The Gentleman, Drex, [[Taking Back Sunday]], [[The Stereo]], Jo Davidson, [[Saves the Day]], [[Hot Rod Circuit]], [[Thursday (band)|Thursday]], Helicopter Helicopter, [[Owen (band)|Owen]], [[Dashboard Confessional]], [[Elf Power]], [[Abandoned Pools]], [[The Get Up Kids]], [[Mink Lungs]], [[Mates of State]], [[Snapcase]], [[The Mooney Suzuki]], [[Jon DeRosa]], [[Ephemera (band)|Ephemera]], Jinnrall, [[Avoid One Thing]], DJ Cellulitis, DJ Piccolo, [[Whippersnapper (band)|Whippersnapper]], [[Matt Pond PA]], Mad City and [[Ron \"Bumblefoot\" Thal|Bumblefoot]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/onair/clone_high/ |title=MTV.com - Onair - Clone High |date=2003-01-19 |accessdate=2010-12-06 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030119090212/http://www.mtv.com/onair/clone_high/ |archivedate=2003-01-19 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.clonehighusa.com/music/music_by_episode.html |title=CloneHighUSA.com |date=2003-01-04 |accessdate=2011-07-03 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030409053346/http://www.clonehighusa.com/music/music_by_episode.html |archivedate=2003-04-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The series' other background music and original score was written and produced by Scott Nickoley and Jamie Dunlap of Mad City Productions. Nickoley and Dunlap went on to score other shows such as ''[[South Park]]'', ''[[The Osbournes]]'' and ''[[Newlyweds: Nick and Jessica|Newlyweds]]''.\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Initial reviews===\nTelevision critics gave ''Clone High'' mixed reviews upon its 2002 premiere. On [[Metacritic]], which assigns a normalized rating out of 100 based on reviews from critics, the show has a score of 60, based on seven reviews, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|title=''Clone High, USA'' Reviews|url=https://metacritic.com/tv/clone-high-usa|publisher=[[Metacritic]] ([[CBS Interactive]])|accessdate=March 29, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402174808/http://www.metacritic.com/tv/clone-high-usa|archive-date=2015-04-02|url-status=live}}</ref> David Bianculli of the ''[[New York Daily News]]'' praised the series, commenting, \"In a year of variations and ripoffs of established themes and genres, it's a true original. It's also a cartoon, and is truly, outrageously bizarre.\"<ref name=\"nydn\">{{cite journal|author=Anita Gates|title=This Class Is One For The History Books|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/entertainment/class-history-books-article-1.672864|journal=[[New York Daily News]]|date=January 20, 2003|accessdate=March 29, 2015|pages=85|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402104555/http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/entertainment/class-history-books-article-1.672864|archive-date=2015-04-02|url-status=live}}</ref> The ''[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]''{{'s}} Rob Owen complimented the show: \"Yes, ''Clone High'' has the MTV-requisite sexual innuendo, but it's more clever than much of what passes for humor in prime time today. And like ''Scrubs'', it has heart, particularly when it comes to Abe and Joan.\"<ref name=\"post\">{{cite journal|author=Rob Owen|title=Historical figures sent back to the drawing board|url=http://old.post-gazette.com/tv/20030112clone0112fnp3.asp|journal=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|date=January 12, 2003|pages=D-3|accessdate=March 29, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402090311/http://old.post-gazette.com/tv/20030112clone0112fnp3.asp|archive-date=2015-04-02|url-status=live}}</ref> Anita Gates of ''[[The New York Times]]'' opined that \"the dialogue isn't always exactly funny, but it's smile worthy,\" observing, \"the characters are intriguing in a lightweight way but could lose their appeal fast.\"<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite web|author=Anita Gates|title=TELEVISION REVIEW; Kennedy and Lincoln, Wooing Cleopatra|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/01/20/arts/television-review-kennedy-and-lincoln-wooing-cleopatra.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=January 20, 2003|accessdate=March 29, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402195640/http://www.nytimes.com/2003/01/20/arts/television-review-kennedy-and-lincoln-wooing-cleopatra.html|archive-date=2015-04-02|url-status=live}}</ref> Scott Sandell of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' felt the show's debut episode lacking: \"The problem is that the first episode, which focuses on crushes and beer, doesn't quite live up to the obvious comedic potential behind the killer premise.\"<ref name=\"lat\">{{cite news|title=Peer pressure of historic proportions|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=January 20, 2003|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2003/jan/20/entertainment/et-sandell20|accessdate=November 8, 2010|first=Scott|last=Sandell|pages=C-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120820022705/http://articles.latimes.com/2003/jan/20/entertainment/et-sandell20|archive-date=2012-08-20|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]''{{'s}} Michael Farkash felt similarly, writing, \"The premise sounds intriguing, but what hatches in the first episode is a disappointing, weak strain of comic material, lacking the cunning, subversive quality of, say, ''[[South Park]]''.\"<ref name=\"hr\">{{cite news|title= Clone High, U.S.A. (TV Brief)|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=January 10, 2003|author=Michael Farkash}}</ref>\n\n===Retrospective reviews===\nBecause of the series' early cancellation in 2003, it quickly fell into obscurity, especially in the US. However, it has garnered a large fanbase throughout the Internet and still occasionally airs reruns on [[Teletoon]]'s ''[[Teletoon at Night]]'' (formerly Teletoon Detour) block and formerly aired on [[MTV Canada|MTV]], [[MTV2 Canada|MTV2]] and [[MTV2 (Canada)|Razer]] (now MTV2) in Canada. [[MuchMusic|Much]] in Canada has also aired reruns of ''Clone High'' for a short time.\n\nHeather Marulli, of the website [[Television Without Pity]], called the series \"a mini-masterpiece of the animated genre; an opus to the primetime cartoon\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Marulli |first=Heather |title=Tonight, On A Very Special Clone High... |url=http://www.televisionwithoutpity.com/brilliantbutcancelled/2009/12/tonight-on-a-very-special-clon.php |publisher=televisionwithoutpity.com |accessdate=2009-12-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091205095712/http://www.televisionwithoutpity.com/brilliantbutcancelled/2009/12/tonight-on-a-very-special-clon.php |archivedate=2009-12-05 }}</ref>\n\nDavid Broermann, from the website Freakin' Awesome Network, gave the series an \"A+\", saying it has \"some really really good character development and depth\" and an \"amazing soundtrack\" He notes the fantastic use of multiple running gags keeping viewers on their toes.<ref>{{cite news |last=Broermann |first=David |title=Dave the Dave's Review: Oh Wesley (Clone High) |url=http://www.freakinawesomenetwork.net/2011/09/dave-the-daves-review-review-oh-wesley/ |date=2011-09-10 |accessdate=2012-05-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116110113/http://www.freakinawesomenetwork.net/2011/09/dave-the-daves-review-review-oh-wesley/ |archive-date=2014-01-16 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nCurrently, the show has an 8.7 rating on [[TV.com]],<ref>{{cite news | title=Clone High, USA on TV.com | url=http://www.tv.com/shows/clone-high/ | access-date=2012-10-02 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104151912/http://www.tv.com/shows/clone-high/ | archive-date=2012-11-04 | url-status=live }}</ref> has an 8.1 rating on [[IMDb]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0305011/ |title=Clone High (TV Series 2002\u20132003) - IMDb<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2018-06-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180318204119/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0305011/ |archive-date=2018-03-18 |url-status=live }}</ref> and is listed as #5 on [[IGN]]'s \"Reader Choice: Top Animated Series\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Fowler |first=Matt |url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/964/964034p3.html |title=Readers' Choice: IGN's Top Animated Series - TV Feature at IGN |publisher=Tv.ign.com |accessdate=2010-12-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100317123722/http://tv.ign.com/articles/964/964034p3.html |archive-date=2010-03-17 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nJesse David Fox of ''[[Vulture (blog)|Vulture]]'', in a retrospective piece on the series, wrote that \"''Clone High'' still holds up more than a decade later as a brilliantly funny, completely nuts, surprisingly heartfelt, tonally inventive masterpiece.\"<ref name=\"vulture\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2014/02/clone-high-lego-movie-phil-lord-christopher-miller.html|date=February 13, 2014|title=Remembering The LEGO Movie Directors' Superb TV Show, Clone High|author=Jesse David Fox|publisher=[[Vulture (blog)|Vulture]]|accessdate=March 29, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402110909/http://www.vulture.com/2014/02/clone-high-lego-movie-phil-lord-christopher-miller.html|archive-date=2015-04-02|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Home media==\nThe two-disc DVD complete series boxset was released in Canada by [[Nelvana]] with the help of [[Teletoon]]. The DVD contains the complete series, including the five episodes which did not originally air in the United States.\n{{Television home release\n| title = Clone High: The Complete Series\n| color = 7ea6e2\n| set_details =\n* 13 episodes\n* 2-disc [[DVD]] set\n* 286 minutes\n* [[Dolby Digital]]:\n** English\n** French\n| special_features =\n* Video clips of:\n** Christopher Miller performing as \"Mr. B\"\n** Phil Lord performing as \"Principal Scudworth\"\n** Bill Lawrence, an executive producer, in a hot tub\n** Tom Martin describing the writing process\n* Video footage of live-action cat depicted in \"Raisin the Skates: A Rock Opera in 3 Acts\"\n| region1 = {{Start date|2005|9|20}}\n| region2 = <small>N/A</small>\n| region4 = Unknown (currently out of print)\n}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Dolly (sheep)|Dolly the sheep]]\n*''[[Afterschool Charisma]]''\n*[[Human cloning]]\n*''[[Total Drama]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Notes===\n* {{cite book |last=Erickson |first=Hal |authorlink=Hal Erickson (author) |year=2005 |title=Television Cartoon Shows |edition=2nd|volume=1 |publisher=McFardland and Company|isbn=07864-2255-6}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n\n* {{official website|URL=https://web.archive.org/web/20050315055511/http://www.corusent.com/corporate/press_room/pressReleaseDetail.asp?id=785}}\n* {{IMDb title|305011}}\n* {{tv.com show|clone-high}}\n* {{Cite web |url=http://www.corusent.com/corporate/press_room/pressReleaseDetail.asp?id=785 |title=DVD press release |access-date=May 8, 2005 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050315055511/http://www.corusent.com/corporate/press_room/pressReleaseDetail.asp?id=785 |archive-date=March 15, 2005 |url-status=bot: unknown |df=mdy-all }}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051120011939/http://www.gazette.uwo.ca/2003/January/24/arts_and_entertainment1.htm UWO Gazette article about Clone High]\n* [http://www.flakmag.com/tv/clonehigh.html Flak Magazine: Clone High]\n\n{{MTV Animation}}\n{{MTV Network programs}}\n{{Teletoon}}\n{{Phil Lord and Christopher Miller}}\n\n[[Category:2000s American adult animated television series]]\n[[Category:2000s American black comedy television series]]\n[[Category:2000s American comedy-drama television series]]\n[[Category:2000s American comic science fiction television series]]\n[[Category:2000s American high school television series]]\n[[Category:2000s American LGBT-related television series]]\n[[Category:2000s American parody television series]]\n[[Category:2000s American sitcoms]]\n[[Category:2000s American surreal comedy television series]]\n[[Category:2000s American teen drama television series]]\n[[Category:2000s Canadian adult animated television series]]\n[[Category:2000s Canadian comedy-drama television series]]\n[[Category:2000s Canadian comic science fiction television series]]\n[[Category:2000s Canadian high school television series]]\n[[Category:2000s Canadian satirical television series]]\n[[Category:2000s Canadian sitcoms]]\n[[Category:2000s Canadian teen drama television series]]\n[[Category:2002 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2002 Canadian television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2003 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:2003 Canadian television series endings]]\n[[Category:American adult animated drama television series]]\n[[Category:American adult animated science fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:American adult animated comic science fiction television series]]\n[[Category:American flash adult animated television series]]\n[[Category:Bangsian fantasy]]\n[[Category:Canadian adult animated drama television series]]\n[[Category:Canadian adult animated comic science fiction television series]]\n[[Category:Canadian flash animated television series]]\n[[Category:Cartoon controversies]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Buddy Holly]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Catherine the Great]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Eva Per\u00f3n]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Joan of Arc]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of John F. Kennedy]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Mahatma Gandhi]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Marie Antoinette]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Marie Curie]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Martin Luther King Jr.]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Napoleon]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Vincent van Gogh]]\n[[Category:Depictions of Cleopatra on television]]\n[[Category:Depictions of Genghis Khan on television]]\n[[Category:Depictions of Julius Caesar on television]]\n[[Category:Fictional depictions of Abraham Lincoln in television]]\n[[Category:LGBT-related animated series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:MTV cartoons]]\n[[Category:Teletoon original series]]\n[[Category:Television controversies in Canada]]\n[[Category:Television controversies in the United States]]\n[[Category:Television series about cloning]]\n[[Category:Television series by ABC Studios]]\n[[Category:Television series by Nelvana]]\n[[Category:Television series created by Bill Lawrence (TV producer)]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about teenagers]]\n[[Category:Teen animated television series]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Television series}}\n{{Infobox television\n | show_name           = Clone High\n | image               = Clone High Logo.png\n | caption             =\n | show_name_2         = Clone High U.S.A.\n | genre               = {{Unbulleted list|\n[[Adult animation]]|\n[[Animated sitcom]]|\n[[Comedy-drama]]|\n[[Comic science fiction]]|\n[[Satire]]|\n[[Surreal humour|Surreal humor]]\n}}\n | runtime              = 22\u201323 minutes\n | creator              = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Phil Lord and Christopher Miller|Phil Lord<br>Christopher Miller]]\n* [[Bill Lawrence (TV producer)|Bill Lawrence]]\n}}\n | director             =  {{Plainlist|\n* Ted Collyer\n* Harold Harris\n}}\n | voices               =  {{Plainlist|\n* [[Will Forte]]\n* Phil Lord\n* [[Michael McDonald (actor)|Michael McDonald]]\n* [[Christa Miller]]\n* Christopher Miller\n* [[Nicole Sullivan]]\n}}\n | opentheme          = \"Clone High\" by [[Abandoned Pools]]\n | theme_music_composer = [[Tommy Walter]]\n | composer             =  {{Plainlist|\n* Jamie Dunlap\n* Scott Nickoley\n}}\n | country              =  {{Plainlist|\n* Canada\n* United States\n}}\n | language             = English\n | num_seasons          = 1\n | num_episodes         = 13\n | list_episodes        = #Episodes\n | picture_format       = [[480i]]/[[576i]] ([[4:3]] [[Standard-definition television|SDTV]])\n | audio_format         = [[Dolby Surround]] 2.0\n | executive_producer   = {{Plainlist|\n* Phil Lord\n* Christopher Miller\n* Bill Lawrence\n* Geoff Suddleston, Jacquelin French and John Miller <small>(for [[MTV]])</small>\n* [[Michael Hirsh (producer)|Michael Hirsh]], Scott Dyer and Toper Taylor </small>(for [[Nelvana]])<small>\n}}\n | producer             = Kim Cleary\n | company              = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Doozer (company)|Doozer]]\n* [[Phil Lord and Christopher Miller|Lord Miller Productions]]\n* [[Nelvana]]\n* [[ABC Studios#Touchstone Television|Touchstone Television]]\n* [[MTV Animation]]\n* [[Paramount Television]]\n}}\n | distributor          =\n | network              = {{Plainlist|\n* [[MTV]] <small>(United States)</small><ref name=\"lat\"/>\n* [[Teletoon]] <small>(Canada)</small>\n}}\n | first_aired          = {{Start date|2002|11|2}}\n | last_aired           = {{End date|2003|4|13}}\n | website              = https://web.archive.org/web/20050315055511/http://www.corusent.com/corporate/press_room/pressReleaseDetail.asp?id=785\n |}}\n'''''Clone High''''' (occasionally referred to in the U.S. as '''''Clone High U.S.A.''''') is a Canadian\u2013American [[adult animation|adult animated]] sitcom created by [[Phil Lord and Christopher Miller|Phil Lord]], [[Phil Lord and Christopher Miller|Christopher Miller]] and [[Bill Lawrence (TV producer)|Bill Lawrence]]. The [[comedy film|comedy]] centers on a [[high school]] populated by the [[Cloning|clones]] of famous historical figures. The show's central cast includes adolescent depictions of [[Abraham Lincoln]], [[Joan of Arc]], [[Mahatma Gandhi]], [[John F. Kennedy]], and [[Cleopatra]]. The series also serves as a parody of [[teen drama]]s; every episode is introduced as a \"[[very special episode]]\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Perlmutter |first1=David |title=The Encyclopedia of American Animated Television Shows |date=2018 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-1538103739 |page=129 }}</ref>\n\nLord and Miller first developed the series' concept while at [[Dartmouth College]] in the 1990s, later pitching it to executives at American network [[Fox Broadcasting Company]], who ultimately decided to pass on the program. It was later purchased by [[cable television|cable]] channel [[MTV]], and was produced between 2002\u201303. The show's design is heavily stylized and its animation style limited, emphasizing humor and story over visuals. The ''Clone High'' theme song was written by [[Tommy Walter]] and performed by his [[alternative rock]] band [[Abandoned Pools]], who also provided much of the series' background music.\n\n''Clone High'' first aired in its entirety on Canadian cable network [[Teletoon]] between 2002 and 2003, later debuting on MTV. It became embroiled in a controversy regarding its depiction of Gandhi soon afterward, which prompted hundreds in [[India]] to mount a [[hunger strike]] in response. Shortly after, MTV pulled the series, which had been receiving low ratings. ''Clone High'' attracted mixed reviews from television critics upon its premiere, but it has since received critical acclaim and a [[cult following]].\n\n==Premise==\n''Clone High'' is set in a [[high school]] in the fictional town of Exclamation, USA, that is secretly being run as an elaborate military experiment orchestrated by a [[Federal government of the United States|government office]] called the Secret Board of Shadowy Figures. The school is entirely populated by the [[cloning|clones]] of famous historical figures that have been created and raised with the intent of having their various strengths and abilities harnessed by the [[United States military]]. The [[school principal|principal]] of the high school, Cinnamon J. Scudworth, has his own plans for the clones, and secretly tries to undermine the wishes of the Board (Scudworth wants to use the clones to create a clone-themed amusement park, dubbed \"Cloney Island\", a decidedly less evil intention than that of the Board). He is assisted by his [[robot]] butler/[[School principal|vice principal]]/[[dehumidifier]], Mr. Butlertron (a parody of ''[[Mr. Belvedere]]''), who is programmed to call everyone \"Wesley\" and speak in two distinct intonations.\n\nThe main protagonists of ''Clone High'' are the clones of [[Abraham Lincoln]] (referred to as \"Abe\"), [[Joan of Arc]], and [[Mahatma Gandhi]]. Much of the plot of the show revolves around the attempts of Abe to woo the vain and promiscuous clone of [[Cleopatra]], while being oblivious to the fact that his friend Joan of Arc is attracted to him. Meanwhile, [[John F. Kennedy]]'s clone (referred to as \"JFK\"), a macho, narcissistic womanizer, is also attempting to win over Cleopatra and has a long-standing rivalry with Abe. Gandhi acts in many of the episodes as the comic relief. Also on a few occasions, the characters that we see learn most of \"Life's Lessons\" the hard way.\n\n===Themes and style===\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Thegrassyknollclonehigh.jpg|thumb|280px|right|The [[Grassy Knoll]], a reference to the [[John F. Kennedy assassination|JFK assassination]] [[John F. Kennedy assassination conspiracy theories|conspiracy theory]] about a second shooter, dubbed \"[[Dealey Plaza#The \"grassy knoll\"|The Man on the Grassy Knoll]]\". Notice the flag at half mast and JFK leaning over the car.]] -->\nWhile the clones derive many character qualities from their ancestors,<ref name=\"Hal205\">Erickson, 2005. p.205</ref> much of the humor in the show comes from the large contrast between the personality of the clones and the actual values and legacy of the historical figures they are descended from. For instance, Gandhi is portrayed as a hyperactive jerk-with-a-heart-of-gold whose biggest dream is to be accepted by those around him, in contrast to his historical legacy of calm nonviolence. Abe Lincoln is similarly portrayed as weak and indecisive, completely lacking the resolve of the [[President of the United States|President]] whose DNA he shares. All of the clones are also given mis-matched [[foster parent]]s who have little in common with them. Gandhi's parents are a [[stereotype|stereotypical]] [[American Jews|Jewish-American]] couple, while JFK is raised by a [[homosexuality|homosexual]], [[interracial couple]]; Joan's \"foster grandpa\" is an elderly blind musician similar to [[Ray Charles]] named Toots, a parody of the stereotypical [[wise old man]] role (and the [[magical negro]] role) found in many teen shows, and who begins many of his declarative sentences with the words, \"Now, I may be blind, but I can see...\" followed by a wise-sounding observation that has little or nothing to do with anything.\n\nThe show also includes humor based on the historical figures themselves. For example, the diner the clones frequent is called The Grassy Knoll, a reference to the [[Assassination of John F. Kennedy|JFK assassination]] [[John F. Kennedy assassination conspiracy theories|conspiracy theory]] about a second shooter, dubbed \"[[Grassy knoll|The Man on the Grassy Knoll]]\". Other references seen are the flag at The Grassy Knoll being permanently at [[half mast]] and the car on the roof of the diner containing the original JFK's body leaning over the edge. There are pictures of assassinations hanging on the walls of the restaurant, such as the famous [[:Image:The Assassination of President Lincoln - Currier and Ives.png|Currier and Ives print]] of the [[Assassination of Abraham Lincoln|Lincoln assassination]] (though this version is in color and considerably more graphic than the original print). The genetic ancestors of all of the five main clones died of similarly irregular causes: three assassinations, one execution and one suicide. Other historical figure-based humor includes offhand coincidental remarks to other students, such as Abe mentioning that the clone of [[Napoleon]] is so annoying because of \"[[Napoleon complex|some kind of complex]]\", or Gandhi telling [[Catherine the Great]] to \"[[Legends of Catherine the Great|get off her high horse]]\".\n\nThe show is also a [[parody]] of \"issue\" episodes of high-school themed comedies. Each episode is introduced as a \"[[very special episode]].\"<ref name=\"Hal205\"/> Episodes center on various social issues, including Gandhi being shunned by his school for having [[attention-deficit hyperactivity disorder|ADD]] (because of misinformation about the disorder), parodying shows which tackle [[AIDS]] awareness (it even included a special guest celebrity who tries to educate the students). Other episodes tackle [[recreational drug use|drugs]] (smoking raisins), the environment, and underage drinking in a similarly ridiculous fashion. In a clear sign that it is parodying the high school genre, it even ends at [[prom]]: a stereotypical \"high school show\" ending. Even the prom is a joke however, as we learn it is only the Winter Prom.\n\nThere was a [[running gag]] that creators Phil Lord and Christopher Miller wanted to include in the show \"where Clone High \u2013 being an exaggeration of typical high schools in teen dramas \u2013 would have many proms throughout the year\".{{Citation needed|date=September 2009}} Planned proms included \"an Early Winter Prom, a Late Winter/Early Spring Prom, a Mid-Semester Prom, a Post-Prom Clean Up Prom, etc\".{{Citation needed|date=September 2009}} The only surviving references to this joke are the Homecoming Prom in episode 6, \"Homecoming: A Shot in D'Arc\", and the winter prom in episode 13, \"Changes: The Big Prom: The Sex Romp: The Season Finale\".<ref name=\"pundog6\">{{cite web | author=Pava, Adam | title=Episode Six: 'Homecoming: A Shot in the D'Arc' Notes | work=CloneHighUSA.com | url=http://www.clonehighusa.com/backstage/episode_notes/episode_six.html | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030427125949/http://www.clonehighusa.com/backstage/episode_notes/episode_six.html | archivedate=2003-04-27}}</ref> Another reference to the gag was deleted from episode 8, \"A Room of One's Clone: Pie of the Storm\".<ref name=\"pundog6\"/>\n\n==Characters==\n{{See also|List of Clone High characters}}\n[[File:Clone High Cast Promo.jpg|thumb|right|The main characters of ''Clone High'': Mr. Butlertron, John F. Kennedy, Cleopatra, Abe Lincoln, Joan of Arc, Gandhi and \"Cinnamon\" J. Scudworth (reclining).]]\n* '''Abe Lincoln''' (voiced by [[Will Forte]]) is a clone of [[Abraham Lincoln]] and the main [[protagonist]]. He admires his clonefather Abraham Lincoln and feels that he is struggling to live up to him. He is in love with Cleopatra and has a very na\u00efve and awkward personality. Abe doesn't notice that Joan has feelings for him and unintentionally mistreats her by reinterpreting it as a sign of friendship. He later realizes his feelings for her too late.\n* '''Joan of Arc''' (voiced by [[Nicole Sullivan]]) is a clone of [[Joan of Arc]] and Abe's closest friend and confidante. She is an intelligent, cynical and angsty goth. She loves Abe and hates how he ignores her in order to hook up with Cleopatra. She holds liberal political views, and \"somewhat naively support[s] every special-interest cause.\"<ref name=\"Hal205\"/> In the Season Finale, realizing that JFK loves her for herself, Joan begins a relationship with him.\n* '''Gandhi''' (voiced by [[Michael McDonald (comedian)|Michael McDonald]]) is a clone of [[Mahatma Gandhi]] and Abe's other best friend. He, like Abe, is struggling to live up to his clonefather Mahatma Gandhi. As a result, he reinvents himself as a wild party animal who tries to become popular by being outrageous and practicing finger snaps. In the end he begins a relationship with Marie Curie\n* '''JFK''' (voiced by [[Phil Lord and Christopher Miller|Chris Miller]]) is a clone of [[John F. Kennedy]] and a handsome, popular, arrogant, and horny jock as well as Abe's on-and-off rival for Cleo's affections. He later develops feelings for Joan and hates how Abe treats her.\n* '''Cleopatra Smith''' (voiced by [[Christa Miller]]) is a clone of [[Cleopatra|Cleopatra VII]] as well as Abe's love interest and later girlfriend. She is a self-absorbed, vain, and often mean-spirited popular cheerleader who is the object of desire for every male in the school, most notably Abe and JFK. She is also known to live with Joan of Arc due to Cleopatra's mum and Joan's grandfathers relationship\n* '''Principal Scudworth''' ('''Dr. Cinnamon J. Scudworth''') (voiced by [[Phil Lord and Christopher Miller|Phil Lord]]) is the literally \"[[wiktionary:mad|mad]]\" scientist and principal of Clone High, who secretly plans to use the clones as attractions for his hypothetical amusement park, dubbed \"Cloney Island,\" and many of the series' subplots surround him trying to find ways to accelerate his plans. He also hates John Stamos. In his spare time he makes little pirate hats from newspapers, which he collects in a drawer on his desk.\n* '''Mr. Lynn Butlertron''' (voiced by Chris Miller) is Scudworth's [[Mr. Belvedere]]-esque sane robotic butler and reluctant sidekick in his stupid schemes. He refers to everyone as \"Wesley\".\n*Phil Lord as [[Genghis Khan]]\n*[[Nicole Sullivan]] as [[Marie Curie]]\n*[[Donald Faison]] as Toots, Wally, X-Stream Bob, [[Martin Luther King Jr.|Martin Luther King]] and [[George Washington Carver]]\n*[[Neil Flynn]] as [[Julius Caesar]], [[Buddy Holly]], Carl, and [[Moses]], Krabby Kakes, Glenn [[Janitor (Scrubs)|The Janitor]]\n*[[Andy Dick]] as Mr. Sheepman, Police Officer and [[Vincent van Gogh]]\n*[[Murray Miller]] as [[Catherine the Great]]\n*[[Judah Miller]] as Scangrade\n*[[Debra Wilson]] as [[Harriet Tubman]], [[Eva Per\u00f3n]], Skunky-Poo, Reporter\n*[[Sarah Chalke]] as X-Stream Erin, [[Marie Antoinette]]\n*[[Zach Braff]] as X-Stream Mike, [[Paul Revere]]\n*[[Joe Flaherty]] as Abe's Foster Dad\n\n==Production==\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| image1 = Phil_Lord_by_Gage_Skidmore.jpg\n| width1 = 150\n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = \n| image2 = Chris_Miller_by_Gage_Skidmore.jpg\n| width2 = 150\n| alt2 = \n| caption2 = \n| footer = The show was created by [[Phil Lord and Christopher Miller]], seen here at [[San Diego Comic-Con International]] in 2013.\n}}\nMiller initially developed the show's premise while in college, initially imagining the clones would be at a university rather than high school.<ref name=\"grantland\"/> The series was originally developed in 2000 under the title ''Clone High School, USA!''. The production was overseen by [[ABC Studios#Touchstone Television|Touchstone Television]]. It was originally pitched to the [[Fox Broadcasting Company]], who purchased the show immediately but ultimately decided not to order it to series. Miller deemed it the \"easiest pitch ever,\" considering the show's use of famous figures.<ref name=\"grantland\"/> Following Fox's rejection, MTV purchased the program in May 2001.<ref>{{cite news|title=MTV set to attend 'Clone High'|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=May 3, 2001|author=Cynthia Littleton}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://clonehighusa.com/backstage/episode_notes/episode_seven.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040215201829/http://clonehighusa.com/backstage/episode_notes/episode_seven.html|archivedate=2004-02-15|website=CloneHighUSA.com|date=2004-02-25|accessdate=2011-07-12}}</ref> All the original character designs were much different from what they would become even though the characters kept the same physical attributes and appearance. Each episode was budgeted at approximately $750,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2003/feb/17/entertainment/et-solomon17|title=Freshman animators|website=articles.latimes.com|date=2003-02-27|accessdate=2011-07-27|first=Charles|last=Solomon|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121107173707/http://articles.latimes.com/2003/feb/17/entertainment/et-solomon17|archive-date=2012-11-07|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDespite being an [[MTV]]/[[Nelvana]] Co-production, the show was co-produced with [[Touchstone Television]], marking as Disney's third adult animated series after ''[[The PJs]]'' and ''[[Clerks: The Animated Series]]''.\n\nIn forming the show's central cast, they found themselves limited in the number of historical figures they could depict, in consideration with avoiding \"litigious estates\" (such as the families of [[Albert Einstein]] or [[Marilyn Monroe]]) and keeping in mind the viewership of MTV.<ref name=\"grantland\"/> The show also parodies teen dramas, such as ''[[Dawson's Creek]]'', which Lord and Miller watched in preparation to create the series.<ref name=\"grantland\"/> The show's art design has been described as angular and \"evocative of [[UPA (animation studio)|UPA]] at its best.\"<ref name=\"Hal205\"/> It is characterized by a flat and very stylized appearance resembling the animation used in [[Cartoon Network]] animated series from the 1990s and early 2000s, such as ''[[Dexter's Laboratory]]'', ''[[The Powerpuff Girls]]'' and ''[[Time Squad]]'' (Lord and Miller specifically cited ''[[Samurai Jack]]'' as an influence). The character designs were all done by Carey Yost, known for his work on ''Dexter's Laboratory'', ''Samurai Jack'', ''The Powerpuff Girls'', ''[[The Ren & Stimpy Show]]'', and ''[[Timon & Pumbaa (TV series)|Timon & Pumbaa]]''. The characters and backgrounds were [[traditional animation|traditionally drawn]], and frames and cels were frequently recycled. Co-creator Chris Miller explained, \"We like the snappy pose-to-pose animation, more for reasons of comic timing than anything else. Things that aren't expected are funnier: If an anvil's going to fall on your head, it had better not take more than three seconds. That's why we like the quick pose-to-pose stuff. For scenes with more emotional content, the characters move a little slower and more fluidly\". Phil Lord added, \"But we never want the viewer to be paying attention to the animation, because it's there to serve the jokes and the story. We strip out extraneous movements, because we don't want to draw your eye to anything that's not part of a joke.\" Gandhi is the most animated character on the show; he requires twice as many story-board poses as any other character.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clonehighusa.com/backstage/funfacts/fun_facts.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080602070504/http://www.clonehighusa.com/backstage/funfacts/fun_facts.html|archivedate=2008-06-02|title=Clone High Fun Facts|accessdate=2011-07-28}}</ref>\n\nThe series was produced by [[Bill Lawrence (TV producer)|Bill Lawrence]], who also produced ''[[Scrubs (TV series)|Scrubs]]'', ''[[Spin City]]'' and ''[[Cougar Town]]''. Many ''Scrubs'' alumni, such as [[Zach Braff]], [[Donald Faison]], [[Sarah Chalke]], [[John C. McGinley]], [[Neil Flynn]], and [[Christa Miller]], provided the voices of characters in ''Clone High''.\n\n''Clone High'' was notable for subtle jokes hidden in the animation. There is an image of a [[dolphin]] hidden in almost every episode. The use of dolphins (sounds or images) would be later featured in Lord and Miller's later work. In the episode \"Raisin the Stakes\", there were numerous hidden messages, which appeared to be a parody of [[subliminal messaging]].\n\n==Controversy and cancellation==\nAn article in ''[[Maxim (magazine)|Maxim]]'' Magazine depicting [[Mahatma Gandhi]] being beaten up by a muscular man sparked outrage in India.<ref name=\"youtube.com\">{{cite web |author=\"\" |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XHlhFghZ1gM |title=Clone High NEW Behind the Scenes Discussion |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=2010-12-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110914092820/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XHlhFghZ1gM |archive-date=2011-09-14 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''Clone High'' was caught in a crossfire when citizens in the country conducted internet searches on the Maxim article but also found out about the show's Gandhi character on MTV's website. This sparked an outrage in India over the show's depiction of Gandhi.<ref name=\"youtube.com\"/> On January 30, 2003, the 55th anniversary of [[Attempts to assassinate Mahatma Gandhi|Mahatma Gandhi's assassination]], approximately 150 protesters (including [[Member of Parliament#India|members of parliament]]) gathered in [[New Delhi]] and vowed to fast in response to ''Clone High''.<ref>{{cite news | first=Ashok | last=Sharma | title=MTV's Gandhi 'insult' outrages Indian MPs | date=2003-01-31 | publisher=The Guardian | url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2003/jan/31/pressandpublishing.india | location=London | access-date=2016-12-14 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217024444/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2003/jan/31/pressandpublishing.india | archive-date=2017-02-17 | url-status=live }}</ref> Tom Freston, the head of [[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]] (owner of MTV), was visiting the network's India branch and was \"trapped in the building\", according to Miller. In 2014, he recalled that protestors \"basically threatened that they'd revoke MTV's broadcasting license in India if they didn't take the show off the air\".<ref name=\"grantland\"/>\n\nMTV offered a quick apology, stating that \"''Clone High'' was created and intended for an American audience\", and \"we recognize and respect that various cultures may view this programming differently, and we regret any offense taken by the content in the show\".<ref name=\"Grossberg\">{{cite news | first=Josh | last=Grossberg | title=MTV Apologizes for Gandhi Goofing | date=2003-01-31 | publisher=E! Online | url=http://www.eonline.com/news/article/index.jsp?uuid=c520a80c-f8ba-4e92-9355-cbbf7c15647a | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080121191507/http://www.eonline.com/news/article/index.jsp?uuid=c520a80c-f8ba-4e92-9355-cbbf7c15647a | archivedate=2008-01-21}}</ref> Miller would later recall that executives at MTV enjoyed the show, and asked for the duo to pitch a second season without Gandhi. Lord and Miller's two potential versions of a second season included one that made no mention of Gandhi's absence, and another that revealed that the character was, in fact, a clone of actor [[Gary Coleman]] all along, and the show continued as normal. \"We pitched that, and it went up to the top at Viacom again and it got a big no,\" he remembered.<ref name=\"grantland\">{{cite web|url=http://grantland.com/hollywood-prospectus/phil-lord-and-chris-miller-of-the-lego-movie-look-back-on-clone-high-their-cult-classic-mtv-cartoon/|date=February 7, 2014|title=Phil Lord and Chris Miller of 'The Lego Movie' Look Back on 'Clone High,' Their Cult Classic MTV Cartoon|author=Amos Barshad|publisher=[[Grantland]]|accessdate=March 29, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402150328/http://grantland.com/hollywood-prospectus/phil-lord-and-chris-miller-of-the-lego-movie-look-back-on-clone-high-their-cult-classic-mtv-cartoon/|archive-date=2015-04-02|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Future==\nLord and Miller have since stated that they have \"considered\" a film adaptation of the series. In 2014, they explained that as they at that time were under contract with [[20th Century Fox Television|Fox]], Lawrence had a television deal at [[Warner Bros. Television]], and the rights to ''Clone High'' were owned by MTV/Viacom, it would be difficult to resurrect the show.<ref name=\"collider\">{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/clone-high-movie-phil-lord-chris-miller/|date=June 12, 2014|title=Phil Lord and Chris Miller Say They're Discussing the Possibility of a CLONE HIGH Movie; Talk Potential Rating and More|author=Adam Chitwood|publisher=Collider.com|accessdate=March 29, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402124455/http://collider.com/clone-high-movie-phil-lord-chris-miller/|archive-date=2015-04-02|url-status=live}}</ref> References to ''Clone High'' are present in their later productions: the duo admitted many jokes in ''[[22 Jump Street]]'' were \"ripped off straight from ''Clone High''\", and Forte also voices a [[Lego]] version of Lincoln in ''[[The Lego Movie]]''.<ref name=\"grantland\"/> In a 2014 [[Grantland]] article, the two joked that \"our entire career has just been about getting ''Clone High'' back on the air\".<ref name=\"grantland\"/> In the 2018 film ''[[Spider-Man: Into the Spider-Verse]],'' there's a movie poster featuring Abe and JFK in [[Miles Morales]]' universe titled \"Clone College.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.avclub.com/in-the-spider-verse-theres-a-shaun-of-the-dead-sequel-1831083941|title=In the Spider-Verse, there's a Shaun Of The Dead sequel and a Clone High movie|date=December 13, 2018|accessdate=December 13, 2018|website=[[The A.V. Club]]|author=Sam Barsanti}}</ref>\n\n==Episodes==\n===Season 1 (2002\u201303)===\n{{Episode table\n|background=#7ea6e2\n|overall=\n|season=\n|title=\n|writer=\n|airdate=\n|airdateT=Canadian air date<ref name=crtclogs>{{cite web|url=ftp://support.crtc.gc.ca/logs/|title=Television Program Logs|date=2016-03-02|publisher=[[Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission]]|archive-url=https://archive.org/details/support_crtc_gc_ca15052016|archive-date=2016-05-16|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|altdate=\n|altdateT=American air date<ref>http://www.mtv.com/shows/clone-high/episode-guide</ref>\n|country=US\n|episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=1\n |EpisodeNumber2=1\n |Title=Escape to Beer Mountain: A Rope of Sand\n |Aux1=[[Phil Lord and Christopher Miller|Phil Lord & Christopher Miller]] and [[Bill Lawrence (TV producer)|Bill Lawrence]]\n |OriginalAirDate=  {{Start date|2002|11|02}}\n |AltDate= January 20, 2003\n |ShortSummary=In desperation to get with the beautiful and popular Cleopatra, Abe Lincoln is hoping to make a move on her at JFK's party. JFK, however, also has the hots for her and will only let Abe come on the condition that he brings the beer. Meanwhile, Joan of Arc, who is trying to win Abe's heart, starts up a Teen Crisis Hotline in an attempt to impress him with her commitment to community service; their mutual friend, Gandhi, who accidentally agrees to help with the hotline, forwards the calls to his cell phone so he can go to the party. All the while, Principal Scudworth and Mr. Butlertron attempt to crash the party so as to better understand the students.<br>''Notable Guest Stars:'' [[Michael J. Fox]] as Gandhi's remaining kidney, [[Andy Dick]] as [[Vincent Van Gogh|Van Gogh]], [[Donald Faison]] as [[George Washington Carver]].\n| LineColor = 7ea6e2  }}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=2\n |EpisodeNumber2=2\n |Title=Episode Two: Election Blu-Galoo\n |Aux1=Phil Lord & Christopher Miller\n |OriginalAirDate=  {{Start date|2002|11|03}}\n |AltDate= January 27, 2003\n |ShortSummary=Cleo discovers she cannot continue to run for Student Body President because of term limits, so she convinces JFK to run on her behalf, and when Abe sees that Cleo appreciates leaders, he decides to run as well. But students of Clone High do not care about real issues, and many are infatuated with JFK; Abe employs a corporate sponsor, \"X-Stream Blu,\" to jazz up his campaign. The only problem is that Gandhi becomes horribly addicted to this mysterious food product.<br>''Notable guest stars'': [[Marilyn Manson]] as himself, [[Sarah Chalke]] as X-stream Erin, [[Donald Faison]] as X-stream Bob, [[Zach Braff]] as X-stream Mike.\n| LineColor = 7ea6e2  }}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=3\n |EpisodeNumber2=3\n |Title=A.D.D.: The Last 'D' is for Disorder\n |Aux1=[[Tom Martin (writer)|Tom Martin]]\n |OriginalAirDate=  {{Start date|2002|11|10}}\n |AltDate= February 3, 2003\n |ShortSummary=When Gandhi is diagnosed with Attention Deficit Disorder (A.D.D.), the students of Clone High begin to ostracize him. Abe must decide whether to please Cleo by doing the same, or to stand up for his \"best dude 4 ever\" and lose any chance of being with Cleo. Meanwhile, Joan struggles with living up to the legacy of her 15th century clone mother, and begins hearing strange religious voices in her head. Also, Principal Scudworth starts wearing Mr. Butlertron's sweater vest, in the belief that it gives him the power to relate to the students of Clone High.<br>''Notable guest stars'': [[Zach Braff]] as [[Paul Revere]], [[Donald Faison]] as Toots, [[Tom Green]] as himself.\n| LineColor = 7ea6e2  }}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=4\n |EpisodeNumber2=4\n |Title=Film Fest: Tears of a Clone\n |Aux1=Erica Rivinoja\n |OriginalAirDate=  {{Start date|2002|11|17}}\n |AltDate= February 10, 2003\n |ShortSummary=When Abe decides to organize a Clone High Student Film Festival, he spends much time working on a movie about a misunderstood football-playing giraffe; Cleo stars in an autobiographical epic about how difficult it is to be as perfect and glamorous as her; Joan directs an avant-garde film which expresses her love for Abe through psychoanalytic dream imagery; and Gandhi and George Washington Carver work together to make a hilarious mixed-race buddy cop action comedy called Black and Tan. Meanwhile, JFK plans a film but never manages to leave the casting couch with his various wouldbe female co-stars, and Principal Scudworth starts to panic when his bosses on the Secret Board of Shadowy Figures invite themselves to his house for dinner, but thankfully for him, Mr. Butlertron is there to save the day.<br>''Notable guest stars'': [[Donald Faison]] as George Washington Carver, [[Neil Flynn]] as Boy auditioning for Abe's film.\n| LineColor = 7ea6e2  }}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=5\n |EpisodeNumber2=5\n |Title=Sleep of Faith: La Rue D'Awakening\n |Aux1=[[Murray Miller]] & [[Judah Miller]]\n |OriginalAirDate=  {{Start date|2002|12|01}}\n |AltDate= February 17, 2003\n |ShortSummary=The PXJTs (a parody of the SATs) are right around the corner, but Abe is losing sleep running errands for his beloved Cleo. When Joan keeps trying to warn Abe about his sleep deprivation, a secret of hers is uncovered. Also, Gandhi, overwhelmed by the pressure of studying, decides not take the test and become a trucker instead. Mr. Butlertron and an old foe battle it out for the last time.<br>''Notable guest stars'': [[John C. McGinley]] as Doug Prepcourse.\n| LineColor = 7ea6e2  }}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=6\n |EpisodeNumber2=6\n |Title=Homecoming: A Shot in D'Arc\n |Aux1=Eric Kentoff\n |OriginalAirDate=  {{Start date|2002|11|24}}\n |AltDate= February 24, 2003\n |ShortSummary=Since the CHHS basketball team refuses to allow girls or animals to play, the athletic Joan decides to cleverly disguise herself as \"John D'Arc\", becoming the star player. Cleo then falls for D'Arc, making team-captain Abe \"Weakest\"-Lincoln jealous. But Cleo's not the only one falling for John, as fellow athlete JFK finds himself having confusingly sexual feelings about the whole affair. Meanwhile, Gandhi and Genghis Khan kidnap the mascot of Clone High's rival school, Genetically Engineered Superhuman High.<br>''Notable guest stars'': [[Chris Berman]] as himself, [[Dan Patrick]] as himself, [[Neil Flynn]] as [[Julius Caesar]].\n| LineColor = 7ea6e2  }}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=7\n |EpisodeNumber2=7\n |Title=Plane Crazy: Gate Expectations\n |Aux1=Tom Martin\n |OriginalAirDate=  {{Start date|2002|12|08}}\n |AltDate= March 3, 2003\n |ShortSummary=Abe and Cleo's new relationship is threatened when she is picked to be on a Canadian Spring Break Dance show, hosted by Ashley Angel from O-Town. Meanwhile, Gandhi becomes an international rap sensation with the help of JFK as his manager. Also, Principal Scudworth is constantly being tricked by a pesky skunk.<br>''Notable guest stars'': [[Ashley Parker Angel|Ashley Angel]] as himself, [[Neil Flynn]] as [[Buddy Holly]].\n| LineColor = 7ea6e2  }}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=8\n |EpisodeNumber2=8\n |Title=A Room of One's Clone: The Pie of the Storm\n |Aux1=Adam Pava\n |OriginalAirDate=  {{Start date|2002|12|15}}\n |AltDate=<small>N/A</small>\n |ShortSummary=Storm's-a-brewin' when Joan's house burns down and her family has no choice but to move in with Cleo's, where conflict ensues; Abe attends a Conflict Mediation Seminar to learn how to more effectively resolve disputes between the two. Gandhi and JFK find themselves in escalating arguments. Meanwhile, Mr. Butlertron becomes jealous when Principal Scudworth forms a relationship with a robotic toy dog.<br>''Notable guest stars'': [[Donald Faison]] as [[Martin Luther King Jr.]] and Toots, [[Neil Flynn]] as [[Moses]].\n| LineColor = 7ea6e2  }}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=9\n |EpisodeNumber2=9\n |Title=Raisin the Stakes: A Rock Opera in Three Acts\n |Aux1=Phil Lord & Christopher Miller\n |OriginalAirDate=  {{Start date|2003|01|12}}\n |AltDate= March 10, 2003\n |ShortSummary=After an anti-drugs assembly at the school, a rumor goes around that one can get high smoking raisins, leading the clones to embark on a musical, mystical journey of intoxication and irresponsibly long hair. Sober Joan is trying to keep Abe from turning into a drugged-out hippie, while Principal Scudworth and the PTA build a giant wall in an attempt to fence the students in. Meanwhile, Gandhi goes on a raisined-out subconscious mindtrip where he encounters a hummingbird-unicorn-donkey creature, a two-headed [[Mary-Kate and Ashley Olsen|Olsen Twins]] monster, a talking Italian pencil, and a stereotypically Australian dragon, on his quest to rescue a princess who he believes will have sex with him.<br>''Notable guest stars'': [[Jack Black]] as Larry Hardcore/the Pusher.\n| LineColor = 7ea6e2  }}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=10\n |EpisodeNumber2=10\n |Title=Litter Kills: Litterally\n |Aux1=[[Murray Miller]] & [[Judah Miller]]\n |OriginalAirDate=  {{Start date|2003|01|19}}\n |AltDate=<small>N/A</small>\n |ShortSummary=JFK's long time best friend, Ponce de Le\u00f3n, literally dies, causing JFK to sink into a spiral of depression. This causes tension between Abe and Cleo, who dutifully attempts to comfort JFK, her former boyfriend, during his grief. Meanwhile, Gandhi is mistakenly sent to death row where he has trouble getting high fives, but makes new friends in the showers.<br>''Notable guest stars'': [[Luke Perry]] as [[Juan Ponce de Le\u00f3n|Ponce]], [[Neil Flynn]] as Glenn the Janitor and Julius Caesar.\n| LineColor = 7ea6e2  }}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=13\n |EpisodeNumber2=11\n |Title=Snowflake Day: A Very Special Holiday Episode\n |Aux1=Erica Rivinoja\n |OriginalAirDate=  {{Start date|2003|04|13}}<ref>{{IMDb episode|0542914|Snowflake Day: A Very Special Holiday Episode| LineColor = 7ea6e2  }}</ref>\n |AltDate=<small>N/A</small>\n |ShortSummary=It's the politically correct Snowflake Day season, and everyone is in the holiday spirit, except for Joan, who is against the commercialism of the made-up holiday. But a homeless urchin who \"may or may not be\" pop sensation Mandy Moore teaches Joan an important lesson. Meanwhile, Abe and Gandhi attempt to invent and market an interesting device, so that Abe will have money to buy Cleo an expensive Snowflake Day gift.<br>''Notable guest stars'': [[Mandy Moore]] as herself.<br>''Note'': This episode begins with a parody of the 1973 \"A [[CBS]] Special Presentation\" bumper.\n| LineColor = 7ea6e2  }}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=11\n |EpisodeNumber2=12\n |Title=Makeover, Makeover, Makeover: The Makeover Episode\n |Aux1=Eric Kentoff\n |OriginalAirDate= {{Start date|2003|01|26}}\n |AltDate=<small>N/A</small>\n |ShortSummary=With prom not too far away, Abe wants to ask his girlfriend, Cleo, but cannot stop thinking about Joan's prom date situation. Meanwhile, Gandhi goes on a desperate search for a date. So, Abe and Cleo each have a go at making over Joan for prom, JFK gives Gandhi a makeover, and Mr. B gives Scudworth a makeover to help him execute a sinister, evil plan to \"win\" the prom king vote.\n| LineColor = 7ea6e2  }}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=12\n |EpisodeNumber2=13\n |Title=Changes: The Big Prom: The Sex Romp: The Season Finale\n |Aux1=Phil Lord & Christopher Miller\n |OriginalAirDate= {{Start date|2003|03|02}}\n |AltDate=<small>N/A</small>\n |ShortSummary=As all the clones are preparing for the winter prom, Abe decides whether to ask Cleo or Joan; Gandhi concocts a brilliant plan to get dates for all the school geeks; and Principal Scudworth attempts to execute his sinister, evil plan, while the Secret Board of Shadowy Figures prepares to abduct the clones on prom night to advance their own evil plan.<br>''Notable guest stars'': [[John Stamos]] and [[Tommy Walter]] as themselves.\n| LineColor = 7ea6e2\n}}}}\n\n==Soundtrack==\nThe previous animated MTV series ''[[Daria]]'' and ''[[Beavis and Butt-head]]'' had used then-current [[popular music]] as a soundtrack, but, in contrast, ''Clone High'' featured a wide variety of music, usually exclusive to [[alternative rock]], [[indie rock]], [[midwest emo]], [[hardcore punk]] [[pop rock]], [[metalcore]], from mostly unknown and [[underground music|underground]] bands and musicians; a previous MTV animated series, ''[[Undergrads]]'', had also done this. Of these include [[Alkaline Trio]], [[American Football (band)|American Football]], [[Ritalin (band)|Ritalin]], [[Catch 22 (band)|Catch 22]], [[Ilya (band)|Ilya]], The Gentleman, Drex, [[Taking Back Sunday]], [[The Stereo]], Jo Davidson, [[Saves the Day]], [[Hot Rod Circuit]], [[Thursday (band)|Thursday]], Helicopter Helicopter, [[Owen (band)|Owen]], [[Dashboard Confessional]], [[Elf Power]], [[Abandoned Pools]], [[The Get Up Kids]], [[Mink Lungs]], [[Mates of State]], [[Snapcase]], [[The Mooney Suzuki]], [[Jon DeRosa]], [[Ephemera (band)|Ephemera]], Jinnrall, [[Avoid One Thing]], DJ Cellulitis, DJ Piccolo, [[Whippersnapper (band)|Whippersnapper]], [[Matt Pond PA]], Mad City and [[Ron \"Bumblefoot\" Thal|Bumblefoot]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/onair/clone_high/ |title=MTV.com - Onair - Clone High |date=2003-01-19 |accessdate=2010-12-06 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030119090212/http://www.mtv.com/onair/clone_high/ |archivedate=2003-01-19 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.clonehighusa.com/music/music_by_episode.html |title=CloneHighUSA.com |date=2003-01-04 |accessdate=2011-07-03 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030409053346/http://www.clonehighusa.com/music/music_by_episode.html |archivedate=2003-04-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The series' other background music and original score was written and produced by Scott Nickoley and Jamie Dunlap of Mad City Productions. Nickoley and Dunlap went on to score other shows such as ''[[South Park]]'', ''[[The Osbournes]]'' and ''[[Newlyweds: Nick and Jessica|Newlyweds]]''.\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Initial reviews===\nTelevision critics gave ''Clone High'' mixed reviews upon its 2002 premiere. On [[Metacritic]], which assigns a normalized rating out of 100 based on reviews from critics, the show has a score of 60, based on seven reviews, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|title=''Clone High, USA'' Reviews|url=https://metacritic.com/tv/clone-high-usa|publisher=[[Metacritic]] ([[CBS Interactive]])|accessdate=March 29, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402174808/http://www.metacritic.com/tv/clone-high-usa|archive-date=2015-04-02|url-status=live}}</ref> David Bianculli of the ''[[New York Daily News]]'' praised the series, commenting, \"In a year of variations and ripoffs of established themes and genres, it's a true original. It's also a cartoon, and is truly, outrageously bizarre.\"<ref name=\"nydn\">{{cite journal|author=Anita Gates|title=This Class Is One For The History Books|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/entertainment/class-history-books-article-1.672864|journal=[[New York Daily News]]|date=January 20, 2003|accessdate=March 29, 2015|pages=85|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402104555/http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/entertainment/class-history-books-article-1.672864|archive-date=2015-04-02|url-status=live}}</ref> The ''[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]''{{'s}} Rob Owen complimented the show: \"Yes, ''Clone High'' has the MTV-requisite sexual innuendo, but it's more clever than much of what passes for humor in prime time today. And like ''Scrubs'', it has heart, particularly when it comes to Abe and Joan.\"<ref name=\"post\">{{cite journal|author=Rob Owen|title=Historical figures sent back to the drawing board|url=http://old.post-gazette.com/tv/20030112clone0112fnp3.asp|journal=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|date=January 12, 2003|pages=D-3|accessdate=March 29, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402090311/http://old.post-gazette.com/tv/20030112clone0112fnp3.asp|archive-date=2015-04-02|url-status=live}}</ref> Anita Gates of ''[[The New York Times]]'' opined that \"the dialogue isn't always exactly funny, but it's smile worthy,\" observing, \"the characters are intriguing in a lightweight way but could lose their appeal fast.\"<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite web|author=Anita Gates|title=TELEVISION REVIEW; Kennedy and Lincoln, Wooing Cleopatra|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/01/20/arts/television-review-kennedy-and-lincoln-wooing-cleopatra.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=January 20, 2003|accessdate=March 29, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402195640/http://www.nytimes.com/2003/01/20/arts/television-review-kennedy-and-lincoln-wooing-cleopatra.html|archive-date=2015-04-02|url-status=live}}</ref> Scott Sandell of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' felt the show's debut episode lacking: \"The problem is that the first episode, which focuses on crushes and beer, doesn't quite live up to the obvious comedic potential behind the killer premise.\"<ref name=\"lat\">{{cite news|title=Peer pressure of historic proportions|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=January 20, 2003|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2003/jan/20/entertainment/et-sandell20|accessdate=November 8, 2010|first=Scott|last=Sandell|pages=C-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120820022705/http://articles.latimes.com/2003/jan/20/entertainment/et-sandell20|archive-date=2012-08-20|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]''{{'s}} Michael Farkash felt similarly, writing, \"The premise sounds intriguing, but what hatches in the first episode is a disappointing, weak strain of comic material, lacking the cunning, subversive quality of, say, ''[[South Park]]''.\"<ref name=\"hr\">{{cite news|title= Clone High, U.S.A. (TV Brief)|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=January 10, 2003|author=Michael Farkash}}</ref>\n\n===Retrospective reviews===\nBecause of the series' early cancellation in 2003, it quickly fell into obscurity, especially in the US. However, it has garnered a large fanbase throughout the Internet and still occasionally airs reruns on [[Teletoon]]'s ''[[Teletoon at Night]]'' (formerly Teletoon Detour) block and formerly aired on [[MTV Canada|MTV]], [[MTV2 Canada|MTV2]] and [[MTV2 (Canada)|Razer]] (now MTV2) in Canada. [[MuchMusic|Much]] in Canada has also aired reruns of ''Clone High'' for a short time.\n\nHeather Marulli, of the website [[Television Without Pity]], called the series \"a mini-masterpiece of the animated genre; an opus to the primetime cartoon\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Marulli |first=Heather |title=Tonight, On A Very Special Clone High... |url=http://www.televisionwithoutpity.com/brilliantbutcancelled/2009/12/tonight-on-a-very-special-clon.php |publisher=televisionwithoutpity.com |accessdate=2009-12-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091205095712/http://www.televisionwithoutpity.com/brilliantbutcancelled/2009/12/tonight-on-a-very-special-clon.php |archivedate=2009-12-05 }}</ref>\n\nDavid Broermann, from the website Freakin' Awesome Network, gave the series an \"A+\", saying it has \"some really really good character development and depth\" and an \"amazing soundtrack\" He notes the fantastic use of multiple running gags keeping viewers on their toes.<ref>{{cite news |last=Broermann |first=David |title=Dave the Dave's Review: Oh Wesley (Clone High) |url=http://www.freakinawesomenetwork.net/2011/09/dave-the-daves-review-review-oh-wesley/ |date=2011-09-10 |accessdate=2012-05-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116110113/http://www.freakinawesomenetwork.net/2011/09/dave-the-daves-review-review-oh-wesley/ |archive-date=2014-01-16 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nCurrently, the show has an 8.7 rating on [[TV.com]],<ref>{{cite news | title=Clone High, USA on TV.com | url=http://www.tv.com/shows/clone-high/ | access-date=2012-10-02 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104151912/http://www.tv.com/shows/clone-high/ | archive-date=2012-11-04 | url-status=live }}</ref> has an 8.1 rating on [[IMDb]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0305011/ |title=Clone High (TV Series 2002\u20132003) - IMDb<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2018-06-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180318204119/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0305011/ |archive-date=2018-03-18 |url-status=live }}</ref> and is listed as #5 on [[IGN]]'s \"Reader Choice: Top Animated Series\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Fowler |first=Matt |url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/964/964034p3.html |title=Readers' Choice: IGN's Top Animated Series - TV Feature at IGN |publisher=Tv.ign.com |accessdate=2010-12-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100317123722/http://tv.ign.com/articles/964/964034p3.html |archive-date=2010-03-17 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nJesse David Fox of ''[[Vulture (blog)|Vulture]]'', in a retrospective piece on the series, wrote that \"''Clone High'' still holds up more than a decade later as a brilliantly funny, completely nuts, surprisingly heartfelt, tonally inventive masterpiece.\"<ref name=\"vulture\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2014/02/clone-high-lego-movie-phil-lord-christopher-miller.html|date=February 13, 2014|title=Remembering The LEGO Movie Directors' Superb TV Show, Clone High|author=Jesse David Fox|publisher=[[Vulture (blog)|Vulture]]|accessdate=March 29, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402110909/http://www.vulture.com/2014/02/clone-high-lego-movie-phil-lord-christopher-miller.html|archive-date=2015-04-02|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Home media==\nThe two-disc DVD complete series boxset was released in Canada by [[Nelvana]] with the help of [[Teletoon]]. The DVD contains the complete series, including the five episodes which did not originally air in the United States.\n{{Television home release\n| title = Clone High: The Complete Series\n| color = 7ea6e2\n| set_details =\n* 13 episodes\n* 2-disc [[DVD]] set\n* 286 minutes\n* [[Dolby Digital]]:\n** English\n** French\n| special_features =\n* Video clips of:\n** Christopher Miller performing as \"Mr. B\"\n** Phil Lord performing as \"Principal Scudworth\"\n** Bill Lawrence, an executive producer, in a hot tub\n** Tom Martin describing the writing process\n* Video footage of live-action cat depicted in \"Raisin the Skates: A Rock Opera in 3 Acts\"\n| region1 = {{Start date|2005|9|20}}\n| region2 = <small>N/A</small>\n| region4 = Unknown (currently out of print)\n}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Dolly (sheep)|Dolly the sheep]]\n*''[[Afterschool Charisma]]''\n*[[Human cloning]]\n*''[[Total Drama]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Notes===\n* {{cite book |last=Erickson |first=Hal |authorlink=Hal Erickson (author) |year=2005 |title=Television Cartoon Shows |edition=2nd|volume=1 |publisher=McFardland and Company|isbn=07864-2255-6}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n\n* {{official website|URL=https://web.archive.org/web/20050315055511/http://www.corusent.com/corporate/press_room/pressReleaseDetail.asp?id=785}}\n* {{IMDb title|305011}}\n* {{tv.com show|clone-high}}\n* {{Cite web 