:American adult animated comic science fiction television series]]\n[[Category:American flash adult animated television series]]\n[[Category:Bangsian fantasy]]\n[[Category:Canadian adult animated drama television series]]\n[[Category:Canadian adult animated comic science fiction television series]]\n[[Category:Canadian flash animated television series]]\n[[Category:Cartoon controversies]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Buddy Holly]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Catherine the Great]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Eva Per\u00f3n]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Joan of Arc]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of John F. Kennedy]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Mahatma Gandhi]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Marie Antoinette]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Marie Curie]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Martin Luther King Jr.]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Napoleon]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Vincent van Gogh]]\n[[Category:Depictions of Cleopatra on television]]\n[[Category:Depictions of Genghis Khan on television]]\n[[Category:Depictions of Julius Caesar on television]]\n[[Category:Fictional depictions of Abraham Lincoln in television]]\n[[Category:LGBT-related animated series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:MTV cartoons]]\n[[Category:Teletoon original series]]\n[[Category:Television controversies in Canada]]\n[[Category:Television controversies in the United States]]\n[[Category:Television series about cloning]]\n[[Category:Television series by ABC Studios]]\n[[Category:Television series by Nelvana]]\n[[Category:Television series created by Bill Lawrence (TV producer)]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about teenagers]]\n[[Category:Teen animated television series]]\n", "name_user": "DracoLumina17", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clone_High"}
{"title_page": "Avi Weiss", "text_new": "{{Cleanup rewrite|overly polemic, with entire paragraphs dedicated to defending/attacking him (lengthy quotes verging on Copyvio). Just state the facts.|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox Jewish leader\n| honorific-prefix = Rabbi\n| name             = Avi Weiss\n| honorific-suffix = \n| title            = \n| image            = Rabbi Weiss Speaking.JPG\n| caption          = Rabbi Weiss, 2007\n| synagogue        = [[Hebrew Institute of Riverdale]]\n| synagogueposition = \n| yeshiva          = [[Yeshivat Chovevei Torah]]<br />[[Yeshivat Maharat]]\n| yeshivaposition  = \n| organisation     = \n| organisationposition = \n| began            = \n| ended            = \n| predecessor      = \n| successor        = \n| rabbi            = \n| rebbe            = \n| kohan            = \n| hazzan           = \n| rank             = \n| other_post       = \n<!---------- Personal details ---------->\n| birth_name       = Avraham Weiss<br />{{Hebrew|\u05d0\u05d1\u05e8\u05d4\u05dd \u05d7\u05d9\u05d9\u05dd \u05d9\u05d5\u05e1\u05e3 \u05d4\u05db\u05d4\u05df \u05d5\u05d5\u05d9\u05d9\u05e1}}\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1944|6|24}}\n| birth_place      = \n| nationality      = American\n| denomination     = [[Open Orthodox]]\n| residence        = \n| dynasty          = \n| parents          = \n| spouse           = \n| children         = \n| occupation       = [[Rabbi]], author\n| profession       = \n| alma_mater       = [[Yeshiva University]], [[RIETS]]\n| semicha          = [[Rabbi Isaac Elchanan Theological Seminary]], 1968\n| signature        = \n}}\n\n'''Avraham Haim Yosef (Avi) haCohen Weiss''' ({{lang-he-n|\u05d0\u05d1\u05e8\u05d4\u05dd \u05d7\u05d9\u05d9\u05dd \u05d9\u05d5\u05e1\u05e3 \u05d4\u05db\u05d4\u05df \u05d5\u05d5\u05d9\u05d9\u05e1}}; born June 24, 1944) is an American [[open Orthodox Judaism|open Orthodox]] ordained [[rabbi]], author, teacher, lecturer, and activist who heads the [[Hebrew Institute of Riverdale]] in [[The Bronx]], New York, from which he retired in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://forward.com/articles/207457/rabbi-avi-weiss-progressive-voice-in-orthodoxy-ste/|title=Rabbi Avi Weiss, Progressive Voice in Orthodoxy, Steps Down From Pulpit|author=Forward Staff|date=16 October 2014|work=The Forward}}</ref> He is the founder of [[Yeshivat Chovevei Torah]], a [[yeshiva|rabbinical seminary]] he refers to as \"Open Orthodox\", a term he coined to describe an offshoot of [[Orthodoxy]], founder of [[Yeshivat Maharat]] for Orthodox women,<ref name=\"nymag\"/> co-founder of the [[International Rabbinical Fellowship]], an Open Orthodox rabbinical association founded as a liberal alternative to the Modern Orthodox [[Rabbinical Council of America]],<ref>{{cite news | work=The Jewish Daily Forward| last= Nathan-Kazis |first= Josh | title= Top Modern Orthodox Rabbi Michael Broyde Admits Fake Name Scheme| url=http://forward.com/articles/174777/top-modern-orthodox-rabbi-michael-broyde-admits-fa/| date=April 12, 2013| accessdate=July 31, 2013}}</ref> and founder of the grassroots organization Coalition for Jewish Concerns \u2013 Amcha.\nHe received his rabbinical ordination at the Rabbi Isaac Elchanan Theological Seminary (Yeshiva University) in 1968.\n\nIn 2013, ''[[Newsweek]]'' ranked him the 10th most prominent rabbi in the United States,<ref name=\"Top13\">{{cite news | url= http://www.thedailybeast.com/galleries/2013/03/21/america-s-top-50-rabbis-for-2013-photos.html#c7a234a8-c2aa-46ad-8c11-638bac4c2eab| title=America's Top 50 Rabbis for 2013|work=The Daily Beast | accessdate=July 31, 2013}}</ref> climbing from number 11 in 2012 and number 12 in 2011,<ref name=\"Top50\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/galleries/2012/04/02/america-s-top-50-rabbis-for-2012.html#slide11|title=America's Top 50 Rabbis for 2012|work=The Daily Beast}}</ref> after being ranked number 18 in 2010.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.newsweek.com/2010/06/28/the-50-most-influential-rabbis-in-america.html#|title=The 50 Most Influential Rabbis in America|last1=Lynton|first1=Michael|last2=Ginsberg|first2=Gary|date=June 28, 2010|accessdate=April 14, 2011|publisher=newsweek.com}}</ref>\n\nOn June 29, 2015, Weiss resigned from the [[Rabbinical Council of America]]. He resigned before he likely would have been removed as he was denounced as an apikores, which means a heretic, by many of the leading members of the rabbinate. The Traditional Orthodox communities view his movement as neo-conservaitve and far removed from orthdoxy.<ref>{{cite web |title=Will The RCA Expel Rabbi Avi Weiss Over \u2018Orthodox Woman Rabbi\u2019 |url=https://www.theyeshivaworld.com/news/general/49447/will-the-rca-expel-rabbi-avi-weiss-over-orthodox-woman-rabbi-aka-maharatrabbah.html |website=Yeshiva World |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|title = Rabbi Avi Weiss quits Rabbinical Council of America in protest - Jewish World News|url = http://www.haaretz.com/jewish-world/jewish-world-news/1.663608|accessdate = 2015-06-30|last = JTA}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Newly minted female Orthodox rabbis to be called 'rabba' - Jewish World News|url = http://www.haaretz.com/jewish-world/jewish-world-news/.premium-1.660857}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = In protest, Avi Weiss quits Rabbinical Council of America|url = http://www.timesofisrael.com/in-protest-avi-weiss-quits-rabbinical-council-of-america/|accessdate = 2015-06-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Avi Weiss Quits Rabbinic Group in Flap Over School - Breaking News|url = http://forward.com/news/breaking-news/311099/avi-weiss-quits-rabbinic-group-in-flap-over-school/|accessdate = 2015-06-30}}</ref>\n\nOn November 3, 2015, the Moetzes of [[Agudath Israel of America]] declared Open Orthodoxy, [[Yeshivat Chovevei Torah]], Yeshivat Maharat and other affiliated entities to be similar to other dissident movements throughout Jewish history in having rejected basic tenets of Judaism.<ref name=\"Hamodia\">{{cite web|url=http://hamodia.com/2015/11/03/moetzes-open-orthodoxy-not-a-form-of-torah-judaism/|title=Moetzes: 'Open Orthodoxy' Not a Form of Torah Judaism|work=Hamodia}}</ref><ref name=\"The Jerusalem Post - JPost.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jpost.com/Diaspora/Breach-in-US-Orthodox-Judaism-grows-as-haredi-body-rejects-Open-Orthodoxy-institutions-431929|title=Breach in US Orthodox Judaism grows as haredi body rejects 'Open Orthodoxy' institutions|work=The Jerusalem Post - JPost.com}}</ref><ref name=\"Josh Nathan-Kazis\">{{cite web|url=http://forward.com/news/323887/agudath-rabbis-declare-war-on-open-orthodoxy/|title=Avi Weiss Defends 'Open Orthodoxy' as Agudah Rabbis Declare War|author=Josh Nathan-Kazis|date=3 November 2015|work=The Forward}}</ref>\n\n== Hebrew Institute of Riverdale ==\n{{Main|Hebrew Institute of Riverdale}}\nThe Hebrew Institute of Riverdale was founded in 1971 in a boiler room of the Whitehall Building off the [[Henry Hudson Parkway]] by former members of the Hebrew Institute of [[University Heights, Bronx|University Heights]] in the Bronx who had moved to Riverdale. Weiss, who had finished his training at [[Yeshiva University]] a few years earlier, became the synagogue's rabbi in 1973.<ref name=\"Olitzky 1996\">{{cite book|last1=Olitzky|first1=Kerry M.|authorlink=Kerry Olitzky|last2=Raphael|first2=Marc Lee|title=The American Synagogue: A Historical Dictionary and Sourcebook|publisher=Greenwood Press|year=1996|pages=223\u2013224}}</ref> The congregation has grown to 850 families, and has served as a platform for Weiss's rabbinical advocacy.<ref name=\"nymag\">{{cite news |url= http://nymag.com/news/features/67145/ |title=The Rabbi and the Rabba|last=Pogrebin |first=Abigail|date=July 11, 2010|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |accessdate=April 14, 2011}}</ref> In October 2014, Weiss announced that he would step down from his pulpit effective mid-2015. In July 2015 Rabbi Steven Exler became HIR's senior rabbi and Rabbi Weiss continues on its staff.<ref>[https://archive.today/20141018220455/http://www.jta.org/2014/10/17/news-opinion/united-states/rabbi-avi-weiss-to-step-down-as-rabbi-of-hebrew-institute-of-riverdale Rabbi Avi Weiss to step down as rabbi of Hebrew Institute of Riverdale]</ref>\n\n== Open Orthodoxy (Neo-Conservatism) ==\n{{Main|Open Orthodoxy (Neo-Conservatism)}}\nWeiss coined the term \"Open Orthodoxy\" in 1997 to describe a form of Modern Orthodoxy that emphasizes [[halakha]], the collective body of Jewish law, intellectual openness, a spiritual dimension, a broad concern for all Jews, and a more expansive role for women.<ref name=\"GRosenblatt\"/> He views halakha as being more flexible and open to innovation than his more traditional counterparts in Orthodox Judaism. He states that all Orthodox Judaism, including Open Orthodoxy, fundamentally differs from [[Conservative Judaism]] in three areas. First, unlike Conservative Judaism,\n*Orthodox Jews believe that the [[Torah]] was given by God at [[Mount Sinai]] in its current form. Second,\n*Orthodoxy believes that \"legal authority is cumulative, and that a contemporary ''[[posek]]'' [decider] can only issue judgments based on a full history of Jewish legal precedent\", whereas Conservative Jews believe \"precedent provides illustrations of possible positions rather than binding law. Conservatism, therefore, remains free to select whichever position within the prior history appeals to it\". Third,\n*Orthodoxy is characterized by ritually-observant members who \"meticulously keep [[Shabbat]] (the Sabbath), [[Kashrut]] (the Dietary Laws), [[Niddah|Taharat ha-Mishpaha]] (the Laws of Family Purity), and [[Jewish services|pray]] three times a day\", whereas Conservative Judaism \"is generally not composed of ritually observant Jews. Thus, only in our community if a 'permissive custom' is accepted, can it be meaningful.\"<ref>{{cite web | url =http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Open+orthodoxy!+A+modern+Orthodox+rabbi's+creed.-a020583577 | title =Open orthodoxy! A modern Orthodox rabbi's creed |work=Judaism: A Journal of Jewish Life & Thought|publisher=[[American Jewish Congress]]|date=Fall 1997|last=Weiss |first=Avi}}</ref>\n\nMore traditional rabbis have opposed this approach. Rabbi [[Steven Pruzansky]], a trustee of the [[Rabbinical Council of America]] (RCA) on the Board of the [[Beth Din of America]],<ref>{{cite news | title=U.S. rabbi faces dissent for slamming Obama| last= Maltz |first=Judy | date=November 16, 2012 | work=Haaretz| accessdate= July 31, 2013 | url=http://www.haaretz.com/jewish-world/jewish-world-features/u-s-rabbi-faces-dissent-for-slamming-obama.premium-1.478303#}}</ref> argues that Weiss' approach closely resembles early 20th century American Conservative Judaism and in his opinion would more aptly be called \"Neo-Conservative\" rather than \"Orthodox\" Judaism. Concluding an opinion piece in Matzav.com he states: {{Quote|text=clarity and honesty at least demand that we recognize before our eyes the creation of a new movement in Jewish life outside the Orthodox world, one that we have seen before. It can be termed&nbsp;... Neo-Conservatism. 'Open Orthodoxy' is a deceptive brand name, an advertising slogan, and an attempt to remain tethered to the Torah world to re-shape it from within, but far from the reality. The reality is that we are living through the rise of the Neo-Conservatives.}} <ref>{{cite web|url= http://matzav.com/open-orthodoxy-the-rise-of-the-neo-cons| title=Open Orthodoxy: The Rise of the Neo-Cons| last=Steven| first=Pruzansky| date=July 17, 2013|work=Matzav.com|accessdate=July 30, 2013}}</ref> Chicago Rabbi Moshe Averick, a columnist for the Jewish magazine ''[[The Algemeiner Journal]]'' and author of ''Nonsense of a High Order: The Confused and Illusory World of the Atheist'', agrees with Pruzansky that Weiss has created a new Jewish movement in America, comparing him with [[Isaac Mayer Wise]] (founder of [[Reform Judaism]]) and [[Solomon Schechter]] (founder of Conservative Judaism in the United States). He compares Weiss's ordination of three women as Maharat on June 16, 2013, with the so-called [[Trefa Banquet]] of 1883, which marked the split between Reform and Traditional Judaism in America. Says Averick: \"Weiss' movement, a form of Judaism that enthusiastically embraces the ideologies of feminism and liberal-progressive-modernism while coating it with a strong Orthodox flavor, could accurately be labeled as Ortho-Feminist Progressive Judaism,\" but \"the term coined by Rabbi Steven Pruzansky&nbsp;... Neo-Conservative Judaism&nbsp;... has managed to fit neatly into the slot to the left of Orthodox Judaism and to the right of Conservative Judaism.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.algemeiner.com/2013/07/18/american-jewry-at-the-crossroads-isaac-mayer-wise-solomon-schechter-and-now-avi-weiss-and-sara-hurwitz/ |title=American Jewry at the Crossroads: Isaac Mayer Wise, Solomon Schechter, and now...Avi Weiss and Sara Hurwitz | work = The Algemeiner |date=July 18, 2013 |accessdate=August 2, 2013}}</ref> In October 2013, dozens of rabbis who defined themselves as \"members in good standing or [who] identify with the Rabbinical Council of America\", signed a letter arguing that Open Orthodoxy has \"plunged ahead, again and again, across the border that divides Orthodoxy from neo-Conservatism\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://orthodoxrabbis.wordpress.com/2013/10/30/statement-on-open-orthodoxy/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-01-11 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150714112152/https://orthodoxrabbis.wordpress.com/2013/10/30/statement-on-open-orthodoxy/ |archivedate=2015-07-14 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2015, [[Conference of European Rabbis|The Conference of European Rabbis]] stated  \"The Conference views with great pain the deviations from religious foundations emanating from the movement called 'Open Orthodoxy', and warns that those who act in this spirit, alumni of the aforementioned movement... will not be recognized by us as rabbis, with all that entails.\" Rabbi Jonathan Guttentag of Manchester, UK, explained that by systematically testing the boundaries of normative Jewish practice, Open Orthodoxy \"has pushed the envelope that bit far, and... led to positions which take its proponents outside the Orthodox umbrella.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/203309#.VkT23yspowc|title=European Rabbis: Open Orthodoxy 'outside the fold' - Jewish World - News - Arutz Sheva|work=Arutz Sheva}}</ref>\n\nSimilarly, also in the fall of that year, the [[Agudath Israel of America]] denounced moves to ordain women, and went even further, declaring Open Orthodoxy, [[Yeshivat Maharat]], [[Yeshivat Chovevei Torah]], and other affiliated entities to be similar to other dissident movements throughout Jewish history in having rejected basic tenets of Judaism.<ref name=\"Hamodia\"/><ref name=\"The Jerusalem Post - JPost.com\"/><ref name=\"Josh Nathan-Kazis\"/>\n\nIn contrast, Dr. [[Steven Bayme]], National Director of Jewish Communal Affairs at the [[American Jewish Committee]], sees Open Orthodoxy as the most authentic form of Modern Orthodoxy. In reference to the installation of Rabbi [[Asher Lopatin]] as incoming president of [[Yeshivat Chovevei Torah]] Rabbinical School, Dr. Bayme said: \"The event demonstrated the power of an Orthodoxy that is truly modern, in the sense of synthesizing modern scholarship and culture with Judaic tradition and learning, and an 'Open Orthodoxy', open to all Jews and open to hearing other viewpoints.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= http://blogs.forward.com/forward-thinking/185346/asher-lopatin-set-as-modern-orthodox-bridge/ |title= Asher Lopatin Set as Modern Orthodox 'Bridge' | work = The Jewish Daily Forward |publisher=forward.com|date=October 9, 2013 |accessdate=June 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Yeshivat Chovevei Torah ===\n{{Main|Yeshivat Chovevei Torah}}\nIn 1999 Weiss founded [[Yeshivat Chovevei Torah]] (YCT), a [[yeshiva|rabbinic seminary]] in the Riverdale neighborhood of the Bronx after resigning from Yeshiva University, where he had taught at [[Stern College for Women]] for decades.<ref name=\"JWMark\">{{cite news | title= Modern Orthodox Rabbinical School Planned | date= December 24, 1999| work= The Jewish Week| last= Mark |first=Jonathan | accessdate= August 7, 2013 | url= http://www.thejewishweek.com/news/new_york/modern_orthodox_rabbinical_school_planned}}</ref> The school's graduates work as rabbis in synagogues, [[Hillel: The Foundation for Jewish Campus Life|college Hillels]] and schools,<ref name=\"Tablet\">{{cite news | work=Tablet Magazine| title= The New 'Morethodox' Rabbi| last=Hoffman |first=Allison | date=April 29, 2013 | accessdate= August 6, 2013| url=http://www.tabletmag.com/jewish-life-and-religion/130760/the-new-morethodox-rabbi?all=1}}</ref> but the Rabbinical Council of America does not permit membership to the school's graduates unless they have also been ordained by a traditional Orthodox rabbinical school.<ref>{{cite news| title=RCA Facing Leadership Challenge| date= June 12, 2012| work=The Jewish Week| last= Dickter |first=Adam| accessdate=August 7, 2013| url= http://www.thejewishweek.com/news/new-york-news/rca-facing-leadership-challenge}}</ref> In June 2013, Weiss handed over the presidency of Yeshivat Chovevei Torah to Chicago rabbi [[Asher Lopatin]].<ref name=\"Tablet\"/>\n\n=== Ordination of Women ===\n\nIn May 2009, Weiss announced the opening of [[Yeshivat Maharat]], a new school to train women as maharat, an acronym for the Hebrew \u05de\u05e0\u05d4\u05d9\u05d2\u05d4 \u05d4\u05dc\u05db\u05ea\u05d9\u05ea \u05e8\u05d5\u05d7\u05e0\u05d9\u05ea \u05ea\u05d5\u05e8\u05e0\u05d9\u05ea (halakhic, spiritual, and Torah leader), a title he created for a female version of a rabbi.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://blogs.jta.org/telegraph/article/2009/05/18/1005240/new-program-to-train-orthodox-women-as-non-rabbis |title=New program to train Orthodox women as non-rabbis |date=May 18, 2009 |last=Harris |first=Ben |accessdate=April 15, 2011 |publisher=blogs.jta.org |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717140922/http://blogs.jta.org/telegraph/article/2009/05/18/1005240/new-program-to-train-orthodox-women-as-non-rabbis |archivedate=July 17, 2011 |df= }}</ref> The school's  mission, according to its website, is \"to train Orthodox women as spiritual leaders and halakhic authorities\" in a four-year full-time course.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://yeshivatmaharat.org/| title=Yeshivat Maharat}}</ref> [[Sara Hurwitz]] was appointed dean of Yeshivat Maharat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hillel.harvard.edu/events/2010/03/03/evening-rabbah-sarah-hurwitz|title=An Evening with Rabbah Sarah Hurwitz|publisher=hillel.harvard.edu|accessdate=April 15, 2011|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110817220326/http://hillel.harvard.edu/events/2010/03/03/evening-rabbah-sarah-hurwitz|archivedate=August 17, 2011|df=}}</ref> On June 16, 2013 the first class of female maharats graduated from Yeshivat Maharat.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://forward.com/articles/178926/orthodox-schism-over-role-of-women-widens-after-gr/?p=all | title=Orthodox Schism Over Role of Women Widens After Graduation of Maharats| last= Cohen |first=Anne | date=June 20, 2013| accessdate=August 7, 2013| work=The Jewish Daily Forward}}</ref>\n\n==== Sara Hurwitz ====\n{{Main|Sara Hurwitz}}\nIn June 2009 Weiss [[Semichah|ordained]] [[Sara Hurwitz]] as rabbi, giving her the title of \"''Maharat''\".<ref name=\"GRosenblatt\">{{cite news| url=http://www.thejewishweek.com/editorial_opinion/gary_rosenblatt/between_rav_and_hard_place| title=Between A Rav And A Hard Place| last=Rosenblatt |first=Gary |date=June 26, 2009| accessdate=April 15, 2011| work=The Jewish Week}}</ref> She was the first formally ordained Orthodox woman.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://heebmagazine.com/rabba-sara-hurwitz-rocks-the-orthodox|title=\"Rabba\" Sara Hurwitz Rocks the Orthodox |date=March 10, 2010 | author=StevenM | work=Heeb | accessdate=March 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2010 Weiss announced that Hurwitz would henceforth be known by the title of \"Rabba\". The move sparked widespread criticism in the Orthodox world.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thejewishweek.com/blogs/route_17/agudah_avi_weiss_shul_not_orthodox|title=Agudah: Avi Weiss Shul Not Orthodox|last=Mark|first=Jonathan|date=March 9, 2010|work=The Jewish Week|accessdate=January 1, 2013}}</ref> The [[Agudath Israel of America|Agudath Israel Council of Torah Sages]] issued a public statement suggesting that Weiss should no longer be considered Orthodox declaring that \"these developments represent a radical and dangerous departure from Jewish tradition and the [[Masoretic Text|mesoras haTorah]], and must be condemned in the strongest terms. Any congregation with a woman in a rabbinical position of any sort cannot be considered Orthodox.\"<ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.jewishjournal.com/nation/article/rabbi_condemned_for_ordaining_woman_20100226|title=Rabbi condemned for ordaining woman|date=February 26, 2010|work=[[The Jewish Journal of Greater Los Angeles]] |accessdate=July 4, 2013}}</ref> Rumors circulated in the Jewish press that RCA considered expelling Weiss. Under pressure from the RCA, Weiss pledged not to ordain anybody else \"rabba\", although Hurwitz retains the title.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://blogs.jta.org/telegraph/article/2010/03/05/1010943/avi-weiss-no-more-rabbas| title=Avi Weiss: No more rabbas| date=March 5, 2010| last=Eden| first=Ami| publisher=JTA| accessdate=April 6, 2013|url-status = dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100420075116/http://blogs.jta.org/telegraph/article/2010/03/05/1010943/avi-weiss-no-more-rabbas| archivedate=April 20, 2010| df=}}</ref> Shortly afterwards, the RCA passed a resolution praising the increased Torah education of women in the Orthodox world encouraging \"halachically and communally appropriate professional opportunities\" for them, but stating: \"We cannot accept either the ordination of women or the recognition of women as members of the Orthodox rabbinate, regardless of title.\"<ref name=\"moment\">{{cite news | title=Do 1 Rabba, 2 Rabbis and 1 Yeshiva = a New Denomination?| last= Breger |first=Sarah | date= November\u2013December 2010| work= [[Moment Magazine]] |accessdate= July 31, 2013 | url= http://www.momentmag.com/do-1-rabba-2-rabbis-and-1-yeshiva-a-new-denomination/}}</ref> In 2015 Yaffa Epstein was ordained as Rabba by the [[Yeshivat Maharat]], which Weiss founded.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yeshivatmaharat.org/class-of-2015/|title=Class of 2015|work=Yeshivat Maharat|access-date=2016-01-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151205231641/http://www.yeshivatmaharat.org/class-of-2015/|archive-date=2015-12-05|url-status = dead|df=}}</ref> Also in 2015, Rabbi [[Lila Kagedan]] was ordained as Rabbi by that same organization, making her their first graduate to take the title Rabbi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cjnews.com/living-jewish/jewish-learning/why-orthodox-judaism-needs-female-rabbis|title=Why Orthodox Judaism needs female rabbis|author=Rabbi Lila Kagedan|date=25 November 2015|work=The Canadian Jewish News}}</ref>\n\n===Criticism By Rabbi Avrohom Gordimer===\nAccording to Dr. [[Marc B. Shapiro|Marc Shapiro]], Rabbi Avrohom Gordimer \"has assumed the mantle of defender of the faith\" and \"sees his goal as exposing the non-Orthodox nature of Open Orthodoxy\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://seforim.blogspot.com/2016/02/open-orthodoxy-and-its-main-critic-part.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-26 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160405134022/http://seforim.blogspot.com/2016/02/open-orthodoxy-and-its-main-critic-part.html |archivedate=2016-04-05 |df= }}</ref> Rabbi Gordimer responded in an article in Cross Currents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cross-currents.com/archives/2016/02/09/response-to-dr-marc-shapiro-good-shot-but-wrong-target/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-26 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160603231855/http://www.cross-currents.com/archives/2016/02/09/response-to-dr-marc-shapiro-good-shot-but-wrong-target/ |archivedate=2016-06-03 |df= }}</ref> Rabbi Ysoscher Katz, Chair, Department of Talmud,\nYeshivat Chovevei Torah Rabbinical School, has also threatened legal action against Cross Currents despite claims on Facebook that he was open to these debates, if they \"continue to publish Avrohom Gordimer\u2019s libelous and unfounded accusations against me.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cross-currents.com/archives/2015/10/12/a-communication-from-open-orthodoxy-with-reply/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-26 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812192947/http://www.cross-currents.com/archives/2015/10/12/a-communication-from-open-orthodoxy-with-reply/ |archivedate=2016-08-12 |df= }}</ref> In August 2015  Gordimer announced that \"After three years of documenting and critiquing various aspects of Open Orthodoxy, I am taking a break...My decision to temporarily withdraw from the discourse is purely volitional. It is unrelated to the countless personal attacks on me and my becoming basically a persona non grata among some. It is certainly not due to the exertion of external pressure. Rather, I am stepping aside for the short term in order to encourage those who are best suited to speak up to do so \u2013 nothing more than that.\" <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cross-currents.com/archives/2016/08/15/taking-a-break-making-a-few-observations/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-09-16 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920150742/http://www.cross-currents.com/archives/2016/08/15/taking-a-break-making-a-few-observations/ |archivedate=2016-09-20 |df= }}</ref>\n\n== Activism ==\nWeiss has been vocal on many issues, including emigration and absorption of [[Soviet Jews]], [[clemency]] for Israeli spy [[Jonathan Pollard]], opposing [[terrorism]], supporting [[Israel]], preserving [[Holocaust]] memorials, and exposing [[anti-semitism]]. In 1992 he founded ''Amcha \u2013 the Coalition for Jewish Concerns'', a [[grassroots]] coalition engaging in pro-Jewish activism.<ref name=\"archive\">{{cite web|url=http://www.amchacjc.org/people.cfm|title=Amcha: The Coalition for Jewish Concerns. Rabbi Avi Weiss, President|publisher=amchacjc.org|accessdate=April 15, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060217051615/http://www.amchacjc.org/people.cfm|archivedate=February 17, 2006}}</ref>\n\n=== Soviet Jewry ===\nWeiss was an early leader of the [[Student Struggle for Soviet Jewry]], founded in 1964. It was one of the first American organizations working to free Russian Jews, who were not allowed to emigrate during the [[Soviet era]]. The group used demonstrations, lobbying, and education to pressure the Soviet authorities into allowing Jews to leave the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/judaica/ejud_0002_0019_0_19306.html|title=Student Struggle for Soviet Jewry|accessdate=April 17, 2011|publisher=jewishvirtuallibrary.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncsj.org/AuxPages/043004JWeek_Birnbaum.shtml |title=Soviet Jewry, 40 Years Later |date=April 30, 2004 |publisher=ncsj.org |accessdate=April 17, 2011 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727114331/http://www.ncsj.org/AuxPages/043004JWeek_Birnbaum.shtml |archivedate=July 27, 2011 |df= }}</ref> In 2015, he published his memoir detailing his efforts to liberate Soviet Jews, ''Open Up the Iron Door: Memoirs of a Soviet Jewry Activist''. The book focuses on how grassroots activism and acts of civil disobedience led to important policy changes for the Soviet Jews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/rabbi-ben-greenberg/social-justice-with-roots_b_6587438.html?|title=Social Justice With Roots: What The Memoirs of a Soviet Jewry Activist Can Teach Us About Today|accessdate=May 5, 2015|publisher=Huffington Post}}</ref>\n\n=== In the United States ===\nWeiss was an official emissary of former New York Governor [[Mario Cuomo]] and former New York Mayor [[Rudolph Giuliani]].<ref name=\"archive\"/>\n\nWeiss has served as personal rabbi to [[Jonathan Pollard]], an American who spied for Israel sentenced to life in prison in 1987.<ref name=\"archive\"/> In 1992 Weiss was one of the signators to a full-page ad in ''[[The New York Times]]'' calling for the release of Pollard.<ref>{{cite news\n |url =http://www.jonathanpollard.org/1992/102592a.htm\n |title = American Rabbis Ask Bush to Give Pollard Clemency\n |work = The Jerusalem Post\n |date = October 25, 1992\n |accessdate = June 10, 2006\n | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060614162325/http://jonathanpollard.org/1992/102592a.htm| archivedate= June 14, 2006 <!--DASHBot-->|url-status = live}}</ref>\nIn 1989 Weiss conducted a \"freedom [[Passover Seder|Seder]]\" in front of the prison where Pollard was incarcerated.<ref>{{cite news\n |url=http://www.thejewishweek.com/features/jonathan_pollard_case_reflection_our_fears \n |title=The Jonathan Pollard Case: A Reflection Of Our Fears \n |publisher=The Jewish Week \n |date=June 28, 2002 \n |accessdate=April 17, 2011 \n |last=Besser \n |first=James D \n |url-status = dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110527051801/http://www.thejewishweek.com/features/jonathan_pollard_case_reflection_our_fears \n |archivedate=May 27, 2011 \n |df= \n}}</ref>\n\nAt a speech at New York City Hall in 2001 Weiss criticized President [[George W. Bush]] for not making a clearer distinction between Arab acts of terrorism and Israeli acts of self-defense. \"The trap that he's falling into is that he's drawn a moral equivalency between cold-blooded murder and acts of self-defense,\" Weiss said.\n<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/2001/06/02/2001-06-02_it_s_self-defense__rabbi_tel.html |location=New York |work=Daily News |title=It's Self-Defense, Rabbi Tells Bush |date=June 2, 2001 |accessdate=April 17, 2011 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629092441/http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/2001/06/02/2001-06-02_it_s_self-defense__rabbi_tel.html |archivedate=June 29, 2011 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2002 Weiss organized a pro-Israel rally on the [[National Mall]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/04/08/nyregion/demonstrators-roar-support-for-israel-444197.html?pagewanted=all | work=The New York Times | first=Robert D. | last=McFadden | title=Demonstrators Roar Support for Israel | date=April 8, 2002|accessdate=April 17, 2011}}</ref> and a boycott of several large newspapers perceived as having an anti-Israeli bias.<ref>\n{{cite news | first=Dan | last=Fost | title=Jewish Groups Battle Media Over Perceived Bias | date=May 2, 2002 | newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle | url=http://www.commondreams.org/headlines02/0502-03.htm | accessdate=April 17, 2011 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110524093431/http://www.commondreams.org/headlines02/0502-03.htm | archivedate=May 24, 2011 |url-status = dead| df= }}</ref>\n\nIn 2006 Weiss organized a protest in front of Syria's UN mission to denounce a [[Hezbollah]] offensive in the Middle East.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/2006/07/17/2006-07-17_dozens_protest_at_un_mission.html |title=Dozens Protest At Un Mission |last=Egbert |first=Bill |newspaper=Daily News |location=New York |accessdate=April 17, 2011 |date=July 17, 2006 }}{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2011, Weiss was arrested in front of the U.N. building in New York while protesting the Palestinian statehood bid.<ref name=\"Top50\"/>\n\nIn a July 15, 2015, [[Haaretz]] opinion piece, Weiss applauded the U.S. Supreme Court [[Obergefell v. Hodges|decision]] legalizing [[same-sex marriage]], which he saw as a part of maintaining the [[separation of church and state]] and protecting his right to refuse to perform gay weddings. He stated that he would not participate in same-sex weddings, because doing so would run contrary to his religious commitments, but that he had met countless gay individuals and couples, some of whom were members of his synagogue, who lived loving, exemplary lives. \"If I welcome with open arms those who do not observe Sabbath, Kashrut or family purity laws, I must welcome, even more so, homosexual Jews, as they are born with their orientation.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Weiss|first1=Avi|title=Why I, as an Orthodox Rabbi, Support Legalizing Same-sex Marriage\n|url=http://www.haaretz.com/opinion/1.666064|accessdate=14 December 2015|work=[[Haaretz]]|date=July 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== In Europe ===\nWeiss has travelled worldwide as an activist in various causes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://amchacjc.org/principles.html |title=Principles of Spiritual Activist |last=Weiss |first=Avi |publisher=amchacjc.org |accessdate=April 17, 2011}}</ref> In 1989 Weiss and others protested at a [[Carmelite]] convent that had been established at [[Auschwitz]]. The group\u2014dressed in [[concentration camp]] clothing\u2014scaled the walls of the convent, blew a [[shofar]], and screamed anti-[[Nazi]] slogans. Workers evicted them from the site.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/judaica/ejud_0002_0002_0_01611.html|title=Auschwitz Convent|publisher=Jewish Virtual Library|accessdate=April 16, 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110514032327/https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/judaica/ejud_0002_0002_0_01611.html| archivedate= May 14, 2011 <!--DASHBot-->|url-status = live}}</ref> In 1993 [[Pope John Paul II]] ordered the closure of the convent, which had been located in a converted building that had stored [[Zyklon B]] gas used to kill prisoners at the camp during World War II.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/04/15/world/pope-orders-nuns-out-of-auschwitz.html|last=Perlez |first=Jane|title= Pope Orders Nuns Out of Auschwitz |newspaper=The New York Times |date= April 15, 1993|accessdate=April 16, 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe protested President [[Ronald Reagan]]'s visit to an [[SS]] cemetery in 1985.<ref name=\"archive\"/> He was arrested in 1990 while protesting [[Kurt Waldheim]]'s visit to the [[Salzburg Festival]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,970799,00.html |title=Austria: The Trojan Guest |date=August 6, 1990 |work=Time |accessdate=April 17, 2011}}</ref> and again in 1994, when he protested in [[Oslo, Norway]], when [[PLO]] chief [[Yasser Arafat]] received the [[Nobel Peace Prize]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://alb.merlinone.net/mweb/wmsql.wm.request?oneimage&imageid=5701594 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723205336/http://alb.merlinone.net/mweb/wmsql.wm.request?oneimage&imageid=5701594 |url-status = dead|archive-date=July 23, 2011 |title=Peace Prize Triumvirate Denounced |newspaper=[[Times Union (Albany)|Times Union]] |location=Albany |agency=Associated Press |page=A2 |date=December 10, 1994 |accessdate=April 17, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nAlong with Rosa Sacharin of [[Glasgow, Scotland]], Weiss sued the [[American Jewish Committee]] in New York state court in 2003 to stop the construction of a path through the [[Belzec extermination camp]] in [[Poland]]. They were concerned that mass graves at the site would be disturbed by the work.<ref>{{cite news\n |first = Joe\n |last = Berkofsky\n |url = http://www.jewishsf.com/content/2-0-/module/displaystory/story_id/20693/edition_id/424/format/html/displaystory.html\n |title = Avi Weiss rekindles battle to block camp memorial\n |work = The Jewish News Weekly of Northern California\n |date = July 25, 2003\n |accessdate = June 10, 2006\n}}</ref>\n\n== Organizations ==\n*[[Hebrew Institute of Riverdale]] (synagogue where Weiss is one of the rabbis)\n*[[Yeshivat Chovevei Torah]] (founded by Weiss)\n*[[Yeshivat Maharat]] (founded by Weiss)\n*The coalition for Jewish concerns (Amcha) (founded by Weiss)\n\n== Works ==\n*{{cite book |title= Haggadah for the Yom HaShoah Seder|last=Weiss |first=Avi |year=2000 |publisher=Jonas Pub |location=Hackensack, NJ |isbn= 0-615-11519-5 }}\n*{{cite book |title=Principles of Spiritual Activism |last=Weiss |first=Avi |year=2001 |publisher=KTAV Publishing House |location=Hoboken, NJ |isbn=0-88125-737-0 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/principlesofspir0000weis }}\n*{{cite book |title= Women at Prayer: A Halakhic Analysis of Women's Prayer Groups|last=Weiss |first=Avi |year=2001 |publisher=KTAV Publishing House |location=Hoboken, NJ|isbn=0-88125-719-2 }}\n*{{cite book |title=The Yeshivat Chovevei Torah Tanakh Companion to the Book of Samuel |chapter=Avigayil: Savior of David|editor1-first=Nathaniel |editor1-last=Helfgot |last=Weiss |first=Avi |year=2006 |publisher= Ben Yehuda Press |location=Teaneck, NJ |isbn= 0-9769862-4-8 }}\n*{{cite book |title= Holistic Prayer: A Guide to Jewish Spirituality|last=Weiss |first=Avi |year=2014 |publisher=Maggid Books |location=Jerusalem |isbn= 978-1-592-64334-9 }}\n*{{cite book |title= Open Up the Iron Door: Memoirs of a Soviet Jewry Activist|last=Weiss |first=Avi |year=2015 |publisher=The Toby Press |location=Jerusalem |isbn= 978-1-592-64385-1 }}\n\n;Articles in ''Sh'ma: A Journal of Jewish Responsibility'':\n*''[http://www.bjpa.org/Publications/details.cfm?PublicationID=6444 Creating an Open Orthodox Rabbinate]'', with Dov Linzer, Vol. 33/no.597-598 2003.\n*''[http://www.bjpa.org/Publications/details.cfm?PublicationID=7126 A Congregation of Holy Souls: Reflections on 9/11 One Year Later]'' Vol.33/no.593 2002.\n*''[http://www.bjpa.org/Publications/details.cfm?PublicationID=7953 NiSh'ma:Apikorus]'', with Rebecca T. Alpert, Shmuley Boteach, Lisa S. Lehmann Vol.31/no.574 2000.\n*''[http://www.bjpa.org/Publications/details.cfm?PublicationID=8500 Endthoughts: Stolen Money and Stolen Souls]'', Vol.27/no.535 1997.\n*''[http://www.bjpa.org/Publications/details.cfm?PublicationID=7491 The Insurmountable Divisiveness of Patrilineality]'', Vol.25/no.469 1994.\n*''[http://www.bjpa.org/Publications/details.cfm?PublicationID=9579 With Jonathan Pollard]'', Vol.23/no.453 1993.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n*Mindell, Cindy. [http://www.jewishledger.com/2013/03/conversation-with-rabbi-avi-weiss/ Conversation with Rabbi Avi Weiss] ''Jewish Ledger'' (Connecticut edition), March 6, 2013\n*[http://www.bbc.co.uk/religion/religions/judaism/subdivisions/modernorthodoxy_1.shtml BBC, Modern Orthodoxy]: BBC summary of Modern Orthodox Judaism\n*[http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/122934 Rabbis on Their Way Home to Zion], ''Israel National News'', July 1, 2007\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hWifvGvcpTE A tribute video to Rabbi Avi and Toby Weiss] for [[Yeshivat Chovevei Torah]]'s 2014 Annual Dinner\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weiss, Avraham}}\n[[Category:People from the Bronx]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Jewish American community activists]]\n[[Category:Modern Orthodox rabbis]]\n[[Category:American Orthodox rabbis]]\n[[Category:20th-century rabbis]]\n[[Category:21st-century rabbis]]\n[[Category:Open Orthodox Judaism]]\n[[Category:Activists from New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Cleanup rewrite|overly polemic, with entire paragraphs dedicated to defending/attacking him (lengthy quotes verging on Copyvio). Just state the facts.|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox Jewish leader\n| honorific-prefix = Rabbi\n| name             = Avi Weiss\n| honorific-suffix = \n| title            = \n| image            = Rabbi Weiss Speaking.JPG\n| caption          = Rabbi Weiss, 2007\n| synagogue        = [[Hebrew Institute of Riverdale]]\n| synagogueposition = \n| yeshiva          = [[Yeshivat Chovevei Torah]]<br />[[Yeshivat Maharat]]\n| yeshivaposition  = \n| organisation     = \n| organisationposition = \n| began            = \n| ended            = \n| predecessor      = \n| successor        = \n| rabbi            = \n| rebbe            = \n| kohan            = \n| hazzan           = \n| rank             = \n| other_post       = \n<!---------- Personal details ---------->\n| birth_name       = Avraham Weiss<br />{{Hebrew|\u05d0\u05d1\u05e8\u05d4\u05dd \u05d7\u05d9\u05d9\u05dd \u05d9\u05d5\u05e1\u05e3 \u05d4\u05db\u05d4\u05df \u05d5\u05d5\u05d9\u05d9\u05e1}}\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1944|6|24}}\n| birth_place      = \n| nationality      = American\n| denomination     = [[Open Orthodox]]\n| residence        = \n| dynasty          = \n| parents          = \n| spouse           = \n| children         = \n| occupation       = [[Rabbi]], author\n| profession       = \n| alma_mater       = [[Yeshiva University]], [[RIETS]]\n| semicha          = [[Rabbi Isaac Elchanan Theological Seminary]], 1968\n| signature        = \n}}\n\n'''Avraham Haim Yosef (Avi) haCohen Weiss''' ({{lang-he-n|\u05d0\u05d1\u05e8\u05d4\u05dd \u05d7\u05d9\u05d9\u05dd \u05d9\u05d5\u05e1\u05e3 \u05d4\u05db\u05d4\u05df \u05d5\u05d5\u05d9\u05d9\u05e1}}; born June 24, 1944) is an American [[open Orthodox Judaism|open Orthodox]] ordained [[rabbi]], author, teacher, lecturer, and activist who heads the [[Hebrew Institute of Riverdale]] in [[The Bronx]], New York, from which he retired in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://forward.com/articles/207457/rabbi-avi-weiss-progressive-voice-in-orthodoxy-ste/|title=Rabbi Avi Weiss, Progressive Voice in Orthodoxy, Steps Down From Pulpit|author=Forward Staff|date=16 October 2014|work=The Forward}}</ref> He is the founder of [[Yeshivat Chovevei Torah]], a [[yeshiva|rabbinical seminary]] he refers to as \"Open Orthodox\", a term he coined to describe an offshoot of [[Orthodoxy]], founder of [[Yeshivat Maharat]] for Orthodox women,<ref name=\"nymag\"/> co-founder of the [[International Rabbinical Fellowship]], an Open Orthodox rabbinical association founded as a liberal alternative to the Modern Orthodox [[Rabbinical Council of America]],<ref>{{cite news | work=The Jewish Daily Forward| last= Nathan-Kazis |first= Josh | title= Top Modern Orthodox Rabbi Michael Broyde Admits Fake Name Scheme| url=http://forward.com/articles/174777/top-modern-orthodox-rabbi-michael-broyde-admits-fa/| date=April 12, 2013| accessdate=July 31, 2013}}</ref> and founder of the grassroots organization Coalition for Jewish Concerns \u2013 Amcha.\nHe received his rabbinical ordination at the Rabbi Isaac Elchanan Theological Seminary (Yeshiva University) in 1968.\n\nIn 2013, ''[[Newsweek]]'' ranked him the 10th most prominent rabbi in the United States,<ref name=\"Top13\">{{cite news | url= http://www.thedailybeast.com/galleries/2013/03/21/america-s-top-50-rabbis-for-2013-photos.html#c7a234a8-c2aa-46ad-8c11-638bac4c2eab| title=America's Top 50 Rabbis for 2013|work=The Daily Beast | accessdate=July 31, 2013}}</ref> climbing from number 11 in 2012 and number 12 in 2011,<ref name=\"Top50\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/galleries/2012/04/02/america-s-top-50-rabbis-for-2012.html#slide11|title=America's Top 50 Rabbis for 2012|work=The Daily Beast}}</ref> after being ranked number 18 in 2010.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.newsweek.com/2010/06/28/the-50-most-influential-rabbis-in-america.html#|title=The 50 Most Influential Rabbis in America|last1=Lynton|first1=Michael|last2=Ginsberg|first2=Gary|date=June 28, 2010|accessdate=April 14, 2011|publisher=newsweek.com}}</ref>\n\nOn June 29, 2015, Weiss resigned from the [[Rabbinical Council of America]]. He resigned before he likely would have been removed as he was denounced as an apikores, which means a heretic, by many of the leading members of the rabbinate. The Traditional Orthodox communities view his movement as neo-conservaitve and far removed from orthdoxy.<ref>{{cite web |title=Will The RCA Expel Rabbi Avi Weiss Over \u2018Orthodox Woman Rabbi\u2019 |url=https://www.theyeshivaworld.com/news/general/49447/will-the-rca-expel-rabbi-avi-weiss-over-orthodox-woman-rabbi-aka-maharatrabbah.html |website=Yeshiva World |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|title = Rabbi Avi Weiss quits Rabbinical Council of America in protest - Jewish World News|url = http://www.haaretz.com/jewish-world/jewish-world-news/1.663608|accessdate = 2015-06-30|last = JTA}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Newly minted female Orthodox rabbis to be called 'rabba' - Jewish World News|url = http://www.haaretz.com/jewish-world/jewish-world-news/.premium-1.660857}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = In protest, Avi Weiss quits Rabbinical Council of America|url = http://www.timesofisrael.com/in-protest-avi-weiss-quits-rabbinical-council-of-america/|accessdate = 2015-06-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Avi Weiss Quits Rabbinic Group in Flap Over School - Breaking News|url = http://forward.com/news/breaking-news/311099/avi-weiss-quits-rabbinic-group-in-flap-over-school/|accessdate = 2015-06-30}}</ref>\n\nOn November 3, 2015, the Moetzes of [[Agudath Israel of America]] declared Open Orthodoxy, [[Yeshivat Chovevei Torah]], Yeshivat Maharat and other affiliated entities to be similar to other dissident movements throughout Jewish history in having rejected basic tenets of Judaism.<ref name=\"Hamodia\">{{cite web|url=http://hamodia.com/2015/11/03/moetzes-open-orthodoxy-not-a-form-of-torah-judaism/|title=Moetzes: 'Open Orthodoxy' Not a Form of Torah Judaism|work=Hamodia}}</ref><ref name=\"The Jerusalem Post - JPost.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jpost.com/Diaspora/Breach-in-US-Orthodox-Judaism-grows-as-haredi-body-rejects-Open-Orthodoxy-institutions-431929|title=Breach in US Orthodox Judaism grows as haredi body rejects 'Open Orthodoxy' institutions|work=The Jerusalem Post - JPost.com}}</ref><ref name=\"Josh Nathan-Kazis\">{{cite web|url=http://forward.com/news/323887/agudath-rabbis-declare-war-on-open-orthodoxy/|title=Avi Weiss Defends 'Open Orthodoxy' as Agudah Rabbis Declare War|author=Josh Nathan-Kazis|date=3 November 2015|work=The Forward}}</ref>\n\n== Hebrew Institute of Riverdale ==\n{{Main|Hebrew Institute of Riverdale}}\nThe Hebrew Institute of Riverdale was founded in 1971 in a boiler room of the Whitehall Building off the [[Henry Hudson Parkway]] by former members of the Hebrew Institute of [[University Heights, Bronx|University Heights]] in the Bronx who had moved to Riverdale. Weiss, who had finished his training at [[Yeshiva University]] a few years earlier, became the synagogue's rabbi in 1973.<ref name=\"Olitzky 1996\">{{cite book|last1=Olitzky|first1=Kerry M.|authorlink=Kerry Olitzky|last2=Raphael|first2=Marc Lee|title=The American Synagogue: A Historical Dictionary and Sourcebook|publisher=Greenwood Press|year=1996|pages=223\u2013224}}</ref> The congregation has grown to 850 families, and has served as a platform for Weiss's rabbinical advocacy.<ref name=\"nymag\">{{cite news |url= http://nymag.com/news/features/67145/ |title=The Rabbi and the Rabba|last=Pogrebin |first=Abigail|date=July 11, 2010|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |accessdate=April 14, 2011}}</ref> In October 2014, Weiss announced that he would step down from his pulpit effective mid-2015. In July 2015 Rabbi Steven Exler became HIR's senior rabbi and Rabbi Weiss continues on its staff.<ref>[https://archive.today/20141018220455/http://www.jta.org/2014/10/17/news-opinion/united-states/rabbi-avi-weiss-to-step-down-as-rabbi-of-hebrew-institute-of-riverdale Rabbi Avi Weiss to step down as rabbi of Hebrew Institute of Riverdale]</ref>\n\n== Open Orthodoxy ==\n{{Main|Open Orthodoxy}}\nWeiss coined the term \"Open Orthodoxy\" in 1997 to describe a form of Modern Orthodoxy that emphasizes [[halakha]], the collective body of Jewish law, intellectual openness, a spiritual dimension, a broad concern for all Jews, and a more expansive role for women.<ref name=\"GRosenblatt\"/> He views halakha as being more flexible and open to innovation than his more traditional counterparts in Orthodox Judaism. He states that all Orthodox Judaism, including Open Orthodoxy, fundamentally differs from [[Conservative Judaism]] in three areas. First, unlike Conservative Judaism,\n*Orthodox Jews believe that the [[Torah]] was given by God at [[Mount Sinai]] in its current form. Second,\n*Orthodoxy believes that \"legal authority is cumulative, and that a contemporary ''[[posek]]'' [decider] can only issue judgments based on a full history of Jewish legal precedent\", whereas Conservative Jews believe \"precedent provides illustrations of possible positions rather than binding law. Conservatism, therefore, remains free to select whichever position within the prior history appeals to it\". Third,\n*Orthodoxy is characterized by ritually-observant members who \"meticulously keep [[Shabbat]] (the Sabbath), [[Kashrut]] (the Dietary Laws), [[Niddah|Taharat ha-Mishpaha]] (the Laws of Family Purity), and [[Jewish services|pray]] three times a day\", whereas Conservative Judaism \"is generally not composed of ritually observant Jews. Thus, only in our community if a 'permissive custom' is accepted, can it be meaningful.\"<ref>{{cite web | url =http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Open+orthodoxy!+A+modern+Orthodox+rabbi's+creed.-a020583577 | title =Open orthodoxy! A modern Orthodox rabbi's creed |work=Judaism: A Journal of Jewish Life & Thought|publisher=[[American Jewish Congress]]|date=Fall 1997|last=Weiss |first=Avi}}</ref>\n\nMore traditional rabbis have opposed this approach. Rabbi [[Steven Pruzansky]], a trustee of the [[Rabbinical Council of America]] (RCA) on the Board of the [[Beth Din of America]],<ref>{{cite news | title=U.S. rabbi faces dissent for slamming Obama| last= Maltz |first=Judy | date=November 16, 2012 | work=Haaretz| accessdate= July 31, 2013 | url=http://www.haaretz.com/jewish-world/jewish-world-features/u-s-rabbi-faces-dissent-for-slamming-obama.premium-1.478303#}}</ref> argues that Weiss' approach closely resembles early 20th century American Conservative Judaism and in his opinion would more aptly be called \"Neo-Conservative\" rather than \"Orthodox\" Judaism. Concluding an opinion piece in Matzav.com he states: {{Quote|text=clarity and honesty at least demand that we recognize before our eyes the creation of a new movement in Jewish life outside the Orthodox world, one that we have seen before. It can be termed&nbsp;... Neo-Conservatism. 'Open Orthodoxy' is a deceptive brand name, an advertising slogan, and an attempt to remain tethered to the Torah world to re-shape it from within, but far from the reality. The reality is that we are living through the rise of the Neo-Conservatives.}} <ref>{{cite web|url= http://matzav.com/open-orthodoxy-the-rise-of-the-neo-cons| title=Open Orthodoxy: The Rise of the Neo-Cons| last=Steven| first=Pruzansky| date=July 17, 2013|work=Matzav.com|accessdate=July 30, 2013}}</ref> Chicago Rabbi Moshe Averick, a columnist for the Jewish magazine ''[[The Algemeiner Journal]]'' and author of ''Nonsense of a High Order: The Confused and Illusory World of the Atheist'', agrees with Pruzansky that Weiss has created a new Jewish movement in America, comparing him with [[Isaac Mayer Wise]] (founder of [[Reform Judaism]]) and [[Solomon Schechter]] (founder of Conservative Judaism in the United States). He compares Weiss's ordination of three women as Maharat on June 16, 2013, with the so-called [[Trefa Banquet]] of 1883, which marked the split between Reform and Traditional Judaism in America. Says Averick: \"Weiss' movement, a form of Judaism that enthusiastically embraces the ideologies of feminism and liberal-progressive-modernism while coating it with a strong Orthodox flavor, could accurately be labeled as Ortho-Feminist Progressive Judaism,\" but \"the term coined by Rabbi Steven Pruzansky&nbsp;... Neo-Conservative Judaism&nbsp;... has managed to fit neatly into the slot to the left of Orthodox Judaism and to the right of Conservative Judaism.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.algemeiner.com/2013/07/18/american-jewry-at-the-crossroads-isaac-mayer-wise-solomon-schechter-and-now-avi-weiss-and-sara-hurwitz/ |title=American Jewry at the Crossroads: Isaac Mayer Wise, Solomon Schechter, and now...Avi Weiss and Sara Hurwitz | work = The Algemeiner |date=July 18, 2013 |accessdate=August 2, 2013}}</ref> In October 2013, dozens of rabbis who defined themselves as \"members in good standing or [who] identify with the Rabbinical Council of America\", signed a letter arguing that Open Orthodoxy has \"plunged ahead, again and again, across the border that divides Orthodoxy from neo-Conservatism\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://orthodoxrabbis.wordpress.com/2013/10/30/statement-on-open-orthodoxy/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-01-11 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150714112152/https://orthodoxrabbis.wordpress.com/2013/10/30/statement-on-open-orthodoxy/ |archivedate=2015-07-14 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2015, [[Conference of European Rabbis|The Conference of European Rabbis]] stated  \"The Conference views with great pain the deviations from religious foundations emanating from the movement called 'Open Orthodoxy', and warns that those who act in this spirit, alumni of the aforementioned movement... will not be recognized by us as rabbis, with all that entails.\" Rabbi Jonathan Guttentag of Manchester, UK, explained that by systematically testing the boundaries of normative Jewish practice, Open Orthodoxy \"has pushed the envelope that bit far, and... led to positions which take its proponents outside the Orthodox umbrella.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/203309#.VkT23yspowc|title=European Rabbis: Open Orthodoxy 'outside the fold' - Jewish World - News - Arutz Sheva|work=Arutz Sheva}}</ref>\n\nSimilarly, also in the fall of that year, the [[Agudath Israel of America]] denounced moves to ordain women, and went even further, declaring Open Orthodoxy, [[Yeshivat Maharat]], [[Yeshivat Chovevei Torah]], and other affiliated entities to be similar to other dissident movements throughout Jewish history in having rejected basic tenets of Judaism.<ref name=\"Hamodia\"/><ref name=\"The Jerusalem Post - JPost.com\"/><ref name=\"Josh Nathan-Kazis\"/>\n\nIn contrast, Dr. [[Steven Bayme]], National Director of Jewish Communal Affairs at the [[American Jewish Committee]], sees Open Orthodoxy as the most authentic form of Modern Orthodoxy. In reference to the installation of Rabbi [[Asher Lopatin]] as incoming president of [[Yeshivat Chovevei Torah]] Rabbinical School, Dr. Bayme said: \"The event demonstrated the power of an Orthodoxy that is truly modern, in the sense of synthesizing modern scholarship and culture with Judaic tradition and learning, and an 'Open Orthodoxy', open to all Jews and open to hearing other viewpoints.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= http://blogs.forward.com/forward-thinking/185346/asher-lopatin-set-as-modern-orthodox-bridge/ |title= Asher Lopatin Set as Modern Orthodox 'Bridge' | work = The Jewish Daily Forward |publisher=forward.com|date=October 9, 2013 |accessdate=June 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Yeshivat Chovevei Torah ===\n{{Main|Yeshivat Chovevei Torah}}\nIn 1999 Weiss founded [[Yeshivat Chovevei Torah]] (YCT), a [[yeshiva|rabbinic seminary]] in the Riverdale neighborhood of the Bronx after resigning from Yeshiva University, where he had taught at [[Stern College for Women]] for decades.<ref name=\"JWMark\">{{cite news | title= Modern Orthodox Rabbinical School Planned | date= December 24, 1999| work= The Jewish Week| last= Mark |first=Jonathan | accessdate= August 7, 2013 | url= http://www.thejewishweek.com/news/new_york/modern_orthodox_rabbinical_school_planned}}</ref> The school's graduates work as rabbis in synagogues, [[Hillel: The Foundation for Jewish Campus Life|college Hillels]] and schools,<ref name=\"Tablet\">{{cite news | work=Tablet Magazine| title= The New 'Morethodox' Rabbi| last=Hoffman |first=Allison | date=April 29, 2013 | accessdate= August 6, 2013| url=http://www.tabletmag.com/jewish-life-and-religion/130760/the-new-morethodox-rabbi?all=1}}</ref> but the Rabbinical Council of America does not permit membership to the school's graduates unless they have also been ordained by a traditional Orthodox rabbinical school.<ref>{{cite news| title=RCA Facing Leadership Challenge| date= June 12, 2012| work=The Jewish Week| last= Dickter |first=Adam| accessdate=August 7, 2013| url= http://www.thejewishweek.com/news/new-york-news/rca-facing-leadership-challenge}}</ref> In June 2013, Weiss handed over the presidency of Yeshivat Chovevei Torah to Chicago rabbi [[Asher Lopatin]].<ref name=\"Tablet\"/>\n\n=== Ordination of Women ===\n\nIn May 2009, Weiss announced the opening of [[Yeshivat Maharat]], a new school to train women as maharat, an acronym for the Hebrew \u05de\u05e0\u05d4\u05d9\u05d2\u05d4 \u05d4\u05dc\u05db\u05ea\u05d9\u05ea \u05e8\u05d5\u05d7\u05e0\u05d9\u05ea \u05ea\u05d5\u05e8\u05e0\u05d9\u05ea (halakhic, spiritual, and Torah leader), a title he created for a female version of a rabbi.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://blogs.jta.org/telegraph/article/2009/05/18/1005240/new-program-to-train-orthodox-women-as-non-rabbis |title=New program to train Orthodox women as non-rabbis |date=May 18, 2009 |last=Harris |first=Ben |accessdate=April 15, 2011 |publisher=blogs.jta.org |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717140922/http://blogs.jta.org/telegraph/article/2009/05/18/1005240/new-program-to-train-orthodox-women-as-non-rabbis |archivedate=July 17, 2011 |df= }}</ref> The school's  mission, according to its website, is \"to train Orthodox women as spiritual leaders and halakhic authorities\" in a four-year full-time course.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://yeshivatmaharat.org/| title=Yeshivat Maharat}}</ref> [[Sara Hurwitz]] was appointed dean of Yeshivat Maharat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hillel.harvard.edu/events/2010/03/03/evening-rabbah-sarah-hurwitz|title=An Evening with Rabbah Sarah Hurwitz|publisher=hillel.harvard.edu|accessdate=April 15, 2011|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110817220326/http://hillel.harvard.edu/events/2010/03/03/evening-rabbah-sarah-hurwitz|archivedate=August 17, 2011|df=}}</ref> On June 16, 2013 the first class of female maharats graduated from Yeshivat Maharat.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://forward.com/articles/178926/orthodox-schism-over-role-of-women-widens-after-gr/?p=all | title=Orthodox Schism Over Role of Women Widens After Graduation of Maharats| last= Cohen |first=Anne | date=June 20, 2013| accessdate=August 7, 2013| work=The Jewish Daily Forward}}</ref>\n\n==== Sara Hurwitz ====\n{{Main|Sara Hurwitz}}\nIn June 2009 Weiss [[Semichah|ordained]] [[Sara Hurwitz]] as rabbi, giving her the title of \"''Maharat''\".<ref name=\"GRosenblatt\">{{cite news| url=http://www.thejewishweek.com/editorial_opinion/gary_rosenblatt/between_rav_and_hard_place| title=Between A Rav And A Hard Place| last=Rosenblatt |first=Gary |date=June 26, 2009| accessdate=April 15, 2011| work=The Jewish Week}}</ref> She was the first formally ordained Orthodox woman.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://heebmagazine.com/rabba-sara-hurwitz-rocks-the-orthodox|title=\"Rabba\" Sara Hurwitz Rocks the Orthodox |date=March 10, 2010 | author=StevenM | work=Heeb | accessdate=March 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2010 Weiss announced that Hurwitz would henceforth be known by the title of \"Rabba\". The move sparked widespread criticism in the Orthodox world.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thejewishweek.com/blogs/route_17/agudah_avi_weiss_shul_not_orthodox|title=Agudah: Avi Weiss Shul Not Orthodox|last=Mark|first=Jonathan|date=March 9, 2010|work=The Jewish Week|accessdate=January 1, 2013}}</ref> The [[Agudath Israel of America|Agudath Israel Council of Torah Sages]] issued a public statement suggesting that Weiss should no longer be considered Orthodox declaring that \"these developments represent a radical and dangerous departure from Jewish tradition and the [[Masoretic Text|mesoras haTorah]], and must be condemned in the strongest terms. Any congregation with a woman in a rabbinical position of any sort cannot be considered Orthodox.\"<ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.jewishjournal.com/nation/article/rabbi_condemned_for_ordaining_woman_20100226|title=Rabbi condemned for ordaining woman|date=February 26, 2010|work=[[The Jewish Journal of Greater Los Angeles]] |accessdate=July 4, 2013}}</ref> Rumors circulated in the Jewish press that RCA considered expelling Weiss. Under pressure from the RCA, Weiss pledged not to ordain anybody else \"rabba\", although Hurwitz retains the title.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://blogs.jta.org/telegraph/article/2010/03/05/1010943/avi-weiss-no-more-rabbas| title=Avi Weiss: No more rabbas| date=March 5, 2010| last=Eden| first=Ami| publisher=JTA| accessdate=April 6, 2013|url-status = dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100420075116/http://blogs.jta.org/telegraph/article/2010/03/05/1010943/avi-weiss-no-more-rabbas| archivedate=April 20, 2010| df=}}</ref> Shortly afterwards, the RCA passed a resolution praising the increased Torah education of women in the Orthodox world encouraging \"halachically and communally appropriate professional opportunities\" for them, but stating: \"We cannot accept either the ordination of women or the recognition of women as members of the Orthodox rabbinate, regardless of title.\"<ref name=\"moment\">{{cite news | title=Do 1 Rabba, 2 Rabbis and 1 Yeshiva = a New Denomination?| last= Breger |first=Sarah | date= November\u2013December 2010| work= [[Moment Magazine]] |accessdate= July 31, 2013 | url= http://www.momentmag.com/do-1-rabba-2-rabbis-and-1-yeshiva-a-new-denomination/}}</ref> In 2015 Yaffa Epstein was ordained as Rabba by the [[Yeshivat Maharat]], which Weiss founded.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yeshivatmaharat.org/class-of-2015/|title=Class of 2015|work=Yeshivat Maharat|access-date=2016-01-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151205231641/http://www.yeshivatmaharat.org/class-of-2015/|archive-date=2015-12-05|url-status = dead|df=}}</ref> Also in 2015, Rabbi [[Lila Kagedan]] was ordained as Rabbi by that same organization, making her their first graduate to take the title Rabbi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cjnews.com/living-jewish/jewish-learning/why-orthodox-judaism-needs-female-rabbis|title=Why Orthodox Judaism needs female rabbis|author=Rabbi Lila Kagedan|date=25 November 2015|work=The Canadian Jewish News}}</ref>\n\n===Criticism By Rabbi Avrohom Gordimer===\nAccording to Dr. [[Marc B. Shapiro|Marc Shapiro]], Rabbi Avrohom Gordimer \"has assumed the mantle of defender of the faith\" and \"sees his goal as exposing the non-Orthodox nature of Open Orthodoxy\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://seforim.blogspot.com/2016/02/open-orthodoxy-and-its-main-critic-part.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-26 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160405134022/http://seforim.blogspot.com/2016/02/open-orthodoxy-and-its-main-critic-part.html |archivedate=2016-04-05 |df= }}</ref> Rabbi Gordimer responded in an article in Cross Currents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cross-currents.com/archives/2016/02/09/response-to-dr-marc-shapiro-good-shot-but-wrong-target/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-26 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160603231855/http://www.cross-currents.com/archives/2016/02/09/response-to-dr-marc-shapiro-good-shot-but-wrong-target/ |archivedate=2016-06-03 |df= }}</ref> Rabbi Ysoscher Katz, Chair, Department of Talmud,\nYeshivat Chovevei Torah Rabbinical School, has also threatened legal action against Cross Currents despite claims on Facebook that he was open to these debates, if they \"continue to publish Avrohom Gordimer\u2019s libelous and unfounded accusations against me.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cross-currents.com/archives/2015/10/12/a-communication-from-open-orthodoxy-with-reply/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-26 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812192947/http://www.cross-currents.com/archives/2015/10/12/a-communication-from-open-orthodoxy-with-reply/ |archivedate=2016-08-12 |df= }}</ref> In August 2015  Gordimer announced that \"After three years of documenting and critiquing various aspects of Open Orthodoxy, I am taking a break...My decision to temporarily withdraw from the discourse is purely volitional. It is unrelated to the countless personal attacks on me and my becoming basically a persona non grata among some. It is certainly not due to the exertion of external pressure. Rather, I am stepping aside for the short term in order to encourage those who are best suited to speak up to do so \u2013 nothing more than that.\" <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cross-currents.com/archives/2016/08/15/taking-a-break-making-a-few-observations/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-09-16 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920150742/http://www.cross-currents.com/archives/2016/08/15/taking-a-break-making-a-few-observations/ |archivedate=2016-09-20 |df= }}</ref>\n\n== Activism ==\nWeiss has been vocal on many issues, including emigration and absorption of [[Soviet Jews]], [[clemency]] for Israeli spy [[Jonathan Pollard]], opposing [[terrorism]], supporting [[Israel]], preserving [[Holocaust]] memorials, and exposing [[anti-semitism]]. In 1992 he founded ''Amcha \u2013 the Coalition for Jewish Concerns'', a [[grassroots]] coalition engaging in pro-Jewish activism.<ref name=\"archive\">{{cite web|url=http://www.amchacjc.org/people.cfm|title=Amcha: The Coalition for Jewish Concerns. Rabbi Avi Weiss, President|publisher=amchacjc.org|accessdate=April 15, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060217051615/http://www.amchacjc.org/people.cfm|archivedate=February 17, 2006}}</ref>\n\n=== Soviet Jewry ===\nWeiss was an early leader of the [[Student Struggle for Soviet Jewry]], founded in 1964. It was one of the first American organizations working to free Russian Jews, who were not allowed to emigrate during the [[Soviet era]]. The group used demonstrations, lobbying, and education to pressure the Soviet authorities into allowing Jews to leave the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/judaica/ejud_0002_0019_0_19306.html|title=Student Struggle for Soviet Jewry|accessdate=April 17, 2011|publisher=jewishvirtuallibrary.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncsj.org/AuxPages/043004JWeek_Birnbaum.shtml |title=Soviet Jewry, 40 Years Later |date=April 30, 2004 |publisher=ncsj.org |accessdate=April 17, 2011 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727114331/http://www.ncsj.org/AuxPages/043004JWeek_Birnbaum.shtml |archivedate=July 27, 2011 |df= }}</ref> In 2015, he published his memoir detailing his efforts to liberate Soviet Jews, ''Open Up the Iron Door: Memoirs of a Soviet Jewry Activist''. The book focuses on how grassroots activism and acts of civil disobedience led to important policy changes for the Soviet Jews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/rabbi-ben-greenberg/social-justice-with-roots_b_6587438.html?|title=Social Justice With Roots: What The Memoirs of a Soviet Jewry Activist Can Teach Us About Today|accessdate=May 5, 2015|publisher=Huffington Post}}</ref>\n\n=== In the United States ===\nWeiss was an official emissary of former New York Governor [[Mario Cuomo]] and former New York Mayor [[Rudolph Giuliani]].<ref name=\"archive\"/>\n\nWeiss has served as personal rabbi to [[Jonathan Pollard]], an American who spied for Israel sentenced to life in prison in 1987.<ref name=\"archive\"/> In 1992 Weiss was one of the signators to a full-page ad in ''[[The New York Times]]'' calling for the release of Pollard.<ref>{{cite news\n |url =http://www.jonathanpollard.org/1992/102592a.htm\n |title = American Rabbis Ask Bush to Give Pollard Clemency\n |work = The Jerusalem Post\n |date = October 25, 1992\n |accessdate = June 10, 2006\n | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060614162325/http://jonathanpollard.org/1992/102592a.htm| archivedate= June 14, 2006 <!--DASHBot-->|url-status = live}}</ref>\nIn 1989 Weiss conducted a \"freedom [[Passover Seder|Seder]]\" in front of the prison where Pollard was incarcerated.<ref>{{cite news\n |url=http://www.thejewishweek.com/features/jonathan_pollard_case_reflection_our_fears \n |title=The Jonathan Pollard Case: A Reflection Of Our Fears \n |publisher=The Jewish Week \n |date=June 28, 2002 \n |accessdate=April 17, 2011 \n |last=Besser \n |first=James D \n |url-status = dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110527051801/http://www.thejewishweek.com/features/jonathan_pollard_case_reflection_our_fears \n |archivedate=May 27, 2011 \n |df= \n}}</ref>\n\nAt a speech at New York City Hall in 2001 Weiss criticized President [[George W. Bush]] for not making a clearer distinction between Arab acts of terrorism and Israeli acts of self-defense. \"The trap that he's falling into is that he's drawn a moral equivalency between cold-blooded murder and acts of self-defense,\" Weiss said.\n<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/2001/06/02/2001-06-02_it_s_self-defense__rabbi_tel.html |location=New York |work=Daily News |title=It's Self-Defense, Rabbi Tells Bush |date=June 2, 2001 |accessdate=April 17, 2011 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629092441/http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/2001/06/02/2001-06-02_it_s_self-defense__rabbi_tel.html |archivedate=June 29, 2011 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2002 Weiss organized a pro-Israel rally on the [[National Mall]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/04/08/nyregion/demonstrators-roar-support-for-israel-444197.html?pagewanted=all | work=The New York Times | first=Robert D. | last=McFadden | title=Demonstrators Roar Support for Israel | date=April 8, 2002|accessdate=April 17, 2011}}</ref> and a boycott of several large newspapers perceived as having an anti-Israeli bias.<ref>\n{{cite news | first=Dan | last=Fost | title=Jewish Groups Battle Media Over Perceived Bias | date=May 2, 2002 | newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle | url=http://www.commondreams.org/headlines02/0502-03.htm | accessdate=April 17, 2011 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110524093431/http://www.commondreams.org/headlines02/0502-03.htm | archivedate=May 24, 2011 |url-status = dead| df= }}</ref>\n\nIn 2006 Weiss organized a protest in front of Syria's UN mission to denounce a [[Hezbollah]] offensive in the Middle East.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/2006/07/17/2006-07-17_dozens_protest_at_un_mission.html |title=Dozens Protest At Un Mission |last=Egbert |first=Bill |newspaper=Daily News |location=New York |accessdate=April 17, 2011 |date=July 17, 2006 }}{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2011, Weiss was arrested in front of the U.N. building in New York while protesting the Palestinian statehood bid.<ref name=\"Top50\"/>\n\nIn a July 15, 2015, [[Haaretz]] opinion piece, Weiss applauded the U.S. Supreme Court [[Obergefell v. Hodges|decision]] legalizing [[same-sex marriage]], which he saw as a part of maintaining the [[separation of church and state]] and protecting his right to refuse to perform gay weddings. He stated that he would not participate in same-sex weddings, because doing so would run contrary to his religious commitments, but that he had met countless gay individuals and couples, some of whom were members of his synagogue, who lived loving, exemplary lives. \"If I welcome with open arms those who do not observe Sabbath, Kashrut or family purity laws, I must welcome, even more so, homosexual Jews, as they are born with their orientation.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Weiss|first1=Avi|title=Why I, as an Orthodox Rabbi, Support Legalizing Same-sex Marriage\n|url=http://www.haaretz.com/opinion/1.666064|accessdate=14 December 2015|work=[[Haaretz]]|date=July 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== In Europe ===\nWeiss has travelled worldwide as an activist in various causes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://amchacjc.org/principles.html |title=Principles of Spiritual Activist |last=Weiss |first=Avi |publisher=amchacjc.org |accessdate=April 17, 2011}}</ref> In 1989 Weiss and others protested at a [[Carmelite]] convent that had been established at [[Auschwitz]]. The group\u2014dressed in [[concentration camp]] clothing\u2014scaled the walls of the convent, blew a [[shofar]], and screamed anti-[[Nazi]] slogans. Workers evicted them from the site.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/judaica/ejud_0002_0002_0_01611.html|title=Auschwitz Convent|publisher=Jewish Virtual Library|accessdate=April 16, 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110514032327/https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/judaica/ejud_0002_0002_0_01611.html| archivedate= May 14, 2011 <!--DASHBot-->|url-status = live}}</ref> In 1993 [[Pope John Paul II]] ordered the closure of the convent, which had been located in a converted building that had stored [[Zyklon B]] gas used to kill prisoners at the camp during World War II.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/04/15/world/pope-orders-nuns-out-of-auschwitz.html|last=Perlez |first=Jane|title= Pope Orders Nuns Out of Auschwitz |newspaper=The New York Times |date= April 15, 1993|accessdate=April 16, 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe protested President [[Ronald Reagan]]'s visit to an [[SS]] cemetery in 1985.<ref name=\"archive\"/> He was arrested in 1990 while protesting [[Kurt Waldheim]]'s visit to the [[Salzburg Festival]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,970799,00.html |title=Austria: The Trojan Guest |date=August 6, 1990 |work=Time |accessdate=April 17, 2011}}</ref> and again in 1994, when he protested in [[Oslo, Norway]], when [[PLO]] chief [[Yasser Arafat]] received the [[Nobel Peace Prize]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://alb.merlinone.net/mweb/wmsql.wm.request?oneimage&imageid=5701594 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723205336/http://alb.merlinone.net/mweb/wmsql.wm.request?oneimage&imageid=5701594 |url-status = dead|archive-date=July 23, 2011 |title=Peace Prize Triumvirate Denounced |newspaper=[[Times Union (Albany)|Times Union]] |location=Albany |agency=Associated Press |page=A2 |date=December 10, 1994 |accessdate=April 17, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nAlong with Rosa Sacharin of [[Glasgow, Scotland]], Weiss sued the [[American Jewish Committee]] in New York state court in 2003 to stop the construction of a path through the [[Belzec extermination camp]] in [[Poland]]. They were concerned that mass graves at the site would be disturbed by the work.<ref>{{cite news\n |first = Joe\n |last = Berkofsky\n |url = http://www.jewishsf.com/content/2-0-/module/displaystory/story_id/20693/edition_id/424/format/html/displaystory.html\n |title = Avi Weiss rekindles battle to block camp memorial\n |work = The Jewish News Weekly of Northern California\n |date = July 25, 2003\n |accessdate = June 10, 2006\n}}</ref>\n\n== Organizations ==\n*[[Hebrew Institute of Riverdale]] (synagogue where Weiss is one of the rabbis)\n*[[Yeshivat Chovevei Torah]] (founded by Weiss)\n*[[Yeshivat Maharat]] (founded by Weiss)\n*The coalition for Jewish concerns (Amcha) (founded by Weiss)\n\n== Works ==\n*{{cite book |title= Haggadah for the Yom HaShoah Seder|last=Weiss |first=Avi |year=2000 |publisher=Jonas Pub |location=Hackensack, NJ |isbn= 0-615-11519-5 }}\n*{{cite book |title=Principles of Spiritual Activism |last=Weiss |first=Avi |year=2001 |publisher=KTAV Publishing House |location=Hoboken, NJ |isbn=0-88125-737-0 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/principlesofspir0000weis }}\n*{{cite book |title= Women at Prayer: A Halakhic Analysis of Women's Prayer Groups|last=Weiss |first=Avi |year=2001 |publisher=KTAV Publishing House |location=Hoboken, NJ|isbn=0-88125-719-2 }}\n*{{cite book |title=The Yeshivat Chovevei Torah Tanakh Companion to the Book of Samuel |chapter=Avigayil: Savior of David|editor1-first=Nathaniel |editor1-last=Helfgot |last=Weiss |first=Avi |year=2006 |publisher= Ben Yehuda Press |location=Teaneck, NJ |isbn= 0-9769862-4-8 }}\n*{{cite book |title= Holistic Prayer: A Guide to Jewish Spirituality|last=Weiss |first=Avi |year=2014 |publisher=Maggid Books |location=Jerusalem |isbn= 978-1-592-64334-9 }}\n*{{cite book |title= Open Up the Iron Door: Memoirs of a Soviet Jewry Activist|last=Weiss |first=Avi |year=2015 |publisher=The Toby Press |location=Jerusalem |isbn= 978-1-592-64385-1 }}\n\n;Articles in ''Sh'ma: A Journal of Jewish Responsibility'':\n*''[http://www.bjpa.org/Publications/details.cfm?PublicationID=6444 Creating an Open Orthodox Rabbinate]'', with Dov Linzer, Vol. 33/no.597-598 2003.\n*''[http://www.bjpa.org/Publications/details.cfm?PublicationID=7126 A Congregation of Holy Souls: Reflections on 9/11 One Year Later]'' Vol.33/no.593 2002.\n*''[http://www.bjpa.org/Publications/details.cfm?PublicationID=7953 NiSh'ma:Apikorus]'', with Rebecca T. Alpert, Shmuley Boteach, Lisa S. Lehmann Vol.31/no.574 2000.\n*''[http://www.bjpa.org/Publications/details.cfm?PublicationID=8500 Endthoughts: Stolen Money and Stolen Souls]'', Vol.27/no.535 1997.\n*''[http://www.bjpa.org/Publications/details.cfm?PublicationID=7491 The Insurmountable Divisiveness of Patrilineality]'', Vol.25/no.469 1994.\n*''[http://www.bjpa.org/Publications/details.cfm?PublicationID=9579 With Jonathan Pollard]'', Vol.23/no.453 1993.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n*Mindell, Cindy. [http://www.jewishledger.com/2013/03/conversation-with-rabbi-avi-weiss/ Conversation with Rabbi Avi Weiss] ''Jewish Ledger'' (Connecticut edition), March 6, 2013\n*[http://www.bbc.co.uk/religion/religions/judaism/subdivisions/modernorthodoxy_1.shtml BBC, Modern Orthodoxy]: BBC summary of Modern Orthodox Judaism\n*[http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/122934 Rabbis on Their Way Home to Zion], ''Israel National News'', July 1, 2007\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hWifvGvcpTE A tribute video to Rabbi Avi and Toby Weiss] for [[Yeshivat Chovevei Torah]]'s 2014 Annual Dinner\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weiss, Avraham}}\n[[Category:People from the Bronx]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Jewish American community activists]]\n[[Category:Modern Orthodox rabbis]]\n[[Category:American Orthodox rabbis]]\n[[Category:20th-century rabbis]]\n[[Category:21st-century rabbis]]\n[[Category:Open Orthodox Judaism]]\n[[Category:Activists from New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "0123456editor", "label": "safe", "comment": "I added Neo-Conservatism in the headline becuase the open orthodox movement is often referred  to as such.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Avi_Weiss"}
