yle=background: #DDFFDD| | | | | | | |!||}}\n{{Familytree|boxstyle=background: #DDFFDD| | | | | | | MTJ | | |MTJ=[[Muhammad al-Taqi|Muhammad al-Jawad]]<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0645\u064f\u062d\u064e\u0645\u064e\u0651\u062f \u0671\u0644\u0652\u062c\u064e\u0648\u064e\u0651\u0627\u062f}})}}\n{{Familytree|boxstyle=background: #DDFFDD| | | | | | | |!||}}\n{{Familytree|boxstyle=background: #DDFFDD| | | | | | | AHN | | |AHN=[[Ali al-Hadi]]<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0639\u064e\u0644\u0650\u064a\u0651 \u0671\u0644\u0652\u0647\u064e\u0627\u062f\u0650\u064a}})}}\n{{Familytree|boxstyle=background: #DDFFDD| | | | | | | |!||}}\n{{Familytree|boxstyle=background: #DDFFDD| | | | | | | HBA | | |HBA=[[Hasan al-Askari]]<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u0652\u062d\u064e\u0633\u064e\u0646 \u0671\u0644\u0652\u0639\u064e\u0633\u0652\u0643\u064e\u0631\u0650\u064a\u0651}})}}\n{{Familytree|boxstyle=background: #DDFFDD| | | | | | | |!||}}\n{{Familytree|boxstyle=background: #DDFFDD| | | | | | | MBH | | |MBH=[[Hujjat-Allah al-Mahdi|Hujjat Allah al-Mahdi]]<br/>({{lang|ar|\u062d\u064f\u062c\u064e\u0651\u0629 \u0671\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0671\u0644\u0652\u0645\u064e\u0647\u0652\u062f\u0650\u064a\u0651}})}}\n{{Familytree/end}}\n\n==List of the Infallibles==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"margin-right: 0;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Islamic calligraphy|Calligraphic Name Depiction]]\n! scope=\"col\" | Name<hr>[[Kunya (Arabic)|Kunya]]\n! scope=\"col\" | Title<br />[[Arabic language|Arabic]]\n! scope=\"col\" | Date of birth and death\n*[[Common Era|CE]]\n*[[Islamic calendar|AH]]{{efn|The abbreviation CE refers to the [[Common Era]] [[solar calendar]], while AH refers to the Islamic [[Islamic calendar|Hijri]] [[lunar calendar]]}} <hr> Place of birth\n! scope=\"col\" | Importance\n! scope=\"col\" | Cause and place of death <hr>Place of burial{{efn|Except the Twelfth Imam}}\n|- \n| [[File:\u062a\u062e\u0637\u064a\u0637 \u0625\u0633\u0645 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f.png|100px]]\n| [[Muhammad|Muhammad ibn Abdullah]]<br />{{lang|ar|\u0645\u064f\u062d\u064e\u0645\u064e\u0651\u062f \u0671\u0628\u0652\u0646 \u0639\u064e\u0628\u0652\u062f \u0671\u0644\u0644\u064e\u0651\u0670\u0647 \u0635\u064e\u0644\u064e\u0651\u0649\u0670 \u0671\u0644\u0644\u064e\u0651\u0670\u0647\u064f \u0639\u064e\u0644\u064e\u064a\u0652\u0647\u0650 \u0648\u064e\u0622\u0644\u0650\u0647\u0650}}<br><hr>Abu al-Qasim<ref name=\"nasr 2006\"/><br />{{lang|ar|\u0623\u064e\u0628\u064f\u0648 \u0671\u0644\u0652\u0642\u064e\u0627\u0633\u0650\u0645}}\n|\n*''[[Ras\u016bl|Ras\u016bl All\u0101h]]''<br />({{lang|ar|\u0631\u064e\u0633\u064f\u0648\u0644 \u0671\u0644\u0644\u064e\u0651\u0670\u0647}})<br />(''Messenger of God'')<ref name=\"nasr 2006\"/>\n*''Kh\u0101tam al-\u02beAnbiy\u0101\u02be''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u062e\u064e\u0627\u062a\u064e\u0645 \u0671\u0644\u0652\u0623\u064e\u0646\u0652\u0628\u0650\u06cc\u064e\u0627\u0621}})<br />(''Seal of the Prophets'')<ref>{{harvnb|Mir|1987|p=171}}</ref>\n*''al-Mu\u1e63\u1e6daf\u0101''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u0652\u0645\u064f\u0635\u0652\u0637\u064e\u0641\u064e\u0649\u0670}})<br />(''The Chosen'')\n| {{bulleted list |570 \u2013 632<ref name=\"nasr 2006\">{{harvnb|Nasr|2006}}</ref>|53 BH<ref>{{Harvnb|Tabatabaei|1975|p=131}}</ref>\u201310<ref>{{Harvnb|Tabatabaei|1975|p=134}}</ref>}}\n----[[Mecca|Makkah]], [[Hejaz|Hijaz]]<ref name=\"nasr 2006\"/>\n| Considered by Muslims to be the [[Khatim an-Nabuwwah|last prophet]] sent by God to mankind. According to Muslims, God [[Wahy|revealed]] to him the [[Quran]], which is God's word.<ref name=\"nasr 2006\"/>\n| Fell ill and died in [[Medina|Madinah]].<ref name=\"nasr 2006\">{{harvnb|Nasr|2006}}</ref> <hr>\nBuried in [[Medina|Madinah]], [[Hejaz|Hijaz]].<ref name=\"nasr 2006\"/>\n|-\n| [[File:Fatimah Calligraphy.png|100px]]\n| [[Fatimah|Fatimah bint Muhammad]]<br />{{lang|ar|\u0641\u064e\u0627\u0637\u0650\u0645\u064e\u0629 \u0671\u0628\u0652\u0646\u064e\u062a \u0645\u064f\u062d\u064e\u0645\u064e\u0651\u062f \u0639\u064e\u0644\u064e\u064a\u0652\u0647\u064e\u0627 \u0671\u0644\u0633\u064e\u0651\u0644\u064e\u0627\u0645}}<hr>\u02beUmm \u02beAb\u012bh\u0101<ref>{{harvnb|Walbridge|2001|p=103}}</ref><br />{{lang|ar|\u0623\u064f\u0645\u0651 \u0623\u064e\u0628\u0650\u06cc\u0647\u064e\u0627}}\n|\n*''az-Zahr\u0101\u02be''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u0632\u064e\u0651\u0647\u0652\u0631\u064e\u0627\u0621}})<br />(''The Luminous'')<ref name=\"Chittick\">{{Harvnb|Chittick|1980|p=136}}</ref>\n*''Sayyidah an-Nis\u0101\u02be''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0633\u064e\u06cc\u0650\u0651\u062f\u064e\u0629 \u0671\u0644\u0646\u0650\u0651\u0633\u064e\u0627\u0621}})<br />(''The Chief of the Women'')<ref name=\"Klemm\">{{harvnb|Klemm|2014}}</ref>\n*''al-Bat\u016bl''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u0652\u0628\u064e\u062a\u064f\u0648\u0644}})<br />(''The Chaste'')<ref>{{harvnb|Ordoni|2009|p=94}}</ref>\n*''a\u1e6d-\u1e6c\u0101hirah''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u0637\u064e\u0651\u0627\u0647\u0650\u0631\u064e\u0629}})<br />(''The Pure'')<ref>{{harvnb|Ordoni|2009|p=70}}</ref>\n*''a\u1e63-\u1e62idd\u012bqah''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u0635\u0650\u0651\u062f\u0650\u0651\u06cc\u0642\u064e\u0629}})<br />(''The Honest'')<ref>{{harvnb|Ordoni|2009|p=56}}</ref>\n| {{bulleted list|615 \u2013 633 <ref name=\"Chittick\"/>|8 BH<ref>{{harvnb|Qurash\u012b|2007|p=38}}</ref>\u2013 11<ref name=\"Chitticka\">{{Harvnb|Chittick|1980|p=137}}</ref>}}\n----[[Mecca|Makkah]], [[Hejaz|Hijaz]]<ref name=\"Fatima\">{{Harvnb|Dungersi|1994|p=4}}</ref>\n| Her father Muhammad called her \"a part of me\".<ref name=\"Chittick\"/> She is also regarded as \"the mother of the Imams\".<ref>{{Harvnb|Hughes|2013|p=258}}</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Rayshahri|2008|p=68}}</ref>\n| According to most Shias, Fatimah suffered a fatal injury while defending Ali against the first Sunni caliph.<ref>{{harvnb|Lammens|2012}}</ref> <hr>\nThe exact location of [[Burial place of Fatimah|her grave]] is unknown but is believed to be in [[Medina|Madinah]].<ref name=\"Klemm\"/>\n|-\n| [[File:Al\u012b.png|100px]]\n| [[Ali|Ali ibn Abi Talib]]<br />{{lang|ar|\u0639\u064e\u0644\u0650\u064a\u0651 \u0671\u0628\u0652\u0646 \u0623\u064e\u0628\u0650\u064a \u0637\u064e\u0627\u0644\u0650\u0628 \u0639\u064e\u0644\u064e\u064a\u0652\u0647\u0650 \u0671\u0644\u0633\u064e\u0651\u0644\u064e\u0627\u0645}}<hr>Abu al-Hasan<ref name=Rizvia>{{harvnb|Rizvi|1988|p=48}}</ref><br />{{lang|ar|\u0623\u064e\u0628\u064f\u0648 \u0671\u0644\u0652\u062d\u064e\u0633\u064e\u0646}}\n|\n*''[[Amir al-Mu'minin|\u02beAm\u012br al-Mu\u02bemin\u012bn]]''<br />({{lang|ar|\u0623\u064e\u0645\u0650\u064a\u0631 \u0671\u0644\u0652\u0645\u064f\u0624\u0652\u0645\u0650\u0646\u0650\u064a\u0646}})<br />(''Commander of the Faithful'')<ref name=\"Ali in Britannica\">{{cite encyclopedia|last=Nasr |first=Seyyed Hossein | authorlink=Seyyed Hossein Nasr | title=Ali | encyclopedia=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Online | accessdate=2007-10-12|url=http://www.britannica.com/eb/article-9005712/Ali}}</ref><br />\n*''al-Murta\u1e0d\u0101''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u0652\u0645\u064f\u0631\u0652\u062a\u064e\u0636\u064e\u0649\u0670}})<br />(''The Beloved'')\n*''al-Wa\u1e63\u012by''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u0652\u0648\u064e\u0635\u0650\u064a\u0651}})<br />(''The Successor'')\n*''al-Wal\u012by''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u0652\u0648\u064e\u0644\u0650\u064a\u0651}})<br />(''The [[Wali]]'')\n| {{bulleted list|600 \u2013 661<ref name=\"Ali in Britannica\"/>|22 or 16 BH \u2013 40 AH <ref>{{Harvnb|Ahmed|2005|p=234}}</ref>}} <hr>[[Mecca|Makkah]], [[Hejaz|Hijaz]]<ref name=\"Ali in Britannica\"/>\n| For all [[Shia]], the son-in-law of  Muhammad is the first Shia Imam<ref name=\"\u02bfAL\u012a B. AB\u012a \u1e6c\u0100LEB Iranica\">{{Harvnb|Poonawala|1985}}</ref> and the rightful [[Succession to Muhammad|successor to Muhammad]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Mashita|2002|p=69}}</ref> For [[Sunni]]s, he is the [[Rashidun|fourth successor]].<ref name=\"Chitticka\"/> He holds an important position in almost all [[Sufism|Sufi]] [[Tariqah|orders]], which trace their lineage to Muhammad through him.<ref name=\"Ali in Britannica\"/>\n| Assassinated in [[Kufa]], Iraq, by [[Abd-al-Rahman ibn Muljam]], a [[Kharijite]] who slashed his head with a poisoned sword while he was praying.<ref name=\"Ali in Britannica\"/><hr>Buried in [[Najaf]], Iraq.<ref name=\"Chitticka\"/>\n|-\n| [[File:Hassan ibn Ali.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Hasan ibn Ali]]<br />{{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u0652\u062d\u064e\u0633\u064e\u0646 \u0671\u0628\u0652\u0646 \u0639\u064e\u0644\u0650\u064a\u0651 \u0639\u064e\u0644\u064e\u064a\u0652\u0647\u0650 \u0671\u0644\u0633\u064e\u0651\u0644\u064e\u0627\u0645}}<hr>Abu Muhammad<ref name=Rizvia/><br />{{lang|ar|\u0623\u064e\u0628\u064f\u0648 \u0645\u064f\u062d\u064e\u0645\u064e\u0651\u062f}}\n|\n*''al-Mujtab\u0101''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u0652\u0645\u064f\u062c\u0652\u062a\u064e\u0628\u064e\u0649\u0670}})<br />(''The Chosen'')<ref>{{Harvnb|Corbin|1993|p=50}}</ref><br/>\n*''Sib\u1e6d an-Nab\u012by''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0633\u0650\u0628\u0652\u0637 \u0671\u0644\u0646\u064e\u0651\u0628\u0650\u064a\u0651}})<br />(''Tribe of the Prophet'')\n| {{bulleted list|625 \u2013 670<ref name=\"Hasan ibn Ali Iranica\">{{Harvnb|Madelung|2003}}</ref>|3 \u2013 50<ref name=\"Chitticka\"/>}} <hr>[[Medina|Madinah]], [[Hejaz|Hijaz]]<ref name=\"Hasan ibn Ali Iranica\"/>\n| The eldest surviving grandson of Muhammad, through his mother, Fatimah, Hasan succeeded his father Ali as the caliph in Kufa; but after a seven-month reign he relinquished control of Iraq following a peace treaty with [[Muawiya I]].<ref name=\"Hasan ibn Ali Iranica\"/>\n|He was poisoned fatally by his wife in Madinah by order of Caliph [[Muawiya]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Tabatabaei|1975|p=173}}</ref><hr> Buried in [[Jannat al-Baqi]], [[Medina|Madinah]].<ref name=\"Hasan ibn Ali Iranica\"/>\n|-\n| [[File:Hhussain ibn ali.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Husayn ibn Ali]]<br />{{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u0652\u062d\u064f\u0633\u064e\u064a\u0652\u0646 \u0671\u0628\u0652\u0646 \u0639\u064e\u0644\u0650\u064a\u0651 \u0639\u064e\u0644\u064e\u064a\u0652\u0647\u0650 \u0671\u0644\u0633\u064e\u0651\u0644\u064e\u0627\u0645}}<hr>Abu Abdillah<ref name=Rizvib>{{harvnb|Rizvi|1988|p=49}}</ref><br />{{lang|ar|\u0623\u064e\u0628\u064f\u0648 \u0639\u064e\u0628\u0652\u062f \u0671\u0644\u0644\u064e\u0651\u0670\u0647}}\n|\n*''Sayyid ash-Shuhad\u0101\u02be''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0633\u064e\u064a\u0650\u0651\u062f \u0671\u0644\u0634\u064f\u0651\u0647\u064e\u062f\u064e\u0627\u0621}})<br />(''Master of the Martyrs'')<ref name=Amir-Moezzi1994/>\n*''al-Ma\u1e93l\u016bm''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u0652\u0645\u064e\u0638\u0652\u0644\u064f\u0648\u0645}})<br/>(''The Tyrannized'')\n*''Sib\u1e6d an-Nab\u012by''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0633\u0650\u0628\u0652\u0637 \u0671\u0644\u0646\u064e\u0651\u0628\u0650\u064a\u0651}})<br />(''Tribe of the Prophet'')\n| {{bulleted list|626 \u2013 680<ref name=\"Tabatabaei 1975 198 \u2013 199\">{{Harvnb|Tabatabaei|1975|pp=198\u2013199}}</ref>|4 \u2013 61<ref name=\"Chitticka\"/>}} <hr>[[Medina|Madinah]], [[Hejaz|Hijaz]]<ref name=\"Husayn ibn Ali Iranica\"/>\n| Grandson of Muhammad and younger brother of Hasan, Husayn rejected the legitimacy of Caliph [[Yazid I]], the son of Muawiyah. As a result, he and his family were  killed in the [[Battle of Karbala]] by Yazid's forces.<ref name=\"Chitticka\"/> Ever since the battle, the [[Arba'een|commemoration of Husayn ibn Ali's martyrdom]] has been at the core of Shia rituals and identity.<ref name=\"Husayn ibn Ali Iranica\">{{Harvnb|Madelung|2004}}</ref>\n| Killed and beheaded at the Battle of Karbala.<ref name=\"Husayn ibn Ali Iranica\"/><hr> Buried at the [[Imam Husayn Shrine]], [[Karbala]], Iraq.<ref name=\"Husayn ibn Ali Iranica\"/>\n|-\n| [[File:Imam sajjad.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Ali ibn Husayn]]<br />{{lang|ar|\u0639\u064e\u0644\u0650\u064a\u0651 \u0671\u0628\u0652\u0646 \u0671\u0644\u0652\u062d\u064f\u0633\u064e\u064a\u0652\u0646 \u0671\u0644\u0633\u064e\u0651\u062c\u064e\u0651\u0627\u062f \u0639\u064e\u0644\u064e\u064a\u0652\u0647\u0650 \u0671\u0644\u0633\u064e\u0651\u0644\u064e\u0627\u0645}}<hr>Abu Muhammad<ref>{{harvnb|Qurash\u012b|2007|p=17}}</ref><br />{{lang|ar|\u0623\u064e\u0628\u064f\u0648 \u0645\u064f\u062d\u064e\u0645\u064e\u0651\u062f}}\n|\n*''as-Sajj\u0101d''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u0633\u064e\u0651\u062c\u064e\u0651\u0627\u062f}})<br />(''The Consistently Prostrating'')<ref name=\"Chittickb\">{{Harvnb|Chittick|1980|p=138}}</ref>\n*''Zayn al-\u02bf\u0100bid\u012bn''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0632\u064e\u064a\u0652\u0646 \u0671\u0644\u0652\u0639\u064e\u0627\u0628\u0650\u062f\u0650\u064a\u0646}})<br />(''Ornament of the Worshippers'')<ref name=\"Ali ibn Husayn in Iranica1\">{{Harvnb|Madelung|1985}}</ref><ref name=\"Ali ibn Husayn in Iranica\">{{cite encyclopedia|last=Madelung |first=Wilferd | authorlink=Wilferd Madelung | title=\u02bfAL\u012a B. \u1e24OSAYN B. \u02bfAL\u012a B. AB\u012a \u1e6c\u0100LEB, ZAYN-AL-\u02bf\u0100BED\u012aN | encyclopedia=Encyclopaedia Iranica | accessdate=2007-11-08 |url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/ali-b-hosayn-b-ali }}</ref>\n| {{bulleted list|658/59<ref name=\"Ali ibn Husayn in Iranica\"/> \u2013 712<ref name=\"Tabatabae\">{{Harvnb|Tabatabaei|1975|pp=178\u2013179}}</ref>|38<ref name=\"Ali ibn Husayn in Iranica\"/>\u2013 95 <ref name=\"Chittickb\"/><ref name=\"Tabatabae\"/>}} <hr>[[Medina|Madinah]], [[Hejaz|Hijaz]]<ref name=\"Ali ibn Husayn in Iranica\"/>\n| The author of the prayers in [[Al-Sahifa al-Sajjadiyya]],<ref name=\"Chittickb\"/> (\"The Scripture of Al-Sajjad\", \"The Psalm of [[Ahl al-Bayt|the Household of the Prophet]]\").<ref name=\"Tabatabae\"/>\n| He was fatally poisoned by order of Caliph [[al-Walid I]] in Madinah.<ref name=\"Tabatabae\"/><hr> Buried in [[Jannat al-Baqi]], [[Medina|Madinah]].<ref name=\"Chittickb\"/>\n|-\n| [[File:Baqir ibn sajjad.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Muhammad al-Baqir|Muhammad ibn Ali]]<br />{{lang|ar|\u0645\u064f\u062d\u064e\u0645\u064e\u0651\u062f \u0671\u0628\u0652\u0646 \u0639\u064e\u0644\u0650\u064a\u0651 \u0671\u0644\u0652\u0628\u064e\u0627\u0642\u0650\u0631 \u0639\u064e\u0644\u064e\u064a\u0652\u0647\u0650 \u0671\u0644\u0633\u064e\u0651\u0644\u064e\u0627\u0645}}<hr>Abu Ja'far<ref name=Rizvib/><ref name=\"Muhammad al-Baqir in Iranica\"/><br />{{lang|ar|\u0623\u064e\u0628\u064f\u0648 \u062c\u064e\u0639\u0652\u0641\u064e\u0631}}\n|\n*''B\u0101qir al-\u02bfUl\u016bm''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0628\u064e\u0627\u0642\u0650\u0631 \u0671\u0644\u0652\u0639\u064f\u0644\u064f\u0648\u0645}})<br />(''The Opener of Knowledge'')<ref name=\"Muhammad al-Baqir in Iranica1\">{{Harvnb|Madelung|1988}}</ref><ref name=\"Muhammad al-Baqir in Iranica\">{{cite encyclopedia|last=Madelung |first=Wilferd | authorlink=Wilferd Madelung | title=B\u0100QER, AB\u016a JA\u02bfFAR MO\u1e24AMMAD | encyclopedia=Encyclopaedia Iranica | accessdate=2007-11-08 |url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/baqer-abu-jafar-mohammad }}</ref>\n| {{bulleted list|677 \u2013 732<ref name=\"Muhammad al-Baqir in Iranica\"/>|57 \u2013 114<ref name=\"Muhammad al-Baqir in Iranica\"/>}} <hr>[[Medina|Madinah]], [[Hejaz|Hijaz]]<ref name=\"Muhammad al-Baqir in Iranica\"/>\n| Sunni and Shia sources consider Al-Baqir an early and pre-eminent [[Faq\u012bh|legal scholar]] who was revered for having educated many students.<ref name=\"Chittickb\"/><ref name=\"Muhammad al-Baqir in Iranica\"/>\n| He was fatally poisoned by Ibrahim ibn Walid ibn 'Abdallah in Madinah by order of Caliph [[Hisham ibn Abd al-Malik]]. <hr>Buried in [[Jannat al-Baqi]], [[Medina|Madinah]]<ref name=\"Chittickb\"/>\n|-\n| [[File:Jaffer-e-Sadiq.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Jafar al-Sadiq|Ja'far ibn Muhammad]]<br />{{lang|ar|\u062c\u064e\u0639\u0652\u0641\u064e\u0631 \u0671\u0628\u0652\u0646 \u0645\u064f\u062d\u064e\u0645\u064e\u0651\u062f \u0671\u0644\u0635\u064e\u0651\u0627\u062f\u0650\u0642 \u0639\u064e\u0644\u064e\u064a\u0652\u0647\u0650 \u0671\u0644\u0633\u064e\u0651\u0644\u064e\u0627\u0645}}<hr>Abu Abdillah<ref name=\"Jafar al-Sadiq in Iranica\">{{cite encyclopedia|last= |first= | authorlink= | title=JA\u02bfFAR AL-\u1e62\u0100DEQ, ABU \u02bfABD-ALL\u0100H | encyclopedia=Encyclopaedia Iranica | accessdate=2014-07-07 |url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/jafar-al-sadeq }}</ref><ref name=\"Chittickb\"/><br />{{lang|ar|\u0623\u064e\u0628\u064f\u0648 \u0639\u064e\u0628\u0652\u062f \u0671\u0644\u0644\u064e\u0651\u0670\u0647}}\n|\n*''a\u1e63-\u1e62\u0101diq''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u0635\u064e\u0651\u0627\u062f\u0650\u0642}})<br />(''The Honest'')<ref>{{Harvnb|Tabatabaei|1975|p=15}}</ref><ref name=\"Jafar al-Sadiq\">Tabatabae (1979), p.203\u2013204</ref>\n| {{bulleted list|702 \u2013 765<ref name=\"Chittickb\"/>|83 \u2013 148<ref name=\"Chittickb\"/>}} <hr>[[Medina|Madinah]], [[Hejaz|Hijaz]]<ref name=\"t180\"/>\n| As-Sadiq established the [[Ja'fari jurisprudence|Ja'fari school of jurisprudence]] and developed the [[Twelver#Theology|theology of the Twelvers]].<ref name=\"Chittickb\"/> He taught many scholars in different fields, including [[Abu Hanifah]]<ref name=\"Chittickb\"/> and [[Malik ibn Anas]] in [[fiqh]], [[Wasil ibn Ata]] and [[Hisham ibn Hakam]] in [[Kalam|Islamic theology]], and [[J\u0101bir ibn Hayy\u0101n|Geber]] in science and alchemy.<ref name=\"t180\">{{harvnb|Tabatabaei|1975|p=180}}</ref>\n| He was fatally poisoned in Madinah by order of Caliph [[Al-Mansur]].<ref name=\"t180\"/><hr> Buried in [[Jannat al-Baqi]], [[Medina|Madinah]]<ref name=\"Chittickb\"/>\n|-\n| [[File:Al-Kazim.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Musa al-Kazim|Musa ibn Ja'far]]<br />{{lang|ar|\u0645\u064f\u0648\u0633\u064e\u0649\u0670 \u0671\u0628\u0652\u0646 \u062c\u064e\u0639\u0652\u0641\u064e\u0631 \u0671\u0644\u0652\u0643\u064e\u0627\u0638\u0650\u0645 \u0639\u064e\u0644\u064e\u064a\u0652\u0647\u0650 \u0671\u0644\u0633\u064e\u0651\u0644\u064e\u0627\u0645}}<hr>Abu al-Hasan I<ref name=\"Ali al-Reza in Iranica1\">{{Harvnb|Madelung|1985b}}</ref><ref name=\"Ali al-Reza in Iranica\">{{cite encyclopedia|last=Madelung |first=Wilferd | authorlink=Wilferd Madelung | title= \u02bfAL\u012a AL-RE\u017b\u0100 | encyclopedia=Encyclopaedia Iranica | accessdate=2007-11-09 |url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/ali-al-reza}}</ref><br />{{lang|ar|\u0623\u064e\u0628\u064f\u0648 \u0671\u0644\u0652\u062d\u064e\u0633\u064e\u0646 \u0671\u0644\u0652\u0623\u064e\u0648\u064e\u0651\u0644}}\n|\n*''al-K\u0101\u1e93im''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u0652\u0643\u064e\u0627\u0638\u0650\u0645}})<br />(''The Confined'')<ref name=\"Musa al-Kazim\">{{Harvnb|Tabatabaei|1975|p=181}}</ref>\n| {{bulleted list|744 \u2013 799<ref name=\"Chittickb\"/>|128 \u2013 183<ref name=\"Chittickb\"/>}} <hr>[[Medina|Madinah]], [[Hejaz|Hijaz]]<ref name=\"Musa al-Kazim\"/>\n| Al-Kazim was leader of the Shia community during the schism between the [[Ismaili]] and other branches of Islam after the death of the previous Imam Jafar al-Sadiq.<ref>{{Harvnb|Tabatabaei|1975|p=68}}</ref> He established a network of agents who collected the [[khums]] in the Shia community of the Middle East and the [[Greater Khorasan]]. He holds a high position in the [[Mahdavia]], the members of which trace their lineage to Muhammad through him.<ref>{{Harvnb|Sachedina|1988|pp=53\u201354}}</ref>\n| He was imprisoned and fatally poisoned in [[Baghdad]], Iraq, by order of Caliph [[Harun al-Rashid]].<ref>{{harvnb|Amir-Moezzi|2011|p=207}}</ref> <hr> Buried in the [[Kazimayn|Kazimayn shrine]], Baghdad, Iraq<ref name=\"Chittickb\"/><ref name=\"Musa al-Kazim\"/>\n|-\n| [[File:Al redah.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Ali al-Rida|Ali ibn Musa]]<br />{{lang|ar|\u0639\u064e\u0644\u0650\u064a\u0651 \u0671\u0628\u0652\u0646 \u0645\u064f\u0648\u0633\u064e\u0649\u0670 \u0671\u0644\u0631\u0650\u0651\u0636\u064e\u0627 \u0639\u064e\u0644\u064e\u064a\u0652\u0647\u0650 \u0671\u0644\u0633\u064e\u0651\u0644\u064e\u0627\u0645}}<hr>Abu al-Hasan II<ref name=\"Ali al-Reza in Iranica\"/><br />{{lang|ar|\u0623\u064e\u0628\u064f\u0648 \u0671\u0644\u0652\u062d\u064e\u0633\u064e\u0646 \u0671\u0644\u062b\u064e\u0651\u0627\u0646\u0650\u064a}}\n|\n*''ar-Ri\u1e0d\u0101''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u0631\u0650\u0651\u0636\u064e\u0627}})<br />(''The Pleasing'')<ref name=\"Musa al-Kazim\"/><ref name=\"Ali al-Reza\">Tabatabae (1979), pp.205\u2013207</ref>\n| {{bulleted list|765 \u2013 817<ref name=\"Chittickb\"/>|148 \u2013 203<ref name=\"Chittickb\"/>}} <hr>[[Medina|Madinah]],<br /> [[Hejaz|Hijaz]]<ref>{{Harvnb|Tabatabaei|1975|pp=182\u2013183}}</ref>\n| Made crown prince by Caliph [[Al-Ma'mun]], Ar-Rida was known for his discussions and debates with both Muslim and non-Muslim religious scholars.<ref name=\"Chittickc\">{{Harvnb|Chittick|1980|p=139}}</ref>\n| He was fatally poisoned in [[Mashad]], Iran, by order of Caliph Al-Ma'mun.<ref name=\"Chittickc\"/> <hr> Buried in the [[Imam Reza shrine]], [[Mashad]], Iran<ref name=\"Chittickc\"/>\n|-\n| [[File:Imam Taqi.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Muhammad al-Taqi|Muhammad ibn Ali]]<br />{{lang|ar|\u0645\u064f\u062d\u064e\u0645\u064e\u0651\u062f \u0671\u0628\u0652\u0646 \u0639\u064e\u0644\u0650\u064a\u0651 \u0671\u0644\u0652\u062c\u064e\u0648\u064e\u0651\u0627\u062f \u0639\u064e\u0644\u064e\u064a\u0652\u0647\u0650 \u0671\u0644\u0633\u064e\u0651\u0644\u064e\u0627\u0645}}<hr>Abu Ja'far<ref name=Rizvib/><br />{{lang|ar|\u0623\u064e\u0628\u064f\u0648 \u062c\u064e\u0639\u0652\u0641\u064e\u0631}}\n|\n*''al-Jaww\u0101d''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u0652\u062c\u064e\u0648\u064e\u0651\u0627\u062f}})<br />(''The Generous'')<ref name=\"Muhammad al-Taqi1\">{{Harvnb|Tabatabaei|1975|p=183}}</ref><ref name=\"Muhammad al-Taqi\">Tabatabae (1979), p. 207</ref>\n*''at-Taq\u012by''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u062a\u064e\u0651\u0642\u0650\u064a\u0651}})<br />(''The God-Fearing'')<ref name=\"Chittickc\"/><ref name=\"Muhammad al-Taqi\" />\n| {{bulleted list|809<ref name=\"Chittickc\"/> or 810 \u2013 835<ref name=\"Chittickc\"/>|195 \u2013 220<ref name=\"Muhammad al-Taqi\"/>}} <hr>[[Medina|Madinah]],<br /> [[Hejaz|Hijaz]]<ref name=\"Muhammad al-Taqi\"/>\n| Al-Jawad was known for his generosity and piety in the face of persecution by the [[Abbasid|Abbasid caliphate]].<ref name=\"Qurashi 2005\">{{harvnb|Qurash\u012b|2005}}</ref>\n| He was fatally poisoned by his wife, the daughter of Caliph Al-Ma'mun, in Baghdad, Iraq, by order of Caliph [[Al-Mu'tasim]].<ref name=\"Muhammad al-Taqi\"/><hr> Buried in the [[Kazmain|Kazmain shrine]], Baghdad, Iraq.<ref name=\"Chittickc\"/>\n|-\n| [[File:Imam naqi.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Ali al-Hadi|Ali ibn Muhammad]]<br />{{lang|ar|\u0639\u064e\u0644\u0650\u064a\u0651 \u0671\u0628\u0652\u0646 \u0645\u064f\u062d\u064e\u0645\u064e\u0651\u062f \u0671\u0644\u0652\u0647\u064e\u0627\u062f\u0650\u064a \u0639\u064e\u0644\u064e\u064a\u0652\u0647\u0650 \u0671\u0644\u0633\u064e\u0651\u0644\u064e\u0627\u0645}}<hr>Abu al-Hasan III<ref name=\"Ali al-Hadi in Iranica1\">{{Harvnb|Madelung|1985a}}</ref><br />{{lang|ar|\u0623\u064e\u0628\u064f\u0648 \u0671\u0644\u0652\u062d\u064e\u0633\u064e\u0646 \u0671\u0644\u062b\u064e\u0651\u0627\u0644\u0650\u062b}}\n|\n*''al-H\u0101d\u012b''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u0652\u0647\u064e\u0627\u062f\u0650\u064a}})<br />(''The Guide'')<ref>{{harvnb|Dungersi|2005|p=16}}</ref><ref name=\"Ali al-Hadi in Iranica\">{{cite encyclopedia|last=Madelung |first=Wilferd | authorlink=Wilferd Madelung | title= \u02bfAL\u012a AL-H\u0100D\u012a  | encyclopedia=Encyclopaedia Iranica | accessdate=2007-11-08 |url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/ali-al-hadi-abul-hasan-b}}</ref>\n*''an-Naq\u012by''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u0646\u064e\u0651\u0642\u0650\u064a\u0651}})<br />(''The Pure'')<ref name=\"Chittickc\"/><ref name=\"Ali al-Hadi in Iranica\" />\n| {{bulleted list|828 \u2013 868 <ref name=\"Ali al-Hadi in Iranica\"/>|212 \u2013 254<ref name=\"Ali al-Hadi in Iranica\"/>}} <hr>Surayya, a village near [[Medina|Madinah]], [[Hejaz|Hijaz]]<ref name=\"Ali al-Hadi in Iranica\"/>\n| Al-Naqi taught religious sciences until 243/857.<ref name=\"Chittickc\"/> He strengthened the network of deputies in the Shia community. He sent them instructions and in turn received financial contributions from the faithful, from the [[khums]] and religious vows.<ref name=\"Ali al-Hadi in Iranica\"/>\n| He was fatally poisoned in [[Samarra]], Iraq, by order of caliph [[Al-Mu'tazz]].<ref name=\"Muhammad al-Taqi\"/> <hr> Buried in the [[Al Askari Mosque]], Samarra, Iraq.<ref name=\"Chittickc\"/>\n|-\n| [[File:Al-askari.svg|100px]]\n| [[Hasan al-Askari|Hasan ibn Ali]]<br />{{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u0652\u062d\u064e\u0633\u064e\u0646 \u0671\u0628\u0652\u0646 \u0639\u064e\u0644\u0650\u064a\u0651 \u0671\u0644\u0652\u0639\u064e\u0633\u0652\u0643\u064e\u0631\u0650\u064a\u0651 \u0639\u064e\u0644\u064e\u064a\u0652\u0647\u0650 \u0671\u0644\u0633\u064e\u0651\u0644\u064e\u0627\u0645}}<hr>Abu al-Mahdi<ref name=Rizvic>{{harvnb|Rizvi|1988|p=50}}</ref><br />{{lang|ar|\u0623\u064e\u0628\u064f\u0648 \u0671\u0644\u0652\u0645\u064e\u0647\u0652\u062f\u0650\u064a\u0651}}\n|\n*''al-\u02bfAskar\u012by''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u0652\u0639\u064e\u0633\u0652\u0643\u064e\u0631\u0650\u064a\u0651}})<br />(''The Garrison Town One'')<ref name=\"al-Askari in Iranica\">{{Harvnb|Halm|1987}}</ref><ref name=\"al-Askari in Iranica\">{{cite encyclopedia|last=Halm |first=H | authorlink= | title=\u02bfASKAR\u012a | encyclopedia=Encyclopaedia Iranica | accessdate=2007-11-08 |url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/askari-abu-mohammad-hasan-b}}</ref>\n| {{bulleted list|845/6 \u2013 874<ref name=\"al-Askari in Iranica\"/>|231 \u2013 260 <ref name=\"al-Askari in Iranica\"/>}} <hr>[[Medina|Madinah]],<br /> [[Hejaz|Hijaz]]<ref name=\"al-Askari in Iranica\"/>\n| Like his father, Al-Askari was placed under house arrest, which would last most of his life, by the Abbasid Caliph [[Al-Mu'tamid]], .<ref>{{Harvnb|Dungersi|2005|p=188}}</ref> During this time, repression of the Shia communities was great because of their growing size and power.<ref name=\"Tabatabae 1979 209 \u2013 210\">{{Harvnb|Tabatabaei|1975|p=184}}</ref>\n| He was fatally poisoned by order of Caliph Al-Mu'tamid in Samarra, Iraq.<ref>{{Harvnb|Dungersi|2005|p=196}}</ref><hr> Buried in the Al Askari Mosque, Samarra, Iraq.<ref name=\"Chittickc\"/>\n|-\n| [[File:Al mehdi.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Hujjat-Allah al-Mahdi|Hujjat Allah ibn al-Hasan]]<br />{{lang|ar|\u062d\u064f\u062c\u064e\u0651\u0629 \u0671\u0644\u0644\u064e\u0651\u0670\u0647 \u0671\u0628\u0652\u0646 \u0671\u0644\u0652\u062d\u064e\u0633\u064e\u0646 \u0671\u0644\u0652\u0645\u064e\u0647\u0652\u062f\u0650\u064a\u0651 \u0639\u064e\u0644\u064e\u064a\u0652\u0647\u0650 \u0671\u0644\u0633\u064e\u0651\u0644\u064e\u0627\u0645}}<hr>Abu al-Qasim<ref name=Amir-Moezzi1994>{{Harvnb|Amir-Moezzi|1994|p=174}}</ref><br />{{lang|ar|\u0623\u064e\u0628\u064f\u0648 \u0671\u0644\u0652\u0642\u064e\u0627\u0633\u0650\u0645}}\n|\n*''[[Mahdi|al-Mahd\u012by]]''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u0652\u0645\u064e\u0647\u0652\u062f\u0650\u064a\u0651}})<br />(''The Guided'')<ref>{{Harvnb|Amir-Moezzi|2007}}</ref><ref name=\"MAHDI in Iranica\">{{cite encyclopedia|last= |first= | authorlink= | title=THE CONCEPT OF MAHDI IN TWELVER SHI\u02bfISM | encyclopedia=Encyclopaedia Iranica | accessdate=2014-07-07 |url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/islam-in-iran-vii-the-concept-of-mahdi-in-twelver-shiism}}</ref>\n*''al-Q\u0101\u02beim''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u0652\u0642\u064e\u0627\u0626\u0650\u0645}})<br />(''The Riser'')<ref name=Amir-Moezzi1994/>\n*''al-Gh\u0101\u02beib''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u0652\u063a\u064e\u0627\u0626\u0650\u0628}})<br />(''[[The Occultation|The Hidden]]'')<ref>{{Harvnb|Amir-Moezzi|1994|p=115}}</ref><ref name=\"\u1e20AYBA in Iranica\">{{cite encyclopedia|last= |first= | authorlink= | title=\u1e20AYBA | encyclopedia=Encyclopaedia Iranica | accessdate=2014-07-07 |url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/gayba}}</ref>\n*''S\u0101hib az-Zam\u0101n''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0635\u064e\u0627\u062d\u0650\u0628 \u0671\u0644\u0632\u064e\u0651\u0645\u064e\u0627\u0646}})<br />(''The Authority of the Era'')<ref name=Rizvic/>\n*''[[Ahl al-Bayt|al-\u1e24ujjah \u02be\u0100l Mu\u1e25ammad]]''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u0652\u062d\u064f\u062c\u064e\u0651\u0629 \u0622\u0644 \u0645\u064f\u062d\u064e\u0645\u064e\u0651\u062f}})<br />(''The [[Hujjah|Proof]] of the House of Muhammad'')<ref name=\"al-Hujjah in Britannica\">{{cite encyclopedia| title=Muhammad al-Mahdi al-Hujjah | encyclopedia=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Online | accessdate=2007-11-08 |url=http://www.britannica.com/eb/article-9054165/Muhammad-al-Mahdi-al-Hujjah}}</ref>\n| {{bulleted list|868 \u2013 Present<ref name=\"al-Hujjah\">{{Harvnb|Tabatabaei|1975|p=186}}</ref>|255 or 256<ref name=\"Chittickc\"/> \u2013 Present<ref name=\"al-Hujjah\"/>}} <hr>[[Samarra]], [[Iraq]]<ref>{{harvnb|Tabatabaei|1975|p=185}}</ref>\n| According to Twelver Shia doctrine, he is the current Imam and the promised [[Mahdi]], a messianic figure who will return with the prophet [[Jesus in Islam|Isa]] ([[Jesus]]). He will reestablish the rightful governance of Islam and establish justice and peace in the earth.<ref>{{Harvnb|Tabatabaei|1979|pp=211\u2013214}}</ref>\n| According to Twelver Shia doctrine, he has been living in the [[The Occultation|Occultation]] since 872, and will continue as long as God wills.<ref name=\"al-Hujjah\"/>\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n{{portal|Shia Islam}}\n{{Twelvers|collapsed=2}}\n\n* [[Shia Islam]]\n* [[Twelvers]]\n* [[Ahl al-Bayt]]\n* [[Ahl al-Kisa]]\n* [[Twelve Imams]]\n* [[Imamate in Twelver doctrine|Imamat doctrine]]\n* [[Ismah]]\n* [[Criticism of Twelver Shia Islam#Infallibility of Imams]]\n* [[Salawat]]\n\n==Notes and references==\n\n===Notes===\n{{notes|30em}}\n\n===References===\n{{reflist|colwidth=25em|refs=}}\n\n===Sources===\n\n; Encyclopedias\n* {{cite book|last = Ahmed|first = M. Mukarram|title = Encyclopaedia of Islam|publisher=Anmol Publications Pvt. Ltd.| year = 2005|isbn = 978-81-261-2339-1 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite encyclopedia |last=Algar |first=Hamid | authorlink=Hamid Algar | title=Chahardah M'asum | encyclopedia=Encyclop\u00e6dia Iranica | accessdate=2008-07-18 |url=http://www