holar]] who was revered for having educated many students.<ref name=\"Chittickb\"/><ref name=\"Muhammad al-Baqir in Iranica\"/>\n| He was fatally poisoned by Ibrahim ibn Walid ibn 'Abdallah in Madinah by order of Caliph [[Hisham ibn Abd al-Malik]]. <hr>Buried in [[Jannat al-Baqi]], [[Medina|Madinah]]<ref name=\"Chittickb\"/>\n|-\n| [[File:Jaffer-e-Sadiq.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Jafar al-Sadiq|Ja'far ibn Muhammad]]<br />{{lang|ar|\u062c\u064e\u0639\u0652\u0641\u064e\u0631 \u0671\u0628\u0652\u0646 \u0645\u064f\u062d\u064e\u0645\u064e\u0651\u062f \u0671\u0644\u0635\u064e\u0651\u0627\u062f\u0650\u0642 \u0639\u064e\u0644\u064e\u064a\u0652\u0647\u0650 \u0671\u0644\u0633\u064e\u0651\u0644\u064e\u0627\u0645}}<hr>Abu Abdillah<ref name=\"Jafar al-Sadiq in Iranica\">{{cite encyclopedia|last= |first= | authorlink= | title=JA\u02bfFAR AL-\u1e62\u0100DEQ, ABU \u02bfABD-ALL\u0100H | encyclopedia=Encyclopaedia Iranica | accessdate=2014-07-07 |url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/jafar-al-sadeq }}</ref><ref name=\"Chittickb\"/><br />{{lang|ar|\u0623\u064e\u0628\u064f\u0648 \u0639\u064e\u0628\u0652\u062f \u0671\u0644\u0644\u064e\u0651\u0670\u0647}}\n|\n*''a\u1e63-\u1e62\u0101diq''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u0635\u064e\u0651\u0627\u062f\u0650\u0642}})<br />(''The Honest'')<ref>{{Harvnb|Tabatabaei|1975|p=15}}</ref><ref name=\"Jafar al-Sadiq\">Tabatabae (1979), p.203\u2013204</ref>\n| {{bulleted list|702 \u2013 765<ref name=\"Chittickb\"/>|83 \u2013 148<ref name=\"Chittickb\"/>}} <hr>[[Medina|Madinah]], [[Hejaz|Hijaz]]<ref name=\"t180\"/>\n| As-Sadiq established the [[Ja'fari jurisprudence|Ja'fari school of jurisprudence]] and developed the [[Twelver#Theology|theology of the Twelvers]].<ref name=\"Chittickb\"/> He taught many scholars in different fields, including [[Abu Hanifah]]<ref name=\"Chittickb\"/> and [[Malik ibn Anas]] in [[fiqh]], [[Wasil ibn Ata]] and [[Hisham ibn Hakam]] in [[Kalam|Islamic theology]], and [[J\u0101bir ibn Hayy\u0101n|Geber]] in science and alchemy.<ref name=\"t180\">{{harvnb|Tabatabaei|1975|p=180}}</ref>\n| He was fatally poisoned in Madinah by order of Caliph [[Al-Mansur]].<ref name=\"t180\"/><hr> Buried in [[Jannat al-Baqi]], [[Medina|Madinah]]<ref name=\"Chittickb\"/>\n|-\n| [[File:Al-Kazim.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Musa al-Kazim|Musa ibn Ja'far]]<br />{{lang|ar|\u0645\u064f\u0648\u0633\u064e\u0649\u0670 \u0671\u0628\u0652\u0646 \u062c\u064e\u0639\u0652\u0641\u064e\u0631 \u0671\u0644\u0652\u0643\u064e\u0627\u0638\u0650\u0645 \u0639\u064e\u0644\u064e\u064a\u0652\u0647\u0650 \u0671\u0644\u0633\u064e\u0651\u0644\u064e\u0627\u0645}}<hr>Abu al-Hasan I<ref name=\"Ali al-Reza in Iranica1\">{{Harvnb|Madelung|1985b}}</ref><ref name=\"Ali al-Reza in Iranica\">{{cite encyclopedia|last=Madelung |first=Wilferd | authorlink=Wilferd Madelung | title= \u02bfAL\u012a AL-RE\u017b\u0100 | encyclopedia=Encyclopaedia Iranica | accessdate=2007-11-09 |url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/ali-al-reza}}</ref><br />{{lang|ar|\u0623\u064e\u0628\u064f\u0648 \u0671\u0644\u0652\u062d\u064e\u0633\u064e\u0646 \u0671\u0644\u0652\u0623\u064e\u0648\u064e\u0651\u0644}}\n|\n*''al-K\u0101\u1e93im''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u0652\u0643\u064e\u0627\u0638\u0650\u0645}})<br />(''The Confined'')<ref name=\"Musa al-Kazim\">{{Harvnb|Tabatabaei|1975|p=181}}</ref>\n| {{bulleted list|744 \u2013 799<ref name=\"Chittickb\"/>|128 \u2013 183<ref name=\"Chittickb\"/>}} <hr>[[Medina|Madinah]], [[Hejaz|Hijaz]]<ref name=\"Musa al-Kazim\"/>\n| Al-Kazim was leader of the Shia community during the schism between the [[Ismaili]] and other branches of Islam after the death of the previous Imam Jafar al-Sadiq.<ref>{{Harvnb|Tabatabaei|1975|p=68}}</ref> He established a network of agents who collected the [[khums]] in the Shia community of the Middle East and the [[Greater Khorasan]]. He holds a high position in the [[Mahdavia]], the members of which trace their lineage to Muhammad through him.<ref>{{Harvnb|Sachedina|1988|pp=53\u201354}}</ref>\n| He was imprisoned and fatally poisoned in [[Baghdad]], Iraq, by order of Caliph [[Harun al-Rashid]].<ref>{{harvnb|Amir-Moezzi|2011|p=207}}</ref> <hr> Buried in the [[Kazimayn|Kazimayn shrine]], Baghdad, Iraq<ref name=\"Chittickb\"/><ref name=\"Musa al-Kazim\"/>\n|-\n| [[File:Al redah.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Ali al-Rida|Ali ibn Musa]]<br />{{lang|ar|\u0639\u064e\u0644\u0650\u064a\u0651 \u0671\u0628\u0652\u0646 \u0645\u064f\u0648\u0633\u064e\u0649\u0670 \u0671\u0644\u0631\u0650\u0651\u0636\u064e\u0627 \u0639\u064e\u0644\u064e\u064a\u0652\u0647\u0650 \u0671\u0644\u0633\u064e\u0651\u0644\u064e\u0627\u0645}}<hr>Abu al-Hasan II<ref name=\"Ali al-Reza in Iranica\"/><br />{{lang|ar|\u0623\u064e\u0628\u064f\u0648 \u0671\u0644\u0652\u062d\u064e\u0633\u064e\u0646 \u0671\u0644\u062b\u064e\u0651\u0627\u0646\u0650\u064a}}\n|\n*''ar-Ri\u1e0d\u0101''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u0631\u0650\u0651\u0636\u064e\u0627}})<br />(''The Pleasing'')<ref name=\"Musa al-Kazim\"/><ref name=\"Ali al-Reza\">Tabatabae (1979), pp.205\u2013207</ref>\n| {{bulleted list|765 \u2013 817<ref name=\"Chittickb\"/>|148 \u2013 203<ref name=\"Chittickb\"/>}} <hr>[[Medina|Madinah]],<br /> [[Hejaz|Hijaz]]<ref>{{Harvnb|Tabatabaei|1975|pp=182\u2013183}}</ref>\n| Made crown prince by Caliph [[Al-Ma'mun]], Ar-Rida was known for his discussions and debates with both Muslim and non-Muslim religious scholars.<ref name=\"Chittickc\">{{Harvnb|Chittick|1980|p=139}}</ref>\n| He was fatally poisoned in [[Mashad]], Iran, by order of Caliph Al-Ma'mun.<ref name=\"Chittickc\"/> <hr> Buried in the [[Imam Reza shrine]], [[Mashad]], Iran<ref name=\"Chittickc\"/>\n|-\n| [[File:Imam Taqi.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Muhammad al-Taqi|Muhammad ibn Ali]]<br />{{lang|ar|\u0645\u064f\u062d\u064e\u0645\u064e\u0651\u062f \u0671\u0628\u0652\u0646 \u0639\u064e\u0644\u0650\u064a\u0651 \u0671\u0644\u0652\u062c\u064e\u0648\u064e\u0651\u0627\u062f \u0639\u064e\u0644\u064e\u064a\u0652\u0647\u0650 \u0671\u0644\u0633\u064e\u0651\u0644\u064e\u0627\u0645}}<hr>Abu Ja'far<ref name=Rizvib/><br />{{lang|ar|\u0623\u064e\u0628\u064f\u0648 \u062c\u064e\u0639\u0652\u0641\u064e\u0631}}\n|\n*''al-Jaww\u0101d''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u0652\u062c\u064e\u0648\u064e\u0651\u0627\u062f}})<br />(''The Generous'')<ref name=\"Muhammad al-Taqi1\">{{Harvnb|Tabatabaei|1975|p=183}}</ref><ref name=\"Muhammad al-Taqi\">Tabatabae (1979), p. 207</ref>\n*''at-Taq\u012by''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u062a\u064e\u0651\u0642\u0650\u064a\u0651}})<br />(''The God-Fearing'')<ref name=\"Chittickc\"/><ref name=\"Muhammad al-Taqi\" />\n| {{bulleted list|809<ref name=\"Chittickc\"/> or 810 \u2013 835<ref name=\"Chittickc\"/>|195 \u2013 220<ref name=\"Muhammad al-Taqi\"/>}} <hr>[[Medina|Madinah]],<br /> [[Hejaz|Hijaz]]<ref name=\"Muhammad al-Taqi\"/>\n| Al-Jawad was known for his generosity and piety in the face of persecution by the [[Abbasid|Abbasid caliphate]].<ref name=\"Qurashi 2005\">{{harvnb|Qurash\u012b|2005}}</ref>\n| He was fatally poisoned by his wife, the daughter of Caliph Al-Ma'mun, in Baghdad, Iraq, by order of Caliph [[Al-Mu'tasim]].<ref name=\"Muhammad al-Taqi\"/><hr> Buried in the [[Kazmain|Kazmain shrine]], Baghdad, Iraq.<ref name=\"Chittickc\"/>\n|-\n| [[File:Imam naqi.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Ali al-Hadi|Ali ibn Muhammad]]<br />{{lang|ar|\u0639\u064e\u0644\u0650\u064a\u0651 \u0671\u0628\u0652\u0646 \u0645\u064f\u062d\u064e\u0645\u064e\u0651\u062f \u0671\u0644\u0652\u0647\u064e\u0627\u062f\u0650\u064a \u0639\u064e\u0644\u064e\u064a\u0652\u0647\u0650 \u0671\u0644\u0633\u064e\u0651\u0644\u064e\u0627\u0645}}<hr>Abu al-Hasan III<ref name=\"Ali al-Hadi in Iranica\">{{Harvnb|Madelung|1985a}}</ref><br />{{lang|ar|\u0623\u064e\u0628\u064f\u0648 \u0671\u0644\u0652\u062d\u064e\u0633\u064e\u0646 \u0671\u0644\u062b\u064e\u0651\u0627\u0644\u0650\u062b}}\n|\n*''al-H\u0101d\u012b''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u0652\u0647\u064e\u0627\u062f\u0650\u064a}})<br />(''The Guide'')<ref>{{harvnb|Dungersi|2005|p=16}}</ref><ref name=\"Ali al-Hadi in Iranica\">{{cite encyclopedia|last=Madelung |first=Wilferd | authorlink=Wilferd Madelung | title= \u02bfAL\u012a AL-H\u0100D\u012a  | encyclopedia=Encyclopaedia Iranica | accessdate=2007-11-08 |url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/ali-al-hadi-abul-hasan-b}}</ref>\n*''an-Naq\u012by''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u0646\u064e\u0651\u0642\u0650\u064a\u0651}})<br />(''The Pure'')<ref name=\"Chittickc\"/><ref name=\"Ali al-Hadi in Iranica\">{{cite encyclopedia|last=Madelung |first=Wilferd | authorlink=Wilferd Madelung | title= \u02bfAL\u012a AL-H\u0100D\u012a  | encyclopedia=Encyclopaedia Iranica | accessdate=2007-11-08 |url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/ali-al-hadi-abul-hasan-b}}</ref>\n| {{bulleted list|828 \u2013 868 <ref name=\"Ali al-Hadi in Iranica\"/>|212 \u2013 254<ref name=\"Ali al-Hadi in Iranica\"/>}} <hr>Surayya, a village near [[Medina|Madinah]], [[Hejaz|Hijaz]]<ref name=\"Ali al-Hadi in Iranica\"/>\n| Al-Naqi taught religious sciences until 243/857.<ref name=\"Chittickc\"/> He strengthened the network of deputies in the Shia community. He sent them instructions and in turn received financial contributions from the faithful, from the [[khums]] and religious vows.<ref name=\"Ali al-Hadi in Iranica\"/>\n| He was fatally poisoned in [[Samarra]], Iraq, by order of caliph [[Al-Mu'tazz]].<ref name=\"Muhammad al-Taqi\"/> <hr> Buried in the [[Al Askari Mosque]], Samarra, Iraq.<ref name=\"Chittickc\"/>\n|-\n| [[File:Al-askari.svg|100px]]\n| [[Hasan al-Askari|Hasan ibn Ali]]<br />{{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u0652\u062d\u064e\u0633\u064e\u0646 \u0671\u0628\u0652\u0646 \u0639\u064e\u0644\u0650\u064a\u0651 \u0671\u0644\u0652\u0639\u064e\u0633\u0652\u0643\u064e\u0631\u0650\u064a\u0651 \u0639\u064e\u0644\u064e\u064a\u0652\u0647\u0650 \u0671\u0644\u0633\u064e\u0651\u0644\u064e\u0627\u0645}}<hr>Abu al-Mahdi<ref name=Rizvic>{{harvnb|Rizvi|1988|p=50}}</ref><br />{{lang|ar|\u0623\u064e\u0628\u064f\u0648 \u0671\u0644\u0652\u0645\u064e\u0647\u0652\u062f\u0650\u064a\u0651}}\n|\n*''al-\u02bfAskar\u012by''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u0652\u0639\u064e\u0633\u0652\u0643\u064e\u0631\u0650\u064a\u0651}})<br />(''The Garrison Town One'')<ref name=\"al-Askari in Iranica\">{{Harvnb|Halm|1987}}</ref><ref name=\"al-Askari in Iranica\">{{cite encyclopedia|last=Halm |first=H | authorlink= | title=\u02bfASKAR\u012a | encyclopedia=Encyclopaedia Iranica | accessdate=2007-11-08 |url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/askari-abu-mohammad-hasan-b}}</ref>\n| {{bulleted list|845/6 \u2013 874<ref name=\"al-Askari in Iranica\"/>|231 \u2013 260 <ref name=\"al-Askari in Iranica\"/>}} <hr>[[Medina|Madinah]],<br /> [[Hejaz|Hijaz]]<ref name=\"al-Askari in Iranica\"/>\n| Like his father, Al-Askari was placed under house arrest, which would last most of his life, by the Abbasid Caliph [[Al-Mu'tamid]], .<ref>{{Harvnb|Dungersi|2005|p=188}}</ref> During this time, repression of the Shia communities was great because of their growing size and power.<ref name=\"Tabatabae 1979 209 \u2013 210\">{{Harvnb|Tabatabaei|1975|p=184}}</ref>\n| He was fatally poisoned by order of Caliph Al-Mu'tamid in Samarra, Iraq.<ref>{{Harvnb|Dungersi|2005|p=196}}</ref><hr> Buried in the Al Askari Mosque, Samarra, Iraq.<ref name=\"Chittickc\"/>\n|-\n| [[File:Al mehdi.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Hujjat-Allah al-Mahdi|Hujjat Allah ibn al-Hasan]]<br />{{lang|ar|\u062d\u064f\u062c\u064e\u0651\u0629 \u0671\u0644\u0644\u064e\u0651\u0670\u0647 \u0671\u0628\u0652\u0646 \u0671\u0644\u0652\u062d\u064e\u0633\u064e\u0646 \u0671\u0644\u0652\u0645\u064e\u0647\u0652\u062f\u0650\u064a\u0651 \u0639\u064e\u0644\u064e\u064a\u0652\u0647\u0650 \u0671\u0644\u0633\u064e\u0651\u0644\u064e\u0627\u0645}}<hr>Abu al-Qasim<ref name=Amir-Moezzi1994>{{Harvnb|Amir-Moezzi|1994|p=174}}</ref><br />{{lang|ar|\u0623\u064e\u0628\u064f\u0648 \u0671\u0644\u0652\u0642\u064e\u0627\u0633\u0650\u0645}}\n|\n*''[[Mahdi|al-Mahd\u012by]]''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u0652\u0645\u064e\u0647\u0652\u062f\u0650\u064a\u0651}})<br />(''The Guided'')<ref>{{Harvnb|Amir-Moezzi|2007}}</ref><ref name=\"MAHDI in Iranica\">{{cite encyclopedia|last= |first= | authorlink= | title=THE CONCEPT OF MAHDI IN TWELVER SHI\u02bfISM | encyclopedia=Encyclopaedia Iranica | accessdate=2014-07-07 |url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/islam-in-iran-vii-the-concept-of-mahdi-in-twelver-shiism}}</ref>\n*''al-Q\u0101\u02beim''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u0652\u0642\u064e\u0627\u0626\u0650\u0645}})<br />(''The Riser'')<ref name=Amir-Moezzi1994/>\n*''al-Gh\u0101\u02beib''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u0652\u063a\u064e\u0627\u0626\u0650\u0628}})<br />(''[[The Occultation|The Hidden]]'')<ref>{{Harvnb|Amir-Moezzi|1994|p=115}}</ref><ref name=\"\u1e20AYBA in Iranica\">{{cite encyclopedia|last= |first= | authorlink= | title=\u1e20AYBA | encyclopedia=Encyclopaedia Iranica | accessdate=2014-07-07 |url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/gayba}}</ref>\n*''S\u0101hib az-Zam\u0101n''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0635\u064e\u0627\u062d\u0650\u0628 \u0671\u0644\u0632\u064e\u0651\u0645\u064e\u0627\u0646}})<br />(''The Authority of the Era'')<ref name=Rizvic/>\n*''[[Ahl al-Bayt|al-\u1e24ujjah \u02be\u0100l Mu\u1e25ammad]]''<br/>({{lang|ar|\u0671\u0644\u0652\u062d\u064f\u062c\u064e\u0651\u0629 \u0622\u0644 \u0645\u064f\u062d\u064e\u0645\u064e\u0651\u062f}})<br />(''The [[Hujjah|Proof]] of the House of Muhammad'')<ref name=\"al-Hujjah in Britannica\">{{cite encyclopedia| title=Muhammad al-Mahdi al-Hujjah | encyclopedia=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Online | accessdate=2007-11-08 |url=http://www.britannica.com/eb/article-9054165/Muhammad-al-Mahdi-al-Hujjah}}</ref>\n| {{bulleted list|868 \u2013 Present<ref name=\"al-Hujjah\">{{Harvnb|Tabatabaei|1975|p=186}}</ref>|255 or 256<ref name=\"Chittickc\"/> \u2013 Present<ref name=\"al-Hujjah\"/>}} <hr>[[Samarra]], [[Iraq]]<ref>{{harvnb|Tabatabaei|1975|p=185}}</ref>\n| According to Twelver Shia doctrine, he is the current Imam and the promised [[Mahdi]], a messianic figure who will return with the prophet [[Jesus in Islam|Isa]] ([[Jesus]]). He will reestablish the rightful governance of Islam and establish justice and peace in the earth.<ref>{{Harvnb|Tabatabaei|1979|pp=211\u2013214}}</ref>\n| According to Twelver Shia doctrine, he has been living in the [[The Occultation|Occultation]] since 872, and will continue as long as God wills.<ref name=\"al-Hujjah\"/>\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n{{portal|Shia Islam}}\n{{Twelvers|collapsed=2}}\n\n* [[Shia Islam]]\n* [[Twelvers]]\n* [[Ahl al-Bayt]]\n* [[Ahl al-Kisa]]\n* [[Twelve Imams]]\n* [[Imamate in Twelver doctrine|Imamat doctrine]]\n* [[Ismah]]\n* [[Criticism of Twelver Shia Islam#Infallibility of Imams]]\n* [[Salawat]]\n\n==Notes and references==\n\n===Notes===\n{{notes|30em}}\n\n===References===\n{{reflist|colwidth=25em|refs=}}\n\n===Sources===\n\n; Encyclopedias\n* {{cite book|last = Ahmed|first = M. Mukarram|title = Encyclopaedia of Islam|publisher=Anmol Publications Pvt. Ltd.| year = 2005|isbn = 978-81-261-2339-1 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite encyclopedia |last=Algar |first=Hamid | authorlink=Hamid Algar | title=Chahardah M'asum | encyclopedia=Encyclop\u00e6dia Iranica | accessdate=2008-07-18 |url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/cahardah-masum|year = 1990|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite encyclopedia|last=Amir-Moezzi |first=Mohammad Ali | authorlink= | title=Islam in Iran-vii. The Concept of Mahdi in Twelver Shi'ism| encyclopedia=Encyclop\u00e6dia Iranica |year=2007 |url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/islam-in-iran-vii-the-concept-of-mahdi-in-twelver-shiism|ref=harv|accessdate=2015-03-11}}\n* {{cite encyclopedia|last=Halm |first=H | authorlink= | title=\u02bfAskari| encyclopedia=Encyclop\u00e6dia Iranica |year=1987|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/askari-abu-mohammad-hasan-b|ref=harv|accessdate=2015-03-11}}\n* {{cite encyclopedia | encyclopedia =Encyclopaedia of Islam 3|title=F\u0101\u1e6dima bt. Mu\u1e25ammad|last =Klemm| year = 2014 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite encyclopedia | encyclopedia =Encyclopaedia of Islam|title=Fatima|last1 =Lammens| year = 2012 | publisher = Brill Online| isbn = 978-90-04-08265-