6XT|PowerVR Series 6 GX6450]] (quad-core)<ref name=\"Apple's A8 SoC: GX6450\">{{cite web\n  | url=http://www.anandtech.com/show/8562/chipworks-a8\n  | title=Chipworks Disassembles Apple's A8 SoC: GX6450, 4&nbsp;MB L3 Cache & More\n  | publisher=AnandTech\n  | date=September 23, 2014\n }}</ref>\n| memory       = 1 [[Gibibytes|GB]] [[LPDDR3]] [[Random-access memory|RAM]]\n| storage      = 16, 32 (iPhone 6 only), 64, 128&nbsp;GB<br />\n| memory_card  =\n| battery      = '''6:''' {{nowrap|3.82 V}} {{nowrap|6.91 W\u00b7h}} {{nowrap|(1,810 mA\u00b7h)}} [[Lithium polymer battery]]<ref>{{cite web  | url=http://www.gsmarena.com/apple_iphone_6-6378.php  | title=Apple iPhone 6 \u2013 Full phone specifications  | work=GSMArena }}</ref><br />'''6 Plus:''' {{nowrap|3.82 V}} {{nowrap|11.1 W\u00b7h}} {{nowrap|(2,915 mA\u00b7h)}} [[Lithium polymer battery]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ifixit.com/Teardown/iPhone+6+Plus+Teardown/29206|title=iPhone 6 Plus Teardown|work=iFixit}}</ref>\n| input        = [[Multi-touch]] [[touchscreen]] display, triple [[microphone]], Apple M8 motion coprocessor, 3-axis [[gyroscope]], 3-axis [[accelerometer]], [[digital data|digital]] [[magnetometer|compass]], [[iBeacon]], [[proximity sensor]], [[photodetector|ambient light]] sensor, [[Touch ID]] [[fingerprint reader]], [[barometer]]\n| display      = '''6:''' {{convert|4.7|in|mm|abbr=on}} [[Retina Display|Retina HD]]: LED-backlit IPS LCD, 1334\u00d7750 px resolution (326&nbsp;[[Pixels per inch|ppi]]) (128 px/cm) pixel density, 16:9 aspect ratio, 1400:1 typ. contrast ratio<ref name=\"iPhone 6 Technical Specifications\">{{cite web\n  | url=https://www.apple.com/iphone-6/specs/\n  | title=iPhone 6 Technical Specifications\n  | publisher=[[Apple Inc.|Apple]]\n  | accessdate=October 2, 2014\n }}</ref><br />'''6 Plus:''' {{convert|5.5|in|mm|abbr=on}} [[Retina Display|Retina HD]]: LED-backlit IPS LCD 1920\u00d71080 (401&nbsp;ppi) (158 px/cm) pixel density, 16:9 aspect ratio, 1300:1 typ. contrast ratio<ref name=\"iPhone 6 Technical Specifications\" /><br />'''All models:''' 500 cd/m\u00b2 max. brightness (typical), with dual-ion exchange-strengthened glass\n| rear_camera  = '''6:''' 8 [[Megapixel|MP]] (3264\u00d72448 px max.) with 1.5 focus pixels, [[flash (photography)|True Tone flash]], [[autofocus]], [[IR filter]], [[burst mode (photography)|burst mode]], f/2.2 [[F-number|aperture]], [[1080p]] HD video recording (30 [[frame rate|fps]] or 60 fps), [[slow-motion]] video ([[720p]] 120 fps or 240 fps), [[timelapse]], [[panorama]] (up to 43 megapixels), [[facial recognition system|facial recognition]], stills from video, auto-[[high-dynamic-range imaging|HDR]],<br />[[digital image stabilization]]<br />'''6 Plus:''' In addition to above: [[optical image stabilization]]\n| front_camera = 1.2 [[megapixel|MP]] (1280\u00d7960 px max.), [[720p]] video recording (30&nbsp;fps), [[burst mode (photography)|burst mode]], f/2.2 [[F-number|aperture]], [[camera#exposure control|exposure control]], [[face detection]], auto-[[high-dynamic-range imaging|HDR]]\n| sound        = Mono speaker, 3.5&nbsp;mm [[TRS connector|stereo audio jack]]\n| connectivity = {{Collapsible list\n | title=''All models:''\n | 1=[[UMTS]]/[[HSPA+]]/[[DC-HSDPA]] (850, 900, 1700/2100, 1900, 2100&nbsp;MHz), [[Code division multiple access|CDMA]] [[Evolution-Data Optimized|EV-DO]] Rev. A and Rev. B (800, 1700/2100, 1900, 2100&nbsp;MHz), GSM/EDGE (850, 900, 1800, 1900&nbsp;MHz), [[Wi-Fi]] ([[802.11]] [[IEEE 802.11a-1999|a]]/[[IEEE 802.11b-1999|b]]/[[IEEE 802.11g-2003|g]]/[[IEEE 802.11n-2009|n]]/[[IEEE 802.11ac|ac]]) (802.11n: 2.4 and 5&nbsp;[[Hertz|GHz]]), [[Bluetooth 4.2]], [[Near field communication|NFC]], [[GPS]] & [[GLONASS]], [[Lightning (connector)|Lightning connector]]\n }}\n {{Collapsible list\n  | title=''models A1549 & A1522:''\n  | 1=[[LTE (telecommunication)|LTE]] (bands 1 to 5, 7, 8, 13, 17 to 20, 25, 26, 28, 29)<ref name=\"Apple bands 1\">{{cite web\n   | url=https://www.apple.com/iphone/LTE\n   | title=Apple \u2013 iPhone 6 \u2013 View countries with supported LTE networks\n   | publisher=[[Apple Inc.|Apple]]\n   | date=\n   | accessdate=October 14, 2014\n  }}</ref>\n }}\n {{Collapsible list\n  | title=''models A1586 & A1524''\n  | 1=[[LTE (telecommunication)|LTE]] (bands 1 to 5, 7, 8, 13, 17 to 20, 25, 26, 28, 29, 38 to 41), [[TD-SCDMA]] 1900 (F), 2000 (A)<ref name=\"Apple bands 1\" />\n }}\n| other        = [[FaceTime]] audio- or video-calling\n| sar          = {{Collapsible list\n | title=6<ref>[https://www.apple.com/legal/rfexposure/iphone7,2/en/ iPhone 6 RF Exposure information]</ref>\n | 1='''Model A1549'''<br />Head: 1.08 W/kg<br />Body: 1.14 W/kg\n | 2='''Model A1586'''<br />Head: 1.08 W/kg<br />Body: 1.14 W/kg\n | 3='''Model A1589'''<br />Head: 0.38 W/kg\n }}\n {{Collapsible list\n  | title=6 Plus<ref>[https://www.apple.com/legal/rfexposure/iphone7,1/en/ iPhone 6 Plus RF Exposure information]</ref>\n  | 1='''Model A1522'''<br />Head: 1.14 W/kg<br />Body: 1.16 W/kg\n  | 2='''Model A1524'''<br />Head: 1.19 W/kg<br />Body: 1.19 W/kg\n  | 3='''Model A1593'''<br />Head: 0.37 W/kg\n }}\n| hac          = M3, T4<ref>{{cite web |author=Apple |date=September 12, 2018 |accessdate=February 28, 2019 |publisher=Apple Support |title=About Hearing Aid Compatibility (HAC) requirements for iPhone - Apple Support |url=https://support.apple.com/en-us/HT202186}}</ref> \n| website = {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141202030024/http://www.apple.com/iphone-6/|title=Apple - iPhone 6|date=December 2, 2014}}\n| references   = \n}}\n{{iPhone models}}\n\nThe '''iPhone 6''' and '''iPhone 6 Plus''' are [[smartphone]]s designed and marketed by [[Apple Inc.]] It is the [[List of iOS devices|eighth]] generation of the [[iPhone]], succeeding the [[iPhone 5S]], and was announced on September 9, 2014 and released on September 19, 2014.<ref name=\"apple pr 6 6+ announced\">{{cite press release |title=Apple Announces iPhone 6 & iPhone 6 Plus\u2014The Biggest Advancements in iPhone History |url=https://www.apple.com/pr/library/2014/09/09Apple-Announces-iPhone-6-iPhone-6-Plus-The-Biggest-Advancements-in-iPhone-History.html |location=Cupertino, CA |publisher=[[Apple Inc.]] |date=September 9, 2014 |access-date=July 27, 2015}}</ref> The iPhone 6 and iPhone 6 Plus jointly were themselves replaced as the flagship devices of the [[iPhone|iPhone series]] by the [[iPhone 6S|iPhone 6S and iPhone 6S Plus]] on September 9, 2015. The iPhone 6 and 6 Plus include larger {{convert|4.7 and 5.5|in|mm}} displays, a faster processor, upgraded cameras, improved [[LTE (telecommunication)|LTE]] and [[Wi-Fi]] connectivity and support for a [[near field communication]]s-based [[mobile payments]] offering.<ref name=verge-announce>{{cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/9/9/6122731/iphone-6-apple-4-7-inch-display-announced|title=iPhone 6 announced: 4.7-inch display, A8 processor, 8-megapixel camera, available September 19th for $199|work=[[The Verge]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|first=Dan|last=Seifert|date=September 9, 2014|accessdate=August 4, 2015}}</ref><ref name=verge-sixplusannounce>{{cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/9/9/6121705/apple-iphone-6-5-5-inch-display-announced|title=iPhone 6 Plus with 5.5-inch display announced|work=[[The Verge]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|first=Carl|last=Franzen|date=September 9, 2014|accessdate=September 9, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe iPhone 6 and 6 Plus received positive reviews, with critics regarding their redesign, specifications, camera, and battery life as being improvements over previous iPhone models. However, aspects of the design of iPhone 6 were also criticized, including plastic strips on the rear of the device for its antenna that disrupted the otherwise metal exterior, and the screen resolution of the standard-sized iPhone 6 being lower than other devices in its class. Pre-orders of the iPhone 6 and iPhone 6 Plus exceeded four million within its first 24 hours of availability\u2014an Apple record.<ref name=\"apple-prrecord\">{{cite press release |url=https://www.apple.com/pr/library/2014/09/15Apple-Announces-Record-Pre-orders-for-iPhone-6-iPhone-6-Plus-Top-Four-Million-in-First-24-Hours.html|title=Apple Announces Record Pre-orders for iPhone 6 & iPhone 6 Plus Top Four Million in First 24 Hours|location=Cupertino, CA|publisher=[[Apple Inc.]]|date=September 15, 2014|accessdate=September 16, 2014}}</ref> Ten million iPhone 6 and iPhone 6 Plus devices were sold in the first three days, marking another Apple record.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/9/22/6826347/iphone-6-opening-weekend-sales-figures|title=Apple sells 10 million iPhones in opening weekend record|work=[[The Verge]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|first=Tom|last=Warren|date=September 22, 2014|accessdate=August 4, 2015}}</ref> During its lifespan, the iPhone 6 and 6 Plus sold more than 220 million in total, which makes them the best selling iPhone models, so far, and [[list of best-selling mobile phones|one of the most successful phones to date]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe iPhone 6 and 6 Plus have been the subject of several hardware issues, including most prominently, being susceptible to bending under hard pressure (dubbed \"Bendgate\"), and as a byproduct of this lack of rigidity, the touchscreen's internal hardware being susceptible to losing its connection to the phone's [[logic board]] (nicknamed \"Touch Disease\"). Additionally, some iPhone 6 Plus models were the subject of camera issues, including some with malfunctioning [[optical image stabilization]] or otherwise defects on rear cameras.\n\nThe iPhone 6 and 6 Plus were moved to the midrange spot in Apple's iPhone lineup when the iPhone 6S and 6S Plus were released in September 2015.  The iPhone 6 and 6 Plus were discontinued in most markets on September 7, 2016 when Apple announced the [[iPhone 7]] and iPhone 7 Plus. Their spot as the entry-level iPhone was replaced by the [[iPhone SE]], which was released earlier on March 31, 2016. The iPhone 6 was relaunched with 32&nbsp;GB of storage in Asian markets in February 2017 as a midrange/budget iPhone. It was later expanded to Europe,<ref name=\"iPhone 6 2017\">{{cite web|url=\nhttp://www.idownloadblog.com/2017/03/15/apple-could-launch-32gb-iphone-6-2017-in-europe-next-week|title=Apple could launch 32&nbsp;GB iPhone 6 (2017) in Europe next week|first=Christian|last=Zibreg|work=[[iDownloadBlog]]|date=March 15, 2017|accessdate=September 11, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"iPhone 6 2017 in europe\">{{cite web|url=\nhttps://9to5mac.com/2017/05/04/32gb-iphone-6-spain|title=Special 32&nbsp;GB iPhone 6 model available in Spain, Germany, Italy, and more|first=Michael|last=Potuck|work=[[9to5Mac]]|date=May 4, 2017|accessdate=September 11, 2017}}</ref> before hitting the US markets in May 2017,<ref name=\"iPhone 6 2017 in US\">{{cite web|url=\nhttps://9to5mac.com/2017/05/09/iphone-6-32gb-space-gray-200-virgin-mobile|title=Special edition 32&nbsp;GB Space Gray iPhone 6 now available for just $200 w/o contract|first=Ben|last=Lovejoy|work=9to5Mac|date=May 9, 2017|accessdate=September 11, 2017}}</ref> and Canada in July 2017.<ref name=\"iPhone 6 2017 in canada\">{{cite web|url=\nhttps://mobilesyrup.com/2017/06/23/special-edition-32gb-space-grey-iphone-6-coming-canada|title=Special edition 32&nbsp;GB Space Grey iPhone 6 coming to Canada|first=Ian|last=Hardy|work=[[MobileSyrup]]|date=June 23, 2017|accessdate=September 11, 2017}}</ref> The iPhone 6 and 6 Plus supported [[iOS 8]], [[iOS9|9]], [[iOS 10|10]], [[iOS 11|11]] and [[iOS12|12]] before being dropped by [[iOS 13]], and they are the third to support five versions of iOS after the [[iPhone 4S]] and the [[iPhone 5]].\n\n== History ==\nFrom the launch of the [[iPhone (1st generation)|original iPhone]] to the [[iPhone 4S]], iPhones used 3.5-inch displays\u2014which are smaller than screens used by flagship phones from competitors. The [[iPhone 5]] and its immediate successors featured a display that was taller, but the same width as prior models, measuring at 4 inches diagonally. Following Apple's loss in smartphone market share to companies producing phones with larger displays, reports as early as January 2014 suggested that Apple was preparing to launch new iPhone models with larger, 4.7-inch and 5.5-inch displays.<ref name=\"wsj-bigphones\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702304856504579338611620927036|title=Apple iPhones to Come Out With Bigger Screens|work=[[Wall Street Journal]]|date=January 24, 2014|accessdate=September 9, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"wsj-bigbet\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/apple-suppliers-gear-up-for-large-screen-iphones-1405985788|title=Apple Readies a Big Bet on Big-Screen Phones|work=[[Wall Street Journal]]|date=September 9, 2014|accessdate=September 9, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"ars-taller\">{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/apple/2012/09/iphone-5-a-little-bit-taller-a-little-bit-baller|title=iPhone 5: a little bit taller, a little bit baller|work=[[Ars Technica]]|date=September 9, 2014|accessdate=September 9, 2014}}</ref> Reports prior to its unveiling also speculated that Apple might use a new iPhone model to introduce a [[mobile payments]] platform using [[near-field communication]]s\u2014a technology that has been incorporated into many [[Android (operating system)|Android]] phones, but has experienced a low adoption rate among users.<ref name=cnet-mobilepayments>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnet.com/news/iphone-6-iwatch-to-use-nfc-tokens-for-mobile-payments-report|title=More signs point to mobile payments for iPhone 6 \u2013 and for an iWatch|work=[[CNET]]|date=September 9, 2014|accessdate=September 9, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe iPhone 6 and iPhone 6 Plus were officially unveiled during a press event at the Flint Center for Performing Arts in [[Cupertino, California]] on September 9, 2014 and released on September 19, 2014; pre-orders began on September 12, 2014, with the iPhone 6 starting at US$649 and the iPhone 6 Plus starting at US$749.<ref name=verge-releasedate>{{cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/9/9/6121325/apple-iphone-6-release-date-pricing|title=iPhone 6 release date September 19th, prices start at $199 for 4.7-inch on contract, $299 for 5.5-inch on contract|work=[[The Verge]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|first=Chris|last=Welch|date=September 9, 2014|accessdate=September 12, 2014}}</ref> In China, where the iPhone 5C and 5S were the first models in the iPhone series to be released in the country on the same day as their international launch, Apple notified local wireless carriers that it would be unable to release the iPhone 6 and iPhone 6 Plus on the 19th  there were \"details which are not ready\"; local media reported that the devices had not yet been approved by the [[Ministry of Industry and Information Technology of the People's Republic of China|Ministry of Industry and Information Technology]], and earlier in the year, a news report by state broadcaster [[China Central Television]] alleged that iPhone devices were a threat to national security because iOS 7's \"frequent locations\" function could expose \"state secrets.\"<ref name=nyt-ip6china>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/11/business/international/release-of-iphone-6-delayed-in-china.html?_r=0|title=Release of iPhone 6 Delayed in China|publisher=New York Times|date=September 10, 2014|accessdate=September 12, 2014}}</ref><ref name=guardian-statesecrets>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/jul/14/apple-denies-iphone-national-security-threat-location-tracking-china|title=Apple denies iPhones are \u2018a national security threat\u2019 to China|publisher=The Guardian|date=July 14, 2014|accessdate=September 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2015, Apple initiated a replacement program for some early iPhone 6 Pluses that were found to have potentially faulty cameras that could be causing photos to appear blurry.<ref name=verge-blurry /><ref name=apple-isight-repl-program /><ref name=cnet-isight-repl-program />\n\nOn September 9, 2015, with the release of the [[iPhone 6S]] and iPhone 6S Plus, the iPhone 6 and 6 Plus were moved to the mid-range of the iPhone lineup. The 128&nbsp;GB versions of the iPhone 6 and iPhone 6 Plus was discontinued along with the gold version of both phones, but the 16&nbsp;GB and 64&nbsp;GB versions of the iPhone 6 and iPhone 6 Plus in silver and space gray remain available for sale at a reduced price.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://appleinsider.com/articles/15/09/09/apple-axes-gold-color-128gb-options-for-iphone-6-and-6-plus-models | title=Apple axes gold color, 128&nbsp;GB options for iPhone 6 and 6 Plus models | work=Apple Insider | date=September 9, 2015 | accessdate=January 10, 2016 | author=Campbell, Mikey}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2016, Apple faced a potential sales ban in China, as Shenzhen Baili, a Chinese device maker, alleged that the iPhone 6 and iPhone 6 Plus infringed on its design patent.<ref>Abhishek, [http://www.techkabaap.com/patent-fight-stop-apple-iphone-6-sales-china/ \"Patent Fight Could Stop Apple iPhone 6 Sales in China] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170807120357/http://www.techkabaap.com/patent-fight-stop-apple-iphone-6-sales-china/ |date=August 7, 2017 }}, Techkabaap, August 3, 2017. Retrieved August 3, 2017.</ref>\n\nThe iPhone 6 and 6 Plus were discontinued on September 7, 2016, when Apple announced the iPhone 7 and iPhone 7 Plus, and the iPhone 6 and 6 Plus' spot as the entry-level iPhone has since been taken by the [[iPhone SE]].  As the iPhone SE has more powerful internal hardware than the midrange iPhone 6 (largely the same as the 6S) and had been released earlier on March 31, 2016, this created an unusual situation when it was sold alongside the iPhone 6 and 6 Plus until September 7 despite being marketed as a lower-tier iPhone.\n\nIn February 2017, the iPhone 6 was quietly relaunched in carrier stores and online, this time the storage has been changed to 32&nbsp;GB. In India, it was sold on [[Amazon.com|Amazon's]] website in Space Grey. In Taiwan, it was sold through [[Taiwan Mobile]] on March 10 in gold color. In mid-March, it was released in the [[European Union|EU]] to Belarus via the i-Store webshop. It also makes an appearance in [[North America]] with [[Sprint Corporation|Sprint]] based US prepaid carriers [[Boost Mobile]] and [[Virgin Mobile]], along with [[AT&T GoPhone]]. These are not being distributed by Apple on their website or their retail stores.\n\n== Specifications ==\n\n=== Hardware ===\nThe design of the iPhone 6 and iPhone 6 Plus is influenced by that of the [[iPad Air]] with a glass front that is curved around the edges of the display, and an aluminum rear that contains two plastic strips for the antenna.<ref name=verge-6review />  The back is built of 6000-series aluminum.<ref>https://www.wired.com/2015/09/iphone-6s-6s-plus-biggest-changes-invisible/</ref>  Both models come in gold, silver, and \"space gray\" finishes. The iPhone 6 has a thickness of {{convert|6.9|mm}}, while the iPhone 6 Plus is {{convert|7.1|mm|abbr=on}} in thickness; both are thinner than the iPhone 5c and iPhone 5s, with the iPhone 6 being Apple's thinnest phone to date. The most significant changes to the iPhone 6 and iPhone 6 Plus are its displays; both branded as \"[[Retina Display|Retina HD Display]]\" and \"ion-strengthened\", the iPhone 6 display is 4.7 inches in size with a [[16:9]] resolution of 1334x750 (326&nbsp;[[Pixels per inch|ppi]], minus one row of pixels), while the iPhone 6 Plus includes a 5.5-inch 1920x1080 ([[1080p]]) display (401&nbsp;PPI). The displays use a multiple-domain LCD panel, dubbed \"dual-domain pixels\"; the RGB pixels themselves are skewed in a pattern, so that every pixel is seen from a different angle. This technique helps improve the viewing angles of the display.<ref name=anandtech-dualdomain>{{cite web|title=Understanding Dual-Domain Pixels in the iPhone 6 and 6 Plus|url=http://www.anandtech.com/show/8509/understanding-dual-domain-pixels-in-the-iphone-6-and-iphone-6-plus|website=Anandtech|publisher=Purch Inc.|accessdate=March 1, 2015}}</ref>\n\nTo accommodate the larger physical size of the iPhone 6 and iPhone 6 Plus, the power button was moved to the side of the phone instead of the top to improve its accessibility.<ref name=verge-announce /><ref name=verge-sixplusannounce /> The iPhone 6 features a 6.91&nbsp;Wh (1810&nbsp;mAh) battery, while the iPhone 6 Plus features an 11.1&nbsp;Wh (2915&nbsp;mAh) battery. Unlike the previous models, the rear-facing camera is not flush with the rear of the device, but instead protrudes slightly.<ref name=verge-bulge>{{cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/9/16/6209759/apple-has-an-embarassing-bulge|title=Apple is hiding an embarrassing iPhone 6 camera bulge|work=[[The Verge]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|first=Tom|last=Warren|date=September 16, 2014|accessdate=September 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\nBoth models include an [[Apple A8]] [[system-on-chip]], and an [[Apple M8|M8]] motion co-processor\u2014an update of the [[Apple M7|M7]] chip from the iPhone 5s. The primary difference between the M8 and the original M7 coprocessor is that the M8 also includes a barometer to measure altitude changes. [[Phil Schiller]] touted that the A8 chip would provide, in comparison to the 5s, a 25% increase in CPU performance, a 50% increase in graphics performance, and less heat output. Early hands-on reports suggested that the A8's GPU performance might indeed break away from previous generations doubling of performance at each yearly release, scoring 21204.26 in Base mark X compared to 20253.80, 10973.36 and 5034.75 on respectively the 5s, 5 and 4s.<ref name=gsmarena-benchmark>{{cite web|url=http://www.gsmarena.com/iphone_6_a8_gpu_benchmark_suggests_its_behind_the_curve-news-9630.php|title=iPhone 6 A8 GPU benchmark suggests it's behind the curve|work=GSMArena|date=September 12, 2014|accessdate=September 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe expanded [[LTE (telecommunication)|LTE]] connectivity on the iPhone 6 and iPhone 6 Plus is improved to [[LTE Advanced]], with support for over 20 LTE bands (seven more than the [[iPhone 5s]]),<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.apple.com/iphone-6/specs/|title=Apple \u2013 iPhone 6 \u2013 Connectivity|publisher=[[Apple Inc.|Apple]]|date=September 9, 2014|accessdate=September 10, 2014}}</ref> for up to 150&nbsp;Mbit/s download speed, and [[VoLTE]] support. [[Wi-Fi]] performance has been improved with support for [[802.11ac]] specifications, providing speeds up to 433.0581&nbsp;Mbit/s\u2014which is up to three times faster than [[802.11n]],<ref name=\":0\" /> along with [[Wi-Fi Calling]] support where available. The iPhone 6 and iPhone 6 Plus add support for [[near-field communications]] (NFC). It is initially used exclusively for [[Apple Pay]]\u2014a new [[mobile payment]]s system which allows users to store their credit cards in [[Passbook (application)|Passbook]] for use with online payments and retail purchases over NFC.<ref name=cnet-applepay>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnet.com/news/apple-adds-nfc-to-iphone-6-with-apple-pay|title=Apple takes NFC mainstream on iPhone 6; Apple Watch with Apple Pay|work=[[CNET]]|first1=Marguerite|last1=Reardon|first2=Shara|last2=Tibken|date=September 9, 2014|accessdate=September 10, 2014}}</ref><ref name=cultofmac-applepaynfc>{{cite web|url=http://www.cultofmac.com/296093/apple-confirms-iphone-6-nfc-apple-pay|title=Apple confirms iPhone 6 NFC chip is only for Apple Pay at launch|first=Buster|last=Hein|date=September 15, 2014|accessdate=September 15, 2014}}</ref> [[iOS 11]] added limited use of near-field communications besides Apple Pay for 3rd party apps.<ref name=\"engadget-nfcios11\">{{cite web|url=https://9to5mac.com/2018/05/25/apple-will-reportedly-open-up-nfc-in-ios-12/|title=iOS 12 will reportedly include new NFC features, enable iPhones to become secure hotel room keys|last=|first=|date=|website=9to5mac|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|accessdate=April 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n\n[[File:88 105 Iphone 6 (154330417).jpeg|thumb|Camera of iPhone 6]]\n\nThe iPhone 6's rear-facing camera now has the ability to shoot 1080p video at either 30 or 60 frames per second and slow-motion video at either 120 or 240 frames per second. The camera also includes [[phase detection autofocus]].<ref name=engadget-review /> The iPhone 6 Plus camera is nearly identical, but also includes [[optical image stabilization]].<ref name=verge-announce /><ref name=verge-sixplusannounce /> The front-facing camera was also updated with a new sensor and f/2.2 aperture, along with support for burst and HDR modes.<ref name=verge-announce /><ref name=verge-sixplusannounce />\n\n=== Software ===\n{{See also|iOS version history|iOS 8|iOS 9|iOS 10|iOS 11|iOS 12}}\nWhen first released, the iPhone 6 and iPhone 6 Plus were supplied pre-loaded with [[iOS 8]], while the [[iPhone 5S]] was supplied pre-loaded with [[iOS 7]]. Apps are able to take advantage of the increased screen size in the iPhone 6 and 6 Plus to display more information on-screen; for example, the Mail app uses a dual-pane layout similar to its [[iPad]] version when the device is in [[landscape mode]] on the iPhone 6 Plus. As it uses an identical aspect ratio, apps designed for the [[iPhone 5]], iPhone 5C, and 5S can be upscaled for use on the iPhone 6 and 6 Plus. To improve the usability of the devices' larger screens, an additional \"Reachability\" gesture was added; double-tapping the Home button will slide the top half of the screen's contents down to the bottom half of the screen. This function allows users to reach buttons located near the top of the screen, such as a \"Back\" button in the top-left corner.<ref name=verge-announce /><ref name=verge-sixplusannounce /> In June 2019, Apple announced that it will drop support for the iPhone 6 and 6 Plus with the release of [[iOS 13]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ios13guide.com/ios-13-compatibility/|title=iOS 13 Compatibility: Full List of All iOS 13 Supported Devices|date=2019-03-07|website=iOS 13 Guide|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.igeeksblog.com/ios-13-compatible-devices/|title=iOS 13 Compatible Devices: What iPhone and iPad Likely to Support iOS 13?|date=2019-05-14|website=www.igeeksblog.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/ios-13-likely-to-drop-support-for-a-lot-of-older-hardware/|title=iOS 13 likely to drop support for a lot of older hardware|last=Kingsley-Hughes|first=Adrian|website=ZDNet|language=en|access-date=2019-05-19}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\nBoth iPhone 6 models received positive reviews. ''[[Re/code]]'' called it \"the best smartphone you can buy\".<ref name=recode-review>{{cite news|title=iPhone 6 Review: It\u2019s a Winner|url=http://recode.net/2014/09/16/iphone-6-review/|accessdate=October 19, 2014|work=Recode|publisher=CNBC}}</ref> ''[[TechRadar]]'' praised the iPhone 6's \"brilliant\" design, improved battery life over the 5s, iOS 8 for being \"smarter and more intuitive than ever\", along with the quality of its camera. However, the plastic antenna strips on the rear of the phone were criticized for resulting in poor aesthetics, the display for having lower resolution and pixel density in comparison to other recent smartphones \u2013 including those with the same physical screen size as the iPhone 6, such as the [[HTC One (2013)|HTC One]], and for not having a sufficient justification for its significantly higher price in comparison to similar devices running [[Android (operating system)|Android]] or [[Windows Phone]].<ref name=techradar-6review>{{cite news|title=iPhone 6 review|url=http://www.techradar.com/reviews/phones/mobile-phones/iphone-6-1264565/review|accessdate=September 23, 2014|work=TechRadar|publisher=Future plc}}</ref> ''[[The Verge]]'' considered the iPhone 6 to be \"simply and cleanly designed\" in comparison to the 5s, noting that the phone still felt usable despite its larger size, but criticized the antenna plastic, the protruding camera lens (which prevents the device from sitting flat without a case), and the lack of additional optimization in the operating system for the bigger screen. Improvements such as performance, battery life, [[VoLTE]] support, and other tweaks were also noted. In conclusion, the iPhone 6 was considered \"good, even great, but there\u2019s little about it that\u2019s truly ambitious or truly moving the needle. It\u2019s just a refinement of a lot of existing ideas into a much more pleasant package\".<ref name=verge-6review>{{cite news|title=iPhone 6 review|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/9/16/6154975/iphone-6-review|work=[[The Verge]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|first=David|last=Pierce|date=September 16, 2014|accessdate=September 23, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn regards to the 6 Plus, ''[[Engadget]]'' panned its design for being uncomfortable to hold and harder to grip in comparison to other devices such as the [[Galaxy Note 3]] and [[LG G3]], but praised its inclusion of optical image stabilization and slightly better battery life than the 6.<ref name=engadget-review>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2014/09/16/iphone-6-and-6-plus-review|title=iPhone 6 and 6 Plus review: bigger and better, but with stiffer competition|publisher=[[Engadget]]|date=September 16, 2014|accessdate=September 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Hardware issues ==\nThe iPhone 6 and 6 Plus were affected by a number of notable hardware-related issues, including but not limited to concerns surrounding their rigidity (which led to incidents surrounding chassis bending, as well as degradation or outright loss of touchscreen functionality), performance issues on models with larger storage capacity, camera problems on the 6 Plus model, as well as an initially undocumented \"error 53\" that appeared under certain circumstances.\n\n=== Bendgate (Chassis bending) ===\nShortly after its public release, it was reported that the iPhone 6 and iPhone 6 Plus chassis was susceptible to bending under pressure, such as when carried tightly in a user's pocket. While such issues are not exclusive to the iPhone 6 and 6 Plus, the design flaw came to be known among users and the media as \"'''{{visible anchor|Bendgate}}'''\".<ref name=\"bi bendgate\">{{cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/apple-replacing-bent-iphone-6-2014-9|title=Apple Will Start Replacing Bent iPhones|work=[[Business Insider]]|date=September 25, 2014|accessdate=September 25, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"bi bendgate 2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.computerbild.de/artikel/cb-News-Handy-Apple-boycotts-COMPUTER-BILD-An-open-letter-to-Tim-Cook-10953399.html|title=Apple boycotts COMPUTER BILD: An open letter to Tim Cook|work=[[Computer Bild]]|date=September 29, 2014|accessdate=September 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\nApple responded to the bending allegations, stating that they had only received nine complaints of bent devices and that the damage occurring due to regular use is \"extremely rare.\" The company maintained that the iPhone 6 and 6 Plus went through durability testing to ensure they would stand up to daily use.<ref name=\"engadget bendgate 1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.engadget.com/2014/09/25/apple-responds-to-bending-iphones|title=hybgbtbtbbApple responds to bent iPhone 6 complaints, all nine of them|work=[[Engadget]]|date=September 25, 2014|accessdate=September 25, 2014}}</ref> The company offered to replace phones that were bent, if it is determined that the bending was unintentional.<ref name=\"bi bendgate\" />\n\nOn October 1, 2014, Axel Telzerow, editor-in-chief of the [[Germany|German]] magazine ''[[Computer Bild]]'', reported that following the posting of a video where a presenter ([[Unbox Therapy]]) was able to bend an iPhone 6 Plus, an Apple Germany representative informed the publication that it had been banned from future Apple events and that it would no longer receive devices directly from Apple for testing. Telzerow responded by saying that \"we congratulate you to your fine new generation of iPhones, even if one of them has a minor weakness with its casing. But we are deeply disappointed about the lack of respect of your company.\"<ref name=\"rt bendgateban\">{{cite web|url=http://rt.com/usa/192296-apple-bendgate-bild-axel|title=Apple accused of banning media covering \u2018Bendgate\u2019 from official events|website=[[Russia Today|RT.com]]|date=October 1, 2014|accessdate=October 3, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Hair ripping ===\nOn October 3, 2014 [[9to5Mac]] released a post claiming that certain iPhone 6\nand iPhone 6 Plus users complained on social networking sites that the phone ripped off their hair when they held the phone close to their ears when making phone calls.<ref name=\"9to5mac hair yank 1\">{{cite web|url=http://9to5mac.com/community/my-iphone-6-plus-is-yanking-out-my-hair|title=My iPhone 6 Plus is yanking out my hair|publisher=[[9to5Mac]]|author=Ayeai|date=October 3, 2014|accessdate=October 4, 2014}}</ref> [[Twitter]] users claimed that the seam between the glass screen and aluminum back of the iPhone 6 is to blame, with hair becoming caught within it.<ref name=\"TOI hair yank 1\">{{cite web|url=http://m.timesofindia.com/tech/tech-news/Buyers-complain-iPhone-6-ripping-out-their-hair/articleshow/44303581.cms|title=Buyers complain iPhone 6 ripping out their hair|publisher=[[Times of India]]|date=October 4, 2014|accessdate=October 4, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"BI hair yank 1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/hairgate-iphone-6-customers-complaining-the-phone-is-ripping-out-their-hair-2014-10|title=HairGate: iPhone 6 Customers Are Complaining That The Phone Is Ripping Out Their Hair|publisher=Business Insider|first=James|last=Cook|date=October 3, 2014|accessdate=October 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Flash storage performance ===\nSome users reported that 64 and 128&nbsp;GB iPhone 6 models had experienced performance issues, and that some 128&nbsp;GB iPhone 6 Plus models would, in rare cases, randomly crash and reboot. ''Business Korea'' reported that the issues were connected to the [[Multi-level cell|triple-layer cell]] [[NAND Flash|NAND]] storage of the affected models. Triple-layer cells can store three bits of data per cell of flash, and are cheaper than dual-layer cell solutions, but at the cost of performance. It was reported that Apple had planned to switch the affected model lines back to multi-layer cell flash, and address the performance issues on existing devices in a future iOS update.<ref name=\"BGR iP6P reboots 1\">{{cite web|url=http://bgr.com/2014/11/04/128gb-iphone-6-plus-crash-and-reboot|title=128GB iPhone 6 Plus crash and reboot bug blamed on memory quality|work=BGR|date=November 4, 2014|accessdate=November 15, 2014}}</ref><ref name=gsmarena-tlcnand>{{cite web|title=Apple to switch faulty flash storage type for iPhone 6, iPhone 6 Plus|url=http://blog.gsmarena.com/apple-switch-faulty-flash-storage-type-iphone-6-iphone-6-plus/|website=GSMArena|accessdate=March 1, 2015}}</ref><ref name=bk-nand>{{cite web|title=Apple to Change Controller IC of NAND Flash Used in iPhone 6, iPhone 6+|url=http://www.businesskorea.co.kr/article/7172/resolution-apple-change-controller-ic-nand-flash-used-iphone-6-iphone-6|website=Business Korea|accessdate=March 1, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150724161612/http://www.businesskorea.co.kr/article/7172/resolution-apple-change-controller-ic-nand-flash-used-iphone-6-iphone-6|archive-date=July 24, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== iPhone 6/6 Plus camera issues ===\nIt was reported that the optical image stabilization systems on some iPhone 6 Plus models were faulty, failing to properly stabilize when the phone is being held perfectly still, leading to blurry photos and \"wavy\"-looking videos.<ref name=phonearena-ois>{{cite web|title=Some iPhone 6 Plus units are suffering from a weird camera issue|url=http://www.phonearena.com/news/Some-iPhone-6-Plus-units-are-suffering-from-a-weird-camera-issue_id63024|website=PhoneArena|accessdate=March 1, 2015}}</ref> The optical image stabilization system was also found to have been affected by accessories that use magnets, such as third-party lens attachments; Apple issued advisories to users and its licensed accessory makers, warning that magnetic or metallic accessories can cause the OIS to malfunction.<ref name=925-magnets>{{cite web|title=Accessories with magnets/metal might interfere w/ iPhone 6 Plus optical image stabilization, NFC on new iPhones|url=http://9to5mac.com/2014/12/14/accessories-with-magnetsmetal-might-interfere-w-iphone-6-plus-optical-image-stabilization-nfc-on-new-iphones/|website=9to5Mac|accessdate=March 1, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn August 21, 2015, Apple instituted a repair program for iPhone 6 Plus models released between September 2014 and January 2015, citing that faulty rear cameras on affected models may produce blurry pictures.<ref name=verge-blurry>{{cite news|title=Apple is offering free camera replacements on some iPhone 6 Plus units due to blurry photos|url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/8/21/9189893/apple-iphone-6-plus-camera-defect|work=[[The Verge]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|first=Ariha|last=Setalvad|date=August 21, 2015|accessdate=August 22, 2015}}</ref><ref name=apple-isight-repl-program>{{cite web|url=https://www.apple.com/support/iphone6plus-isightcamera/|title=iSight Camera Replacement Program for iPhone 6 Plus|publisher=[[Apple Inc]]|date=August 21, 2015|accessdate=August 24, 2015}}</ref><ref name=cnet-isight-repl-program>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnet.com/news/some-iphone-6-plus-phones-have-faulty-cameras-says-apple-as-it-offers-free-repair/|title=Some iPhone 6 Plus devices have faulty cameras, says Apple, as it offers free repair|work=[[CNET]]|first=Edward|last=Moyer|date=August 22, 2015|accessdate=August 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\nSome iPhone 6 and iPhone 6 Plus models have an issue in which the front-facing camera is somehow \"shifted\", or out of place. Apple stated that they would replace most affected iPhone 6 models with this issue, free of charge. Despite numerous complaints regarding this issue, it does not seem to affect the camera itself. It is said that the camera is not what has shifted, but a piece of protective foam around the camera module itself that has gone out of place.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.businessinsider.com/crescentgate-problem-with-the-iphone-6-selfie-camera-2014-12 | title=There's A New, Widespread Problem With The iPhone 6 Selfie Camera | publisher=Business Insider | date=December 1, 2014 | accessdate=January 10, 2016 | author=Cook, James}}</ref>\n\n=== \"Error 53\" ===\nIf the iPhone 6 home button is repaired or modified by a third party, the device will fail security checks related to Touch ID as the components have not been \"re-validated\" for security reasons\u2014a process that can only be performed by an authorized Apple outlet. Failing these checks disables all features related to Touch ID. Such effects have sometimes happened as a result of damage as well.<ref name=\"guardian-error53\" /><ref name=\"dailydot-error53\" />\n\nIt was reported these same hardware integrity checks would trigger an [[Brick (electronics)|unrecoverable]] loop into \"Recovery Mode\" if iOS is updated or restored, with attempts to restore the device via [[iTunes]] software resulting in an \"error 53\" message. Beyond the explanation that this is related to hardware integrity errors regarding Touch ID components, Apple provided no official explanation of what specifically triggers error 53 or how it can be fixed without replacing the entire device.<ref name=\"guardian-error53\">{{cite news|title=\u2018Error 53\u2019 fury mounts as Apple software update threatens to kill your iPhone 6|url=https://www.theguardian.com/money/2016/feb/05/error-53-apple-iphone-software-update-handset-worthless-third-party-repair|accessdate=February 5, 2016|work=The Guardian}}</ref><ref name=\"dailydot-error53\">{{cite web|title=Error 53 will kill your iPhone and no one knows what it is|url=http://www.dailydot.com/technology/what-is-error-53-iphone/|website=[[The Daily Dot]]|accessdate=February 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn February 18, 2016, Apple released an iOS 9.2.1 patch through iTunes which addresses this issue and admitted that error 53 was actually related to a diagnostic check for inspecting the Touch ID hardware before an iPhone is shipped from its factories.<ref name=\"tc-error53fix\">{{cite web|title=Apple Apologizes And Updates iOS To Restore iPhones Disabled By Error 53|url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/02/18/apple-apologizes-and-updates-ios-to-restore-iphones-disabled-by-error-53/|website=TechCrunch|accessdate=February 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Touchscreen failure (\"Touch disease\") ===\n[[File:IPhone 6 display removed 2.jpg|thumb|A removed display of iPhone 6 ]]\n\nTouchscreen control components on iPhone 6 [[logic board]]s have insufficient support, including a lack of underfill\u2014which strengthens and stabilizes [[integrated circuit]]s, and a lack of rigid metal [[Electromagnetic shielding|shielding]] on the logic board unlike previous iPhone models; the touchscreen controller is instead shielded by a flexible \"sticker\". Normal use of the device can cause the logic board to flex internally, which strains the touchscreen IC connectors and leads to a degradation or outright loss of touchscreen functionality. A symptom that has been associated with this type of failure is a flickering grey bar near the top of the display.<ref name=\"ext-touchdisease\">{{cite web|title=The iPhone 6\u2019s \u2018touch disease\u2019 is spreading, now the largest problem reported to Apple Stores|url=http://www.extremetech.com/mobile/234661-the-iphone-6s-touch-disease-is-spreading-now-the-largest-problem-reported-to-apple-stores|website=ExtremeTech|publisher=Ziff Davis Media|accessdate=August 31, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"techradar-underfill\">{{cite web|title=iPhone 6 touch problems? The gray flickering is an epidemic|url=http://www.techradar.com/news/phone-and-communications/mobile-phones/iphone-6-touch-problems-the-gray-flickering-is-an-epidemic-disease-1327020|website=Techradar|publisher=Future|accessdate=August 31, 2016}}</ref> [[iFixit]] reported that this issue, nicknamed \"touch disease\",<ref name=\"ext-touchdisease\" /><ref name=\"fortune-touchdisease\">{{cite web|title=Apple Is Being Sued Over the iPhone 'Touch Disease'|url=http://fortune.com/2016/08/30/apple-touch-disease-lawsuit/|website=Fortune|publisher=Time Inc.|accessdate=August 31, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"extremetech-failingearly\" /> was a byproduct of the previous \"Bendgate\" design flaw because of the device's demonstrated lack of rigidity. As such, the larger iPhone 6 Plus is more susceptible to the flaw, but it has also been reported on a small percentage of iPhone 6 models.<ref name=\"extremetech-failingearly\">{{cite web|title=Apple\u2019s iPhone 6, 6 Plus are failing early thanks to \u2018touch disease,\u2019 bending problems|url=http://www.extremetech.com/mobile/234552-apples-iphone-6-6-plus-are-failing-early-thanks-to-touch-disease-bending-problems|website=ExtremeTech|accessdate=August 31, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"ifixit-touchdisease\">{{cite web|title=A Touch Defect Is Breaking a Ton of iPhone 6 Pluses|url=http://ifixit.org/blog/8309/iphone-6-plus-gray-flicker-touch-death/|website=iFixit Blog|publisher=iFixit|accessdate=August 31, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"bbcnews-touchdisease\" /> The devices' successor, the [[iPhone 6S]], is not afflicted by this flaw due to changes to their internal design, which included the strengthening of \"key points\" in the rear casing, and the re-location of the touchscreen controllers to the display assembly from the logic board.<ref name=\"ifixit-touchdisease\" />\n\nInitially, Apple did not officially acknowledge this issue. The issue was widely discussed on Apple's support forum\u2014where posts discussing the issue have been subject to [[Censorship by Apple|censorship]].<ref name=\"techradar-underfill\" /> The touchscreen can be repaired via [[microsoldering]]: [[Apple Store]]s are not equipped with the tools needed to perform the logic board repair, which had led to affected users sending their devices to unofficial, third-party repair services. An Apple Store employee interviewed by ''Apple Insider'' reported that six months after they first started noticing the problem, Apple had issued guidance instructing them to tell affected users that this was a hardware issue that could not be repaired and that their iPhone had to be replaced. However, some in-stock units have also been afflicted with this issue out of the box, leading to an employee stating that they were \"tired of pulling service stock out of the box, and seeing the exact same problem that the customer has on the replacement\".<ref name=\"bbcnews-touchdisease\" /><ref name=\"ai-touchdisease\">{{cite web|title=Sources: iPhone 6 series 'touch disease' now accounting for about 11% of Apple Store repairs|url=http://appleinsider.com/articles/16/08/26/sources-iphone-6-series-touch-disease-now-accounting-for-about-11-of-apple-store-repairs|website=Apple Insider|accessdate=August 31, 2016}}</ref> The issue received mainstream attention in August 2016 when reported by iFixit.<ref name=\"ext-touchdisease\" /><ref name=\"extremetech-failingearly\" /><ref name=\"bbcnews-touchdisease\">{{cite web|title=Apple accused of iPhone 6 'touch disease' defect|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-37174316|website=BBC News|accessdate=August 31, 2016}}</ref> On August 26, 2016, ''Apple Insider'' reported that based on data from four \"high-traffic\" Apple Store locations, there was a spike in the number of iPhone 6 devices brought into them for repairs following mainstream reports of the \"touch disease\" problem.<ref name=\"ai-touchdisease\" />\n\nOn August 30, 2016, a group of three iPhone 6 owners sued Apple Inc. in the [[United States District Court for the Northern District of California]] and filed for a proposed [[class action lawsuit]], alleging that Apple was engaging in unfair business practices by having \"long been aware\" of the defective design, yet refusing to acknowledge or repair it.<ref name=\"fortune-touchdisease\" /><ref name=\"tc-tdlawsuit\">{{cite web|title=Sufferers of iPhone 6\u2019s \u2018Touch Disease\u2019 may soon have a class action lawsuit|url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/08/29/sufferers-of-iphone-6s-touch-disease-may-soon-have-a-class-action-lawsuit/|website=TechCrunch|publisher=AOL|accessdate=August 31, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"mercurynews-classaction\">{{cite web|title=iPhone 'touch disease': Apple faces class-action lawsuit|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/bay-area-news/ci_30309040/apple-faces-class-action-lawsuit-over-iphone-touch|website=The Mercury News|accessdate=August 31, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn November 17, 2016, Apple officially acknowledged the issue and announced a paid repair program for affected iPhone 6 Plus models, stating that \"some iPhone 6 Plus devices may exhibit display flickering or Multi-Touch issues after being dropped multiple times on a hard surface and then incurring further stress on the device\".<ref name=\"verge-touchdiseaseprogram\">{{cite web|title=Apple launches repair program for iPhone 6 Plus \u2018touch disease\u2019 flaw|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/11/17/13672788/apple-iphone-6-plus-touch-disease-repair-program|website=The Verge|publisher=Vox Media|accessdate=December 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Sales ==\nApple Inc. announced that, within 24 hours of availability, over 4 million pre-orders of the iPhone 6 and 6 Plus were made, exceeding the supply available.<ref name=\"MW orders 1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.macworld.com/article/2643110/apple-iphone-6-and-6-plus-pre-orders-top-4-million-in-24-hours.html|title=Apple iPhone 6 and 6 Plus pre-orders top 4 million in 24 hours|first=Serenity|last=Caldwell|work=[[Macworld]]|date=September 15, 2014|accessdate=September 16, 2014}}</ref> 13 million iPhone 6 and iPhone 6 Plus devices were sold in the first three days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2015/09/28Apple-Announces-Record-iPhone-6s-iPhone-6s-Plus-Sales/|title=Apple Announces Record iPhone 6s & iPhone 6s Plus Sales|website=Apple Newsroom|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-26}}</ref> During their lifetime, the iPhone 6 and iPhone 6 Plus sold a total of more than 220 million, making them one of the [[List of best-selling mobile phones|best selling mobile phones]] of all time.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.androidauthority.com/5-best-selling-smartphones-888017/|title=5 best selling smartphones of all time|date=2018-08-05|website=Android Authority|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref>\n== Timeline of models ==\n{{Timeline of iPhone models}}\n\n== See also ==\n*[[List of iOS devices]]\n*[[History of iPhone]]\n*[[Comparison of smartphones]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Commons category|IPhone 6|lcfirst=yes}}\n{{S-start}}\n{{Succession box\n| title = iPhone 6/Plus\n| before = [[iPhone 5C]] / [[iPhone 5S]]\n| after = {{nowrap|[[iPhone 6S]]/Plus}}\n| years = 8th generation\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{iOS}}\n{{Apple hardware since 1998}}\n{{Apple Inc. hardware}}\n{{Apple}}\n\n[[Category:Products introduced in 2014]]\n[[Category:Products and services discontinued in 2019]]\n[[Category:IPhone|*]]\n[[Category:Mechanical failure]]\n[[Category:Mobile phones introduced in 2014]]\n[[Category:IOS]]\n[[Category:Discontinued smartphones]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Smartphone developed by Apple Inc. and eighth generation iPhone}}\n{{lowercase}}\n{{Good article}}\n{{Use American English|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox mobile phone\n| name         = iPhone 6<br />iPhone 6 Plus\n| codename     = [[List of Apple codenames#N|N61]]\n| logo         = IPhone 6 Logo.svg\n| logo_size    = 160px\n| logosize     =\n| image        = IPhone6 silver frontface.png\n| image_size   = 150px\n| alt          = \n| caption      