{"title_page": "Street Fight Radio", "text_new": "{{Infobox podcast\n| title        = Street Fight Radio\n| image        = Street Fight Radio.jpg\n| caption      = The logo used by ''Street Fight Radio'' is an [[anvil]] with \"SF\" as an acronym. \n| host         = Brett Payne and Bryan Quinby\n| genre        = Politics, humor\n| language = English\n| updates      = Thrice-weekly\n| length       = 60\u2013180 minutes\n| num_episodes = \n| production   = \n| began        = {{Start date and age|df=yes|June 23, 2011}}\n| website      = {{URL|http://www.streetfightradio.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''''Street Fight Radio''''', or '''''Street Fight''''' is an American politics and humor [[radio show]] and [[podcast]] founded in June 2011 and hosted by Brett Payne and Bryan Quinby. The show produces three distinct episodes per week.{{sfn|Street Fight Radio|n.d.}} In addition to producing the radio show and podcasts, through its Patreon, ''Street Fight Radio'' also publishes a monthly [[zine]] and additional video content.{{sfn|Patreon|n.d.}}\n\nAlong with other podcasts such as ''[[Chapo Trap House|Chapo Trap House,]]'' and publications like ''[[The Baffler]]'' and ''[[Current Affairs (magazine)|Current Affairs]],'' ''Street Fight Radio'' has been cited as an example of the \"Dirtbag Left,\" a group of [[left-wing politics|left-wing]] media figures described as mixing humor with \"a take-no-prisoners style of American socialism.\"{{sfn|Heer|2017|loc=para. 8}}{{sfn|LeJacq|2019|loc=para. 15}}{{sfn|Smith IV|2017|loc=para. 18}}\n\n==Content==\n''Street Fight'' bills itself as an \"[[anarchism|anarcho]]-comedy\"{{sfn|Kennedy|2019|loc= para. 2}} radio show, where the hosts and fans of the show have sympathies to [[left-wing politics]]. Common topics and discussions on the show include [[Modern flat Earth societies|the shape of the earth]], [[labor union]]s, the merits of [[Barefoot#Laws|footwear]], getting your hair cut at the [[United States Postal Service|post office]], [[socialism]], failures of [[capitalism]] and the [[gig economy]], [[Nu metal]], and anarchism.{{sfn|Smith IV|2017|loc=para. 18}}{{sfn|Gomez|2019|loc=para. 8}}\n\nCurrently, ''Street Fight Radio'' produces three episodes per week. The first is a live [[call-in]] show broadcast Sundays weekly on the [[community radio]] station [[WCRM-LP|WCRS]] in [[Columbus, Ohio]].{{sfn|WCRS|n.d.}} A second episode with just the hosts (termed \"the basement show\") is released as a free podcast on Wednesdays.{{sfn|Street Fight Radio|n.d.}} A final weekly \"bonus\" episode is released only to [[Patreon]] subscribers of $1 or more.{{sfn|Patreon|n.d.}}\n\nThe format of the call-in shows (which can stretch to over three hours each week{{sfn|Denis|2019|loc=para. 5}}) is the first portion of the show features Brett and Brian riffing on topics such as drugs, current events, news articles, or their families, with the remainder of the show answering calls from fans. Fans typically call in with anecdotes from their jobs, political organizing that the caller may be participating in, or just call in to talk about anything that's on the top of their mind. The second show each week, the \"basement show\", is a sixty to ninety minute show that is similar in format to the first part of the call in shows. The third show features either Brett or Bryan interviewing a guest of their choice. Past guests on the Interview Show have included the hosts of sister podcasts like ''Chapo Trap House'', ''Struggle Session'', and ''Delete Your Account'', writers for various websites or other publications, and users associated with [[weird Twitter]].\n\n==History==\nBoth hosts are natives of Columbus, Ohio and its immediate suburbs.{{sfn|Day|2019|loc=para. 2}}\nQuinby began making podcasts with a friend in 2007.{{sfn|Quinby|2019|p=28}} That same year, Payne had also co-hosted a different short-lived podcast ''Relatively Unknown.''{{sfn|Payne|2019|p=12}} In 2008, Payne & Quinby met while making a new podcast, ''Murder Rebel Radio,'' which they created with several mutual friends.{{sfn|Payne|2019|p=14}} The two bonded over their shared experiences of financial hardship.{{sfn|Day|2019|loc=para. 30}}\n\nDuring this period, both hosts gained experience in stand-up comedy by attending open mics, but they quickly became frustrated with the open mic scene, and decided to focus on podcasts.{{sfn|Denis|2019|loc=para. 7}}{{sfn|Payne|2019|p=17}} In 2010, they began producing shows under the name \"Brett & Bryan Recording Themselves\" as part of the ''Murder Rebel Radio'' stream.{{sfn|Payne|2019|p=15}}{{sfn|Quinby|2019|p=32}} Deciding to go \"all in,\" Quinby & Payne left ''Murder Rebel Radio'' to focus on their new solo work shortly thereafter.{{sfn|Quinby|2019|p=33}}\n\n''Street Fight Radio'' began in June 2011.{{sfn|Gomez|2019|loc=para. 6}} Previously identifying as apolitical, the hosts underwent a radicalization process during 2012.{{sfn|Thompson|2016|loc=para. 5}} Through their discussions with each other, they gradually became to identify as anarchists.{{sfn|Day|2019|loc=para. 32}} In addition to recording the weekly podcast, they began to do live shows.{{sfn|Quinby|2019|p=34}} ''Street Fight''{{'s}} [[Patreon]] was launched on October 13, 2014, but the show remained free.{{sfn|Graphtreon|n.d.}}\n\nA February 2016 episode of ''Street Fight'' served as the launching point for ''Chapo Trap House,'' when the latter show's future hosts met while reviewing the film ''[[13 Hours: The Secret Soldiers of Benghazi]]''.{{sfn|Tolentino|2016|loc=para. 2}}{{sfn|Street Fight Radio|2016}} Chapo's immediate success provided ''Street Fight'' with a boost as well.{{sfn|Payne|2019|p=22}} This allowed the hosts to turn the show in to their full-time jobs in 2016{{sfn|Ebright|2018|loc=para. 2}} The show went from 1100 to 5000 weekly listeners by 2017.{{sfn|Welsh|2017|loc=para. 1}} In order to differentiate themselves from the many left-wing podcasts appearing, ''Street Fight'' adopted a narrow focus on real-life & working-class experiences.{{sfn|Ebright|2018|loc=para. 4}}{{sfn|Smith IV|2017|loc=para. 18}}{{sfn|Thompson|2016|loc=para. 9-10}}{{sfn|Quinby|2019|p=37}} Seeing Chapo's success with the Patreon bonus show format lead to ''Street Fight'' adopting the paywalled third show for $1.{{sfn|Quinby|2019|p=36}}\n\n==Collaborations==\nTheir close connection with ''Chapo Trap House'' has meant the two podcasts have frequently worked together live. The first such \"''Chapo Trap House'' X ''Street Fight Radio'' Live Show\" was recorded in Philadelphia during the [[2016 Democratic National Convention]].{{sfn|Ebright|2018|loc=para. 7}} The two podcasts put on multiple joint shows in the spring of 2017, including performances in [[Washington, D.C.]] coinciding with the [[DisruptJ20]] protests.{{sfn|Street Fight Radio|2017a}}{{sfn|Street Fight Radio|2017b}} They also appeared together during Chapo's tour in support of their book release in October 2018.{{sfn|Ebright|2018|loc=para. 1}}\n\nThe podcast's 2017 \"Flat Earth Tour\" was arranged in part with support from members of the [[Democratic Socialists of America]] (DSA), Louisville Socialists, and [[Socialist Alternative (United States)|Socialist Alternative]] (SA).{{sfn|Street Fight Radio|2017c}} A live show during the podcast's 2018 \"Middlewest Tour\" was held alongside an [[Incarcerated Workers Organizing Committee]] fundraising cook-off.{{sfn|Street Fight Radio|2018a}} In December of the same year, ''Street Fight'' held a fundraiser show in conjunction with the Pittsburgh DSA Socialist Feminist Committee in support of the [[abortion fund]] Western PA Fund For Choice.{{sfn|Street Fight Radio|2018b}}\n\nOne of the hosts' stated goals of the podcast has been to bring together like-minded people in parts of America who are outside of its major urban centers, and to help create a support system and audience for other leftist content producers in those areas.{{sfn|LeJacq|2019|loc=para. 20}} In July 2019, under the collective name of \"The Hellfire Congregation of Radical Egalitarianism,\" ''Street Fight'' went on a tour of the [[Southern United States]] with the podcasts District Sentinel Radio & Trillbilly Workers Party, which included a visit to the DSA 2019 conference in Atlanta.{{sfn|Street Fight Radio|2019d}}\n\n''Street Fight'' has been cited as an inspiration for videographer Nick Hayes to transition from work on commercials, ultimately leading him to create the anti-capitalist video service [[Means.tv|Means TV]].{{sfn|Hayes|2019|p=40}} Hayes worked with the show to record live performances in 2017 & 2019.{{sfn|Beer|2019|loc=para. 1}}{{sfn|Hayes|2019|p=41}} Once Means TV launched, Quinby and Payne provided some of the launch video content for the fledgling service in early 2019.{{sfn|Beer|2019|loc=para. 7}}\n\n==Reception==\nA 2016 feature in [[The A.V. Club]], on the episode \"Patriotic Motorcycle Heroes,\" described ''Street Fight'' as \"frank and consistently hilarious.\"{{sfn|Griffith|2016}} In February 2018, XFDR named ''Street Fight'' its podcast of the week, praising it as \"a different kind of leftist podcast\" in a market that was already \"oversaturated.\"{{sfn|Moon|2018|loc=para. 1}}\n\nAs of August 2019, the show's Patreon was the 220th most popular overall, and 9th in its category (Adult Video).{{sfn|Graphtreon|n.d.}} For the same month, ''Street Fight'' was ranked 416th in its category (News) by Apple Podcasts.{{sfn|Chartable|n.d.}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{Cite web|ref=harv| last = Beer| first = Jeff| title = This new streaming service wants to be the anti-capitalist Netflix| work = [[Fast Company]]| accessdate = 2019-08-10| date = 2019-04-02| url = https://www.fastcompany.com/90327425/this-new-streaming-service-wants-to-be-the-anti-capitalist-netflix}}\n*{{Cite web|ref={{harvid|Chartable|n.d.}}|author=Chartable| title = Street Fight Radio - Rankings on Apple Podcasts : United States of America :| work = Chartable| accessdate = 2019-08-13